{"title_page": "MS Achille Lauro", "text_new": "{{short description|Cruise ship launched in 1946}}\n{{Redirect|Willem Ruys|the Dutch game show host|Willem Ruis}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2009}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Achille39.jpg\n|Ship caption= ''Achille Lauro''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=*''Willem Ruys'' (1947\u20131965)\n*''Achille Lauro'' (1965\u20131994)\n|Ship owner=*1947\u20131965: N. V. Koninklijke Rotterdamsche Lloyd, [[Vlissingen]], [[Netherlands]]\n*1965\u20131987: Achille Lauro FU G. & C.\n*1987\u20131994: Star Lauro S.P.A.<ref name=\"SMHD\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marhisdata.nl/main.php?to_page=schip&id=7323 |title=Name ship: Willem Ruys |publisher=Stichting Maritiem-Historische Databank |date= |accessdate=March 12, 2016}}</ref>\n|Ship operator=* Royal Rotterdam Lloyd (1947\u20131964)\n*[[Flotta Lauro Lines]] (1965\u20131986)\n*[[StarLauro]] (1987\u20131994)\n|Ship registry=*1947\u20131965: [[Rotterdam]], {{flag|Netherlands}}\n*1965\u20131994: [[Naples]], {{flag|Italy|civil}}\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered= 7 May 1938\n|Ship builder= Koninklijke Maatschappij \"De Schelde\" Shipbuilding\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=214\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down= 25 January 1939<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship launched= 1 July 1946<ref name=\"SMHD\"/> (Delayed due to WWII)\n|Ship completed= 21 November 1947<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship christened= by HM [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Queen Wilhelmina]] <ref name=\"Ward\">{{cite book |title=Berlitz Complete Guide to Cruising & Cruise Ships |url=https://archive.org/details/berlitzcompleteg0000ward |url-access=registration |last=Ward |first=Douglas |year=1995 |publisher=Berlitz |location=Oxford |isbn=978-2-8315-1327-0}}</ref>\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage= 2 December 1947<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service= 30 November 1994\n|Ship identification=*[[Call sign]]: PIQF \u2192 IBHE<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n*{{IMO number|5390008}}\n|Ship fate= Sank on 2 December 1994 off the coast of Somalia due to fire on board.\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage=*21,119 GRT as built\n*23,629 GRT after refurbishment\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length= {{convert|642|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Ward\"/>\n|Ship beam= {{convert|82|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Ward\"/>\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught= \n|Ship draft={{convert|29.3|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Ward\"/>\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks= 9 <ref name=\"Ward\"/> (6 passenger accessible)<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship power=*2 \u00d7 [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4|Sulzer/ Winterthur]] + 6 \u00d7 [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4|Sulzer/de Schelde]]\n*{{convert|32000|BHP|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"SMHD\"/> \n|Ship propulsion=2 propellers<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship speed={{convert|22.0|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>   \n|Ship capacity=*869 passengers (as built)<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n*1,372 passengers<ref name=\"Ward\"/> \n|Ship crew= 300 <ref name=\"Ward\"/>\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n{{Coord|2|N|47|E|display=title}}\n\n'''MS ''Achille Lauro''''' was a [[cruise ship]] based in Naples, Italy. Built between 1939 and 1947 as '''MS ''Willem Ruys''''', a [[passenger liner]] for the Rotterdamsche Lloyd, she was [[Achille Lauro hijacking|hijacked]] by members of the [[Palestine Liberation Front]] in 1985.\n\nIn other incidents, she also suffered two serious collisions (in 1953 with the {{MS|Oranje}} and in 1975 with the cargo ship ''Youseff'') and four onboard fires or explosions (in 1965, 1972, 1981, and 1994). In the last of these, in 1994, the ship caught fire and sank in the [[Indian Ocean]] off [[Somalia]].\n\n==Concept and construction==\nOrdered in 1938 to replace the aging ships on the [[Dutch East Indies]] route, her [[keel]] was laid in 1939 at De Schelde shipyard in [[Vlissingen]], [[Netherlands]], for Rotterdamsche Lloyd (now [[Nedlloyd]]). Interrupted by [[World War II]] and two bombing raids, the ship was finally launched in July 1946, as ''Willem Ruys''. The ship was named after the grandson of the founder of the Rotterdamsche Lloyd who was taken hostage and shot during the war.\n\n''Willem Ruys'' was completed in late 1947. At that time, the Rotterdamsche Lloyd had been granted a royal prefix in honour of its services during the war. ''Willem Ruys'' was {{convert|192|m|ft|0}} in length, {{convert|25|m|ft|0}} in beam, had a draught of {{convert|8.9|m|ft|1}}, and measured 21,119 [[tonnage|gross register ton]]s. Eight [[Sulzer (manufacturer)|Sulzer]] engines drove two [[propeller]]s. She could accommodate 900 passengers. She featured a superstructure very different from other liners of that era; ''Willem Ruys'' pioneered low-slung aluminium lifeboats, within the upper-works' flanks. The next ship to adopt this unique arrangement was the {{SS|Canberra}} in 1961. Today, all cruise ships follow this layout, with fibreglass-reinforced plastic (FRP) used for lifeboat hulls.\n\n==Service history==\n\n===As the ''Willem Ruys''===\n\n====On the East Indies route====\nAs ''Willem Ruys'', the ship began her maiden voyage on 5 December 1947. Together with her main competitor and running mate, the [[MS Oranje|MS ''Oranje'']] of the [[Netherland Line]], she became a popular fixture on the [[Dutch East Indies]] route. However, when the East Indies gained independence from The Netherlands in 1949, passengers' numbers decreased.\n\nThe former [[Prime Minister of Singapore]], [[Lee Kuan Yew]], had travelled aboard ''Willem Ruys'' as a fresh graduate upon completing his studies in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite magazine|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2056737-5,00.html|title=The Singapore Story|magazine=Time|date= 3 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Collision with ''Oranje''====\nOn 6 January 1953, ''Willem Ruys'' collided in the Red Sea with running mate {{MS|Oranje}}, which was heading in the opposite direction. At that time, it was common for passenger ships to pass each other at close range to entertain their passengers. During the (later heavily criticized) abrupt and fast approach of ''Oranje'', ''Willem Ruys'' made an unexpected swing to the left, resulting in a collision. ''Oranje'' badly damaged her bow. Due to the possibility that she would be impounded for safety reasons, she was unable to call at Colombo as scheduled, and went directly to Jakarta. ''Willem Ruys'' suffered less damage. There was no loss of life involved. Later, it was determined that miscommunication on both ships had caused the collision.\n\n====''Journey to Java''====\nDuring 1957, the English diplomat, author and diarist [[Harold Nicolson]] and his wife, the author and poet [[Vita Sackville-West]], toured the [[Far East]] for two months aboard ''Willem Ruys''. The voyage is documented in ''Journey to Java'', his published journal of the trip,<ref name=\"Journey To Java\">{{cite book |title= Journey to Java |last= Nicolson|first= Harold|year= 1957|publisher= Constable|location= [[London]]}}</ref> which provides a detailed account of [[first class travel]] on the vessel in the 1950s.\n\n====Later years====\nAfter repairs, Royal Rotterdam Lloyd decided to release ''Willem Ruys'' on the North Atlantic run. First, she was placed on the [[New York (state)|New York]] service, and later [[Canada]] was included.\n\nIn 1958, the Royal Rotterdamsche Lloyd and the [[Netherland Line]] signed a co-operative agreement to create a round-the-world passenger service. The joint fleet would sail under the banner of \"The Royal Dutch Mail Ships\". Together with ''Oranje'' and ''[[TSMS Lakonia|Johan van Oldenbarneveldt]]'', ''Willem Ruys'' underwent an extensive refit to prepare her for this new service. She made two charter trips to [[Montreal]] for the Europa-Canada service. Then, from 20 September 1958, until 25 February 1959, she underwent a major facelift at the [[Wilton-Fijenoord]] shipyard in [[Amsterdam]], turning her from a passenger liner into a cruise ship. Her original four class distinctions became First and Tourist Class. A hundred new cabins were installed and [[air-conditioning]] was extended throughout all accommodations. The Javanese crew members were replaced by Europeans, who required upgraded crew accommodation. Externally, she was fitted with a new glazing in Tourist Class Wintergarden, her forward funnel was heightened and [[Stabilizer (ship)|stabilizers]] were fitted. ''Willem Ruys'' was now able to accommodate 275 first class and 770 tourist class passengers, although there were many interchangeable cabins which had additional berths fitted, which could increase the maximum passenger number to 1167. Her new specifications would see her tonnage increase from 21,119 to 23,114 [[tonnage|gross register ton]].\n\nOn 7 March 1959, ''Willem Ruys'' went off on her new world service to [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. She departed from [[Rotterdam]], sailing via [[Southampton]], the [[Mediterranean]], the [[Suez Canal]], [[Fremantle]], [[Melbourne]], [[Sydney]], [[New Zealand]], returning via the [[Panama Canal]]. The Royal Dutch Mail Ships (''Willem Ruys'', ''Johan van Oldenbarnevelt'' and ''Oranje'') became a popular alternative to the British liners.\n\nAt the end of 1964, due to a strong drop in passenger numbers, ''Willem Ruys'' was laid up in [[Rotterdam]] and put up for sale.\n\n===As ''Achille Lauro''===\nIn 1965, she was sold to the [[Flotta Lauro Line]], or [[Star Lauro]], (now [[MSC Cruises]]) and renamed ''Achille Lauro'' after [[Achille Lauro|the company's owner]]. She was extensively rebuilt and modernized after an August 1965 onboard explosion, and entered service in 1966 carrying passengers to [[Sydney]], Australia. The ship played a role in evacuating the families of British servicemen caught up in unrest in [[Aden]], and made one of the last northbound transits through the [[Suez Canal]] before its closure during the [[Six-Day War]].\n\n''Achille Lauro'' was converted to a cruise ship in early 1972, during which time she suffered a disastrous fire. A 1975 collision with the cargo ship ''Youseff'' resulted in the sinking of the latter, and another onboard fire in 1981 took her out of service for a time. She was laid up in [[Tenerife]] when Lauro Lines went bankrupt in 1982. The [[Chandris Line]] took possession of her under a charter arrangement in 1985, shortly before the hijacking.\n\n====1985 hijacking====\n{{main|Achille Lauro hijacking}}\nOn 7 October 1985, four members of the [[Palestine Liberation Front]] (PLF) took control of the liner off [[Egypt]] as she was sailing from [[Alexandria]] to [[Port Said]]. Holding the passengers and crew hostage, they directed the vessel to sail to [[Tartus]], [[Syria]], and demanded the release of 50 [[Palestinians]] then in Israeli prisons. After being refused permission to dock at Tartus, the hijackers killed disabled Jewish-American passenger [[Leon Klinghoffer]] and then threw his body overboard.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |last=Berman |first=Daphna |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/pages/ShArt.jhtml?itemNo=981987&contrassID=2&subContrassID=16 |title=Klinghoffer daughters recall personal tragedy at commemoration of terror victims outside Israel |work=Haaretz |date=9 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe ship then headed back towards Port Said, and after two days of negotiations, the hijackers agreed to abandon the liner in exchange for safe conduct and were flown towards [[Tunisia]] aboard an Egyptian commercial airliner. This plane, however, was intercepted by US fighter aircraft and directed to land in [[Sicily]], where the hijackers were to be tried for murder, but could not be extradited. The four terrorists were sentenced to prison terms by the Italian courts, while the operation's mastermind, who had not taken part in the actual hijacking, was given passage to Yugoslavia and escaped.\n\n====Later years, fire, and sinking====\nThe ship continued in service; she was reflagged in 1987 when the Lauro Line was taken over by the [[Mediterranean Shipping Company]] to become \"StarLauro\". On 30 November 1994, she caught fire off the coast of Somalia while ''en route'' to [[South Africa]], with 979 passengers and crew on board. At that time, Italian officials said the fire had been caused by a discarded cigarette, but it actually began in the engine room after one of the engines exploded. Because of a lack of supervision, the fire burned out of control before its discovery.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news |last=Cowell |first=Alan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/02/world/achille-lauro-smolders-after-1000-are-rescued.html|title=Achille Lauro Smolders After 1,000 Are Rescued|work=[[The New York Times]]|date= 2 December 1994 |access-date=30 September 2019 }}</ref> The crew tried to battle the fire for several hours but were unsuccessful. The vessel was abandoned, and during transfer to rescue ships, including the USS Halyburton FFG-40, two died and eight were wounded.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite news |title=BBC ON THIS DAY 30 November 1994: Blazing liner abandoned off east Africa |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2008 |access-date=30 September 2019 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/30/newsid_2525000/2525643.stm }}</ref> The Achille Lauro sank two days later on 2 December 1994.<ref>{{cite web|author=Reuben Goossens |url=http://www.ssmaritime.com/achillelauro.htm |title=Achille Lauro |publisher=ssMaritime.com ||access-date=30 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Lauro Lines s.r.l. v. Chasser et al.]]'', a [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] case dealing with the ''Achille Lauro'' hijacking\n*''[[The Hijacking of the Achille Lauro]]'', 1989 film\n*''[[Voyage of Terror: The Achille Lauro Affair]]'', 1990 film\n*''[[The Death of Klinghoffer]]'', 1991 opera\n*[[List of hostage crises]]\n*[[1979 Nahariya attack]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bohn, Michael K. (2004). [https://books.google.com/books?id=754tx7I-98cC&printsec=frontcover ''The Achille Lauro Hijacking: Lessons in the Politics and Prejudice of Terrorism'']. Potomac Books, Inc. {{ISBN|978-1-574-88779-2}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100729111538/http://www.cnn.com/resources/video.almanac/1985/index2.html CNN Interactive: Video Almanac of 1985]\n\n{{MSC Ships}}\n{{1985 shipwrecks}}\n{{1994 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Achille Lauro}}\n[[Category:MS Achille Lauro|*]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1994]]\n[[Category:Ocean liners]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of MSC Cruises]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of Africa]]\n[[Category:1946 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents involving cruise ships]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cruise ship launched in 1946}}\n{{Redirect|Willem Ruys|the Dutch game show host|Willem Ruis}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2009}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Achille39.jpg\n|Ship caption= ''Achille Lauro''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=*''Willem Ruys'' (1947\u20131965)\n*''Achille Lauro'' (1965\u20131994)\n|Ship owner=*1947\u20131965: N. V. Koninklijke Rotterdamsche Lloyd, [[Vlissingen]], [[Netherlands]]\n*1965\u20131987: Achille Lauro FU G. & C.\n*1987\u20131994: Star Lauro S.P.A.<ref name=\"SMHD\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marhisdata.nl/main.php?to_page=schip&id=7323 |title=Name ship: Willem Ruys |publisher=Stichting Maritiem-Historische Databank |date= |accessdate=March 12, 2016}}</ref>\n|Ship operator=* Royal Rotterdam Lloyd (1947\u20131964)\n*[[Flotta Lauro Lines]] (1965\u20131986)\n*[[StarLauro]] (1987\u20131994)\n|Ship registry=*1947\u20131965: [[Rotterdam]], {{flag|Netherlands}}\n*1965\u20131994: [[Naples]], {{flag|Italy|civil}}\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered= 7 May 1938\n|Ship builder= Koninklijke Maatschappij \"De Schelde\" Shipbuilding\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=214\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down= 25 January 1939<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship launched= 1 July 1946<ref name=\"SMHD\"/> (Delayed due to WWII)\n|Ship completed= 21 November 1947<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship christened= by HM [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Queen Wilhelmina]] <ref name=\"Ward\">{{cite book |title=Berlitz Complete Guide to Cruising & Cruise Ships |url=https://archive.org/details/berlitzcompleteg0000ward |url-access=registration |last=Ward |first=Douglas |year=1995 |publisher=Berlitz |location=Oxford |isbn=978-2-8315-1327-0}}</ref>\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage= 2 December 1947<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service= 30 November 1994\n|Ship identification=*[[Call sign]]: PIQF \u2192 IBHE<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n*{{IMO number|5390008}}\n|Ship fate= Sank on 2 December 1994 off the coast of Somalia due to fire on board.\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage=*21,119 GRT as built\n*23,629 GRT after refurbishment\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length= {{convert|642|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Ward\"/>\n|Ship beam= {{convert|82|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Ward\"/>\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught= \n|Ship draft={{convert|29.3|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Ward\"/>\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks= 9 <ref name=\"Ward\"/> (6 passenger accessible)<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship power=*2 \u00d7 [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4|Sulzer/ Winterthur]] + 6 \u00d7 [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4|Sulzer/de Schelde]]\n*{{convert|32000|BHP|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"SMHD\"/> \n|Ship propulsion=2 propellers<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n|Ship speed={{convert|22.0|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>   \n|Ship capacity=*869 passengers (as built)<ref name=\"SMHD\"/>\n*1,372 passengers<ref name=\"Ward\"/> \n|Ship crew= 300 <ref name=\"Ward\"/>\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n{{Coord|2|N|47|E|display=title}}\n\n'''MS ''Achille Lauro''''' was a [[cruise ship]] based in Naples, Italy. Built between 1939 and 1947 as '''MS ''Willem Ruys''''', a [[passenger liner]] for the Rotterdamsche Lloyd, she was [[Achille Lauro hijacking|hijacked]] by members of the [[Palestine Liberation Front]] in 1985.\n\nIn other incidents, she also suffered two serious collisions (in 1953 with the {{MS|Oranje}} and in 1975 with the cargo ship ''Youseff'') and four onboard fires or explosions (in 1965, 1972, 1981, and 1994). In the last of these, in 1994, the ship caught fire and sank in the [[Indian Ocean]] off [[Somalia]].\n\n==Concept and construction==\nOrdered in 1938 to replace the aging ships on the [[Dutch East Indies]] route, her [[keel]] was laid in 1939 at De Schelde shipyard in [[Vlissingen]], [[Netherlands]], for Rotterdamsche Lloyd (now [[Nedlloyd]]). Interrupted by [[World War II]] and two bombing raids, the ship was finally launched in July 1946, as ''Willem Ruys''. The ship was named after the grandson of the founder of the Rotterdamsche Lloyd who was taken hostage and shot during the war.\n\n''Willem Ruys'' was completed in late 1947. At that time, the Rotterdamsche Lloyd had been granted a royal prefix in honour of its services during the war. ''Willem Ruys'' was {{convert|192|m|ft|0}} in length, {{convert|25|m|ft|0}} in beam, had a draught of {{convert|8.9|m|ft|1}}, and measured 21,119 [[tonnage|gross register ton]]s. Eight [[Sulzer (manufacturer)|Sulzer]] engines drove two [[propeller]]s. She could accommodate 900 passengers. She featured a superstructure very different from other liners of that era; ''Willem Ruys'' pioneered low-slung aluminium lifeboats, within the upper-works' flanks. The next ship to adopt this unique arrangement was the {{SS|Canberra}} in 1961. Today, all cruise ships follow this layout, with fibreglass-reinforced plastic (FRP) used for lifeboat hulls.\n\n==Service history==\n\n===As the ''Willem Ruys''===\n\n====On the East Indies route====\nAs ''Willem Ruys'', the ship began her maiden voyage on 5 December 1947. Together with her main competitor and running mate, the [[MS Oranje|MS ''Oranje'']] of the [[Netherland Line]], she became a popular fixture on the [[Dutch East Indies]] route. However, when the East Indies gained independence from The Netherlands in 1949, passengers' numbers decreased.\n\nThe former [[Prime Minister of Singapore]], [[Lee Kuan Yew]], had travelled aboard ''Willem Ruys'' as a fresh graduate upon completing his studies in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite magazine|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2056737-5,00.html|title=The Singapore Story|magazine=Time|date= 3 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Collision with ''Oranje''====\nOn 6 January 1953, ''Willem Ruys'' collided in the Red Sea with running mate {{MS|Oranje}}, which was heading in the opposite direction. At that time, it was common for passenger ships to pass each other at close range to entertain their passengers. During the (later heavily criticized) abrupt and fast approach of ''Oranje'', ''Willem Ruys'' made an unexpected swing to the left, resulting in a collision. ''Oranje'' badly damaged her bow. Due to the possibility that she would be impounded for safety reasons, she was unable to call at Colombo as scheduled, and went directly to Jakarta. ''Willem Ruys'' suffered less damage. There was no loss of life involved. Later, it was determined that miscommunication on both ships had caused the collision.\n\n====Journey to Java====\nDuring 1957, the English diplomat, author and diarist [[Harold Nicolson]] and his wife, the author and poet [[Vita Sackville-West]], toured the [[Far East]] for two months aboard ''Willem Ruys''. The voyage is documented in ''Journey to Java'', his published journal of the trip,<ref name=\"Journey To Java\">{{cite book |title= Journey to Java |last= Nicolson|first= Harold|year= 1957|publisher= Constable|location= [[London]]}}</ref> which provides a detailed account of [[first class travel]] on the vessel in the 1950s.\n\n====Later years====\nAfter repairs, Royal Rotterdam Lloyd decided to release ''Willem Ruys'' on the North Atlantic run. First, she was placed on the [[New York (state)|New York]] service, and later [[Canada]] was included.\n\nIn 1958, the Royal Rotterdamsche Lloyd and the [[Netherland Line]] signed a co-operative agreement to create a round-the-world passenger service. The joint fleet would sail under the banner of \"The Royal Dutch Mail Ships\". Together with ''Oranje'' and ''[[TSMS Lakonia|Johan van Oldenbarneveldt]]'', ''Willem Ruys'' underwent an extensive refit to prepare her for this new service. She made two charter trips to [[Montreal]] for the Europa-Canada service. Then, from 20 September 1958, until 25 February 1959, she underwent a major facelift at the [[Wilton-Fijenoord]] shipyard in [[Amsterdam]], turning her from a passenger liner into a cruise ship. Her original four class distinctions became First and Tourist Class. A hundred new cabins were installed and [[air-conditioning]] was extended throughout all accommodations. The Javanese crew members were replaced by Europeans, who required upgraded crew accommodation. Externally, she was fitted with a new glazing in Tourist Class Wintergarden, her forward funnel was heightened and [[Stabilizer (ship)|stabilizers]] were fitted. ''Willem Ruys'' was now able to accommodate 275 first class and 770 tourist class passengers, although there were many interchangeable cabins which had additional berths fitted, which could increase the maximum passenger number to 1167. Her new specifications would see her tonnage increase from 21,119 to 23,114 [[tonnage|gross register ton]].\n\nOn 7 March 1959, ''Willem Ruys'' went off on her new world service to [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. She departed from [[Rotterdam]], sailing via [[Southampton]], the [[Mediterranean]], the [[Suez Canal]], [[Fremantle]], [[Melbourne]], [[Sydney]], [[New Zealand]], returning via the [[Panama Canal]]. The Royal Dutch Mail Ships (''Willem Ruys'', ''Johan van Oldenbarnevelt'' and ''Oranje'') became a popular alternative to the British liners.\n\nAt the end of 1964, due to a strong drop in passenger numbers, ''Willem Ruys'' was laid up in [[Rotterdam]] and put up for sale.\n\n===As ''Achille Lauro''===\nIn 1965, she was sold to the [[Flotta Lauro Line]], or [[Star Lauro]], (now [[MSC Cruises]]) and renamed ''Achille Lauro'' after [[Achille Lauro|the company's owner]]. She was extensively rebuilt and modernized after an August 1965 onboard explosion, and entered service in 1966 carrying passengers to [[Sydney]], Australia. The ship played a role in evacuating the families of British servicemen caught up in unrest in [[Aden]], and made one of the last northbound transits through the [[Suez Canal]] before its closure during the [[Six-Day War]].\n\n''Achille Lauro'' was converted to a cruise ship in early 1972, during which time she suffered a disastrous fire. A 1975 collision with the cargo ship ''Youseff'' resulted in the sinking of the latter, and another onboard fire in 1981 took her out of service for a time. She was laid up in [[Tenerife]] when Lauro Lines went bankrupt in 1982. The [[Chandris Line]] took possession of her under a charter arrangement in 1985, shortly before the hijacking.\n\n====1985 hijacking====\n{{main|Achille Lauro hijacking}}\nOn 7 October 1985, four members of the [[Palestine Liberation Front]] (PLF) took control of the liner off [[Egypt]] as she was sailing from [[Alexandria]] to [[Port Said]]. Holding the passengers and crew hostage, they directed the vessel to sail to [[Tartus]], [[Syria]], and demanded the release of 50 [[Palestinians]] then in Israeli prisons. After being refused permission to dock at Tartus, the hijackers killed disabled Jewish-American passenger [[Leon Klinghoffer]] and then threw his body overboard.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |last=Berman |first=Daphna |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/pages/ShArt.jhtml?itemNo=981987&contrassID=2&subContrassID=16 |title=Klinghoffer daughters recall personal tragedy at commemoration of terror victims outside Israel |work=Haaretz |date=9 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe ship then headed back towards Port Said, and after two days of negotiations, the hijackers agreed to abandon the liner in exchange for safe conduct and were flown towards [[Tunisia]] aboard an Egyptian commercial airliner. This plane, however, was intercepted by US fighter aircraft and directed to land in [[Sicily]], where the hijackers were to be tried for murder, but could not be extradited. The four terrorists were sentenced to prison terms by the Italian courts, while the operation's mastermind, who had not taken part in the actual hijacking, was given passage to Yugoslavia and escaped.\n\n====Later years, fire, and sinking====\nThe ship continued in service; she was reflagged in 1987 when the Lauro Line was taken over by the [[Mediterranean Shipping Company]] to become \"StarLauro\". On 30 November 1994, she caught fire off the coast of Somalia while ''en route'' to [[South Africa]], with 979 passengers and crew on board. At that time, Italian officials said the fire had been caused by a discarded cigarette, but it actually began in the engine room after one of the engines exploded. Because of a lack of supervision, the fire burned out of control before its discovery.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news |last=Cowell |first=Alan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/02/world/achille-lauro-smolders-after-1000-are-rescued.html|title=Achille Lauro Smolders After 1,000 Are Rescued|work=[[The New York Times]]|date= 2 December 1994 |access-date=30 September 2019 }}</ref> The crew tried to battle the fire for several hours but were unsuccessful. The vessel was abandoned, and during transfer to rescue ships, including the USS Halyburton FFG-40, two died and eight were wounded.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite news |title=BBC ON THIS DAY 30 November 1994: Blazing liner abandoned off east Africa |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2008 |access-date=30 September 2019 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/30/newsid_2525000/2525643.stm }}</ref> The Achille Lauro sank two days later on 2 December 1994.<ref>{{cite web|author=Reuben Goossens |url=http://www.ssmaritime.com/achillelauro.htm |title=Achille Lauro |publisher=ssMaritime.com ||access-date=30 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Lauro Lines s.r.l. v. Chasser et al.]]'', a [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] case dealing with the ''Achille Lauro'' hijacking\n*''[[The Hijacking of the Achille Lauro]]'', 1989 film\n*''[[Voyage of Terror: The Achille Lauro Affair]]'', 1990 film\n*''[[The Death of Klinghoffer]]'', 1991 opera\n*[[List of hostage crises]]\n*[[1979 Nahariya attack]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bohn, Michael K. (2004). [https://books.google.com/books?id=754tx7I-98cC&printsec=frontcover ''The Achille Lauro Hijacking: Lessons in the Politics and Prejudice of Terrorism'']. Potomac Books, Inc. {{ISBN|978-1-574-88779-2}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100729111538/http://www.cnn.com/resources/video.almanac/1985/index2.html CNN Interactive: Video Almanac of 1985]\n\n{{MSC Ships}}\n{{1985 shipwrecks}}\n{{1994 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Achille Lauro}}\n[[Category:MS Achille Lauro|*]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1994]]\n[[Category:Ocean liners]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of MSC Cruises]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of Africa]]\n[[Category:1946 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents involving cruise ships]]\n", "name_user": "RHodnett", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJourney to Java:Italicized name of this section, since it refers to the name of a book.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MS_Achille_Lauro"}
{"title_page": "Christian Brothers University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = Christian Brothers University\n|image_name      = Christian Brothers University seal.png\n|image_size     = 200px\n|motto           = ''Virtus et Scientia''\n|mottoeng        = Character and Knowledge\n|established     = 1871\n|type            = [[Private school|Private]]\n|religious_affiliation     = [[Catholic Church]] ([[Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools|Christian Brothers]])\n|endowment       = $34,500,000 <ref name=\"ABC 2008\" />\n|faculty         = 110\n|president       = John T. (Jack) Shannon, Jr.\n|students        = 1779<ref name=\"nces\">[http://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=christian+brothers+university&s=all&id=219833 Christian Brothers University]. National Center for Education Statistics. Accessed May 30, 2008.</ref>\n|undergrad       =1455<ref name=\"nces\"/>\n|postgrad        =324\n|address         =\n|city            =[[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]]\n|state           =[[Tennessee]]\n|country         = United States\n|coor            = {{coord|35.127376|-89.982297|type:edu|display=title,inline}}\n|campus          =[[Urban area|Urban]], 76 acres\n|colors          =Red and Gray<br/>{{color box|#CC092F}}&nbsp;{{color box|#A49791}}\n|mascot          = Bucky the Buccaneer\n|nickname        =[[Christian Brothers Buccaneers|Buccaneers & Lady Buccaneers]]\n|athletics       = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] \u2013 [[Gulf South Conference|Gulf South]]\n|affiliations    = [[IALU]], [[Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities|ACCU]], [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]], [[Council of Independent Colleges|CIC]]\n|website         = {{URL|www.cbu.edu}}\n|logo        = [[File:Christian Brothers University logo.png|250px]]\n}}\n\n'''Christian Brothers University''' is a private [[Catholic higher education|Catholic university]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].  The university is run by the [[Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools|De La Salle Brothers]], a Roman [[Catholic religious order]] founded by [[Jean-Baptiste de la Salle|St. John Baptist de la Salle]], the [[patron saint]] of teachers. It is the oldest collegiate degree-granting institution in the city.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:John baptist de la salle 1.jpg|thumb|120px|left|Saint John Baptist de la Salle]]\nChristian Brothers College was founded November 19, 1871, by members of the [[De La Salle Christian Brothers]]. The Brothers came to Memphis at the request of the people and [[clergy]] of the city, after more than a decade of efforts to persuade the Brothers to open a college there.<ref name=\"CBU History\">[http://www.cbu.edu/About/history.html \"CBU History.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050427205925/http://www.cbu.edu/About/history.html |date=2005-04-27 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref>\n\nChristian Brothers University traces its origins to the French priest and educational innovator, St. John Baptist de la Salle.<ref name=\"Lasallian Terminology.\">[http://www.cbu.edu/About/terms.html \"Lasallian Terminology.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712232456/http://www.cbu.edu/About/terms.html |date=July 12, 2007 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref> De la Salle began a system of [[Christianity|Christian]] schools in which teachers assist parents in the educational, ethical, and religious formation of their children. To continue his [[spirituality|spiritual]] and [[pedagogy|pedagogical]] vision, de la Salle founded the Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools, known today as the De La Salle Christian Brothers.\n\nChristian Brothers College officially became Christian Brothers University in June 1990.<ref name=\"CBU History\" />\n\n=== Founding ===\nAfter more than a decade of efforts to persuade the Brothers to open a college in Memphis, Christian Brothers College was founded in 1871.<ref name=\"CBU History\"/>\n\nBrother Maurelian was appointed the first president. His three terms as president totalled 31 years. During his presidency, the Brothers purchased the 612 Adams Street building, which housed the college until 1940 when the college moved to its present location at Central Avenue and [[East Parkway (Memphis, Tennessee)|East Parkway South]].\n\nFunctioning as a combined elementary school, high school (now [[Christian Brothers High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Christian Brothers High School]]), and college, Christian Brothers College granted [[high school diploma]]s as well as [[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor's]] and [[Master's degree|Master's Degrees]] until 1915, when the college division was suspended. Elementary classes were dropped in 1922, and the institution operated as only a high school for 18 years. Reopened in 1940 as a [[junior college]], the college began granting [[Associate's degree|Associate's Degrees]] in 1942.\n\n=== Oldest degree-granting institution in Memphis ===\nChristian Brothers awarded the first post-secondary degree in the city in 1875.<ref name=\"About CBU\">[http://www.cbu.edu/About/mission.html \"About CBU.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223185102/http://www.cbu.edu/About/mission.html |date=2010-12-23 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed March 2, 2008.</ref> LeMoyne College (one of the two constituent parts of present-day [[LeMoyne-Owen College]]) has a founding year of 1871, but it was an elementary and secondary school at the time. The city's largest university, The [[University of Memphis]], was not founded until 1912. Although [[Rhodes College]] was founded 1848, it did not move from [[Clarksville, Tennessee]] to Memphis until 1925.\n\n=== Lasallian tradition ===\nChristian Brothers University traces its origins to priest and educational innovator, [[Jean-Baptiste de la Salle|St. John Baptist de la Salle]].<ref name=\"Lasallian Terminology.\"/> De la Salle began a system of [[Christianity|Christian]] schools in which teachers assist parents in the educational, ethical, and religious formation of their children. To continue his [[spirituality|spiritual]] and [[pedagogy|pedagogical]] vision, de la Salle founded the Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools, known today as the De La Salle Christian Brothers.\n\nThe university currently has a [[laity|lay]] interim president following the fatal car accident of former president Brother Vincent Malham in 2008.<ref>{{cite web| date=May 3, 2008\n|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/may/03/cbu-president-killed-car-wreck-louisiana|title =CBU president Malham killed in car wreck in Louisiana: Had been named school head in 2005| publisher ='The Commercial Appeal'| last =Aarons | first =Dakarai I. | accessdate =2009-02-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Higher education ===\nIn 1953, the decision was made to expand the community college into a four-year institution to better serve the needs of the community. The four-year curriculum began with degrees in [[Administration (business)|Business Administration]] and [[Electrical engineering|Electrical Engineering]], with the first graduates in recent times receiving their degrees in 1955.\n\nThe curriculum was soon expanded to meet the needs for new programs in the fields of [[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical Engineering]] and [[Chemistry]]. The following degree programs were later added: [[Biology]], [[Civil Engineering]], [[Mathematics]], [[English studies|English]], [[Physics]], [[Chemical engineering|Chemical Engineering]], [[History]], [[Psychology]], [[Natural science|Natural Science]], [[Engineering physics|Engineering Physics]], [[Computer science|Computer Science]], and Religion and Philosophy. Teacher preparation programs in secondary education were added in 1969. An accelerated evening program offering a degree in Business Administration was added in 1978 to meet the needs of the adult student, and the [[Applied psychology|Applied Psychology]] degree was added in 1999. In Fall 2007, CBU introduced its [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree.\n\nPrograms at the graduate level were reinstated in 1987 with the Master's program in Telecommunication and Information Systems. The [[Master of Business Administration]] and the [[Engineering management|Master in Engineering Management]] were added in 1989. A [[Master of Education]] was added in 1997, and the [[Master of Arts in Teaching]] and Master of Science in Educational Leadership were offered beginning in 2001. The Master of Arts in Executive Leadership was added in 2005.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nWhen another Catholic college in Memphis (the all-female [[Siena College (Memphis, Tennessee)|Siena College]]) closed,  Christian Brothers University became [[coeducation]]al in 1970. Currently, women comprise approximately 55% of the student body.<ref name=\"nces\"/> Christian Brothers College officially became Christian Brothers University in June 1990.<ref name=\"CBU History\"/>\n\n== Academics ==\n\n=== Schools ===\nThe university has four schools:\n* Gadomski School of Engineering\n* Rosa Deal School of Arts\n* School of Business\n* School of Sciences\n\n=== Study abroad ===\nAs a member of the Lasallian Consortium,<ref>[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/SemestersAbroad/index.htm \"Semesters Abroad\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223012257/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/SemestersAbroad/index.htm |date=2009-02-23 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref> i.e. the seven Lasallian universities in the United States, CBU offers study abroad semesters in [[Australia]], [[Brazil]], [[China]], [[England]], [[France]], [[Ireland]], [[Italy]], [[Mexico]], [[South Africa]], and [[Spain]].<ref>[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/index.htm \"Travel/Study Abroad 2008\u20132009\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081124021357/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/index.htm |date=2008-11-24 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref> Additionally, CBU offers study abroad courses during spring and fall vacations. Upcoming courses include travel in England, France, Italy, Mexico, and [[Uganda]]. Medical missions to [[Haiti]] are available but have been postponed for the present.<ref>[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/Haiti/index.htm \"Haiti Medical Missions \u2013 Fall and Spring Breaks*\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223025151/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/Haiti/index.htm |date=2009-02-23 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref> Study abroad is optional for students but is required for completion of the global studies minor.<ref>[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/GlobalStudiesMinor/index.htm \"Global Studies Minor\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201160814/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/GlobalStudiesMinor/index.htm |date=2008-12-01 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nCBU has one of the most diverse student bodies in the [[Southern United States|South]].<ref>America's Best Colleges 2008. [http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/college/rankings/brief/univmas_s_campdiv_brief.php \"Campus Ethnic Diversity: University-Master's (South).\"] U.S. News & World Report. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref> 51% of students are [[White American|White-American]] (non-Hispanic), 33% are [[African American|African-American]] (non-Hispanic), 5% are [[Asian American|Asian-American]] or [[Pacific Islander American|Pacific Islander-American]], 2% are [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic-American]], and 2% are [[international student]]s. 6% of students have an unknown ethnicity.<ref>[http://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=219833 \"Christian Brothers University.\"] National Center for Education Statistics. Accessed October 18, 2007.</ref> Students hail from more than 28 states and 14 countries.<ref name=\"Closer Look\">[http://www.cbu.edu/About \"Take a Closer Look at CBU.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050425001527/http://www.cbu.edu/About/ |date=2005-04-25 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref>\n\nAlthough CBU is a [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] university, only 23% of students are Catholic. Religious observances are not required, and 32 different [[List of religions|faiths]] are represented in the student body.<ref name=\"Closer Look\" />\n\nNotably, 99% of Christian Brothers University undergraduates receive [[Student financial aid (United States)|financial aid]], broken down as institutional grants (98%), state/local grants (68%), federal grants (29%), and student loans (58%).<ref name=\"nces\"/>\n\nThere are 110 full-time faculty members. All of them hold at least [[master's degree]]s, and 89% hold [[doctorate]]s or [[terminal degree]]s. No courses are taught by [[teaching assistant]]s. The student to faculty ratio is 12 to 1.<ref name=\"Closer Look\" /> School of Sciences graduating classes from 2002 to 2006 boasted a 91% acceptance rate for medical school, and an 87% acceptance for pharmacy school.<ref>School of Sciences Newsletter: September 2006. [http://www.cbu.edu/~jholmes/Sciences/Newsletters/Sept/Sept06.html \"Featuring 'Natural Science' and the 'Professional School Acceptance Stats'\"] Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\n[[Image:CBUbuckman.gif|right|thumb|250px|Buckman Hall]]\n\n=== Campus ===\nChristian Brothers University is located on a {{convert|75|acre|m2|adj=on}} wooded campus in the heart of [[Midtown, Memphis]], four miles (6&nbsp;km) east of [[Downtown Memphis, Tennessee|Downtown]].\n\nThe first building on campus, Kenrick Hall, constructed in 1939 as the original [[Christian Brothers High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Christian Brothers High School]], was demolished in 2015 to make room for the Rosa Deal School of Arts, set to open in January 2017.\n\nThe university's architecture follows the [[Georgian architecture|Georgian style]] popular at the time of the campus' relocation to [[East Parkway (Memphis, Tennessee)|East Parkway]]. Arch-covered walkways traverse the main campus, allowing students and faculty to get to most buildings shielded from the weather. The campus is enclosed by an iron fence with brick accents with entrances on East Parkway South, Central Avenue, and Avery Avenue.\n\n==== Outside organizations housed on campus ====\n*Barret School of Banking\n\n=== Canale Arena ===\n{{Main|Canale Arena}}\nCanale Arena, originally called De La Salle Gymnasium, was completed in 1950.<ref name=\"chronology\">{{cite web | url = http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/AboutCBU/OverviewHistory/chronology/index.htm | title = CBU Chronology | publisher = Christian Brothers University | accessdate = 2008-05-30 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080616030514/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/AboutCBU/OverviewHistory/chronology/index.htm | archivedate = 2008-06-16 }}</ref> At that time, it was the largest indoor [[arena]] in the city of Memphis.<ref name=\"renovation\">{{cite web | date= December 1, 2004 | url= http://www.cbu.edu/News/Releases/canale.html | title = Canale Family Foundation Provides Lead Gift: CBU to Dedicate Renovated Arena on December 10 | publisher = Christian Brothers University | last = Kerr | first = John | accessdate =2008-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThe arena was fully renovated in 2004 and has a capacity of 1,000.<ref name=\"renovation\"/>\n\n==Student life==\n\n=== Athletics ===\n{{Main|Christian Brothers Buccaneers}}\nCBU is an [[NCAA Division II]] team and a member of the [[Gulf South Conference]]. Buccaneer teams include baseball, basketball, cross country, golf, and soccer. Lady Buccaneer teams include basketball, cross country, golf, soccer, softball, and volleyball.\n\nThe Lady Buccaneers and Buccaneers have won multiple athletic competitions, including the 2002 [[NCAA Women's Soccer Championship|Division II women's soccer championship]]<ref>{{cite web | date= December 9, 2002 | url =http://www.cbu.edu/News/Releases/WomenSoccerChamps.html | title =Christian Brothers University Women's Soccer Team 2002 NCAA Division II Champions! | publisher =Christian Brothers University | last =Yovich | first =Rudy | accessdate =2008-05-29}}</ref> and the 2008 GSC men's basketball championship.<ref>{{cite web | date= March 9, 2008 | url =http://gobucsgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/030908aaa.html | title =Bucs Hold On For First GSC Championship, 93-89: Kohs named Most Outstanding Player, Weybright All-Tournament | publisher =Christian Brothers University Athletics | accessdate =2009-02-23}}</ref>\nThe Men's Soccer Team has won back to back Conference titles Under Coach Clint Browne during the 2011, 2012 Seasons. Also Making it into the NCAA Tournament in 2011.\n\n=== Greek life ===\n21% of male students and 24% of female students are members of [[fraternities and sororities]]<ref name=\"ABC 2008\">America's Best Colleges 2008. [http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/college/directory/brief/drglance_3482_brief.php \"Christian Brothers University.\"] U.S. News & World Report. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref>\n\nCampus Greek councils include the [[North American Interfraternity Conference|Interfraternity Council]] (IFC), the [[National Panhellenic Conference|Panhellenic Council]] (NPC), and the [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px\" |\n! IFC Fraternities\n! Panhellenic Sororities\n|-\n| [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]] (\u03a3\u0391\u0395): 1989\u2013present\n| [[Alpha Sigma Alpha]] (\u0391\u03a3\u0391): 1986\u20131992\n|-\n| ------------------------------------\n| [[Alpha Sigma Tau]] (\u0391\u03a3\u03a4): 2005\u20132012\n|-\n| [[Tau Kappa Epsilon]] (\u03a4\u039a\u0395): 1979\u2013present\n| [[Alpha Xi Delta]] (\u0391\u039e\u0394): 1994\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Kappa Sigma]] (\u039a\u03a3): 1996\u2013present\n| [[Zeta Tau Alpha]] (\u0396\u03a4\u0391): 1985\u2013present\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px\" |\n! NPHC Fraternities\n! NPHC Sororities\n|-\n| [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] (\u0391\u03a6\u0391): 1977\u2013present\n| [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] (\u0391\u039a\u0391): 1978\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Phi Beta Sigma]] (\u03a6\u0392\u03a3): 1996\u2013present\n| [[Delta Sigma Theta]] (\u0394\u03a3\u0398): 1998\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] (\u039a\u0391\u03a8): 1999\u2013present\n| [[Sigma Gamma Rho]] (\u03a3\u0393\u03a1): 2001\u2013present\n|}\n \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px\" |\n! Professional Fraternity\n|-\n| [[Delta Sigma Pi]] (\u0394\u03a3\u03a0): 1964\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Theta Tau]] (\u0398\u03a4): 2015\u2013present\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px\" |\n! Local & Non-Traditional Fraternities & Sororities\n|-\n| Gamma Theta Phi (\u0393\u0398\u03a6 / Gamma): 1964\u20131997\n|-\n| [[Knights of Columbus]] (K of C): 1972\u20131988\n|}\n\n=== Honor societies and professional organizations ===\nChapters of a number of [[honor society|honor societies]] exist at CBU to recognize excellence in academia and leadership. Active honor societies and their specialties include: [[Alpha Chi]] (general academic), [[Beta Beta Beta]] (biology), the [[Order of Omega]] (fraternity and sorority members), [[Phi Alpha Theta]] (history), [[Psi Chi]] (psychology), [[Sigma Tau Delta]] (English), [[Alpha Psi Omega]] (theatre), and [[Tau Beta Pi]] (engineering).<ref name=\"clubsorg\">[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/StudentLife/ActivitiesOrganizations/StudentGovernment/ClubsOrganizations/index.htm \"Clubs & Organizations\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126022645/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/StudentLife/ActivitiesOrganizations/StudentGovernment/ClubsOrganizations/index.htm |date=2009-01-26 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref>\n\nProfessional organizations include: [[American Institute of Chemical Engineers]], [[American Society of Civil Engineers]], [[American Society of Mechanical Engineers]], [[Institute of Electrical Engineers]], [[Society of Physics Students]], and the Student Affiliates of the [[American Chemical Society]].<ref name=\"clubsorg\" />\n\n=== Engineering competitions ===\n\n==== ASCE / AISC Student Steel Bridge Competition ====\nCivil engineering students also compete in the annual Student Steel Bridge Competition, sponsored by the American Society of Civil Engineers and the American Institute of Steel Construction, Inc. Scale bridges are constructed; judging is based on speed of construction, strength and durability of the bridge, and more.<ref>{{cite web|year=2008 |url=http://www.asce.org/inside/nccc.cfm |title=Student Steel Bridge Competition: 2008 Rules (page 4) |publisher=ASCE/AISC Student Steel Bridge Competition (SSBC) |accessdate=2008-03-28 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027100255/http://www.asce.org/inside/nccc.cfm |archivedate=2007-10-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== ASCE National Concrete Canoe Competition ====\nCivil engineering students construct [[concrete canoe]]s to compete at annual Deep South regional conferences for student chapters of the [[American Society of Civil Engineers]]. These canoes must be able to float and support the weight of several students as they will be raced.<ref>{{cite web|year=2008 |url=http://www.asce.org/inside/nccc.cfm |title=ASCE National Concrete Canoe Competition |publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers |accessdate=2008-03-28 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027100255/http://www.asce.org/inside/nccc.cfm |archivedate=2007-10-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====  IEEE Robotics Competition ====\nElectrical and computer engineering students annually participate in a [[robotics]] Competition organized by the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]]. The 2008 competition was held in [[Huntsville, Alabama]].<ref>{{cite web| date=March 31, 2008| url=http://ewh.ieee.org/reg/3/secon/08| title=IEEE SoutheastCon 2008 \u2013 Huntsville, Alabama| publisher=Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers| accessdate=2008-06-02| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509092841/http://ewh.ieee.org/reg/3/secon/08/| archive-date=May 9, 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==== NASA Great Moonbuggy Race ====\nMechanical engineering students gear up against competitors from schools across the country to build and race vehicles that can travel over simulated lunar terrain. The [[Great Moonbuggy Race|competition]] is held annually at the [[United States Space & Rocket Center]].<ref>{{cite web| date=March 9, 2008| url=http://moonbuggy.msfc.nasa.gov/compete.html| title=Competition, The| publisher=NASA| accessdate=2008-03-28| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403053253/http://moonbuggy.msfc.nasa.gov/compete.html| archive-date=2008-04-03| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Notable CBU people==\n{{unreferenced section|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Notable alumni===\n* [[Harry Bennett Anderson]] - former [[United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Charles Bartliff]] - soccer player and Olympian\n* [[Zach Curlin]] - college basketball coach at [[University of Memphis]] \n* [[Robert B. Hawley]] - U.S. Representative for [[Texas's 10th congressional district]] and accomplished businessman\n* [[Thomas Aquinas Higgins]] - Senior [[United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Bill Justis]] - [[rock and roll]] pioneer\n* [[Youssef Naciri]]- Moroccan professional soccer player (most recently with [[Harrisburg City Islanders]]) \n* [[David Parker (Mississippi politician)|David Parker]]- member of the [[Mississippi State Senate]]\n* [[Malcolm R. Patterson]], [[Governor of Tennessee]] (1907\u20131911)\n* [[Chip Saltsman]] - Republican political strategist and Presidential campaign manager\n* [[Kevin H. Sharp]] - former [[United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Ray Crone]] - Former Major League Baseball Pitcher who played for the Milwaukee Braves and New York Giants\n\n===Notable faculty (current and former)===\n* [[Arun Manilal Gandhi]], scholar and peace activist\n* [[Jeffrey Gros]], Catholic theologian and ecumenist\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Eiffel Tower (Paris, Tennessee)]]\n* [[Christian Brothers High School (Memphis, Tennessee)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.CBU.edu/}}\n* [http://www.gobucsgo.com/ Official athletics website]\n\n{{Lasallian universities and colleges in the United States}}\n{{Gulf South Conference navbox}}\n{{Tennessee private colleges and universities}}\n{{Colleges and universities in the Memphis Metro Area}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Christian Brothers University|*]]\n[[Category:Lasallian colleges and universities]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1871]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = Christian Brothers University\n|image_name      = Christian Brothers University seal.png\n|image_size     = 200px\n|motto           = ''Virtus et Scientia''\n|mottoeng        = Character and Knowledge\n|established     = 1871\n|type            = [[Private school|Private]]\n|religious_affiliation     = [[Catholic Church]] ([[Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools|Christian Brothers]])\n|endowment       = $34,500,000 <ref name=\"ABC 2008\" />\n|faculty         = 110\n|president       = John T. (Jack) Shannon, Jr.\n|students        = 1779<ref name=\"nces\">[http://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=christian+brothers+university&s=all&id=219833 Christian Brothers University]. National Center for Education Statistics. Accessed May 30, 2008.</ref>\n|undergrad       =1455<ref name=\"nces\"/>\n|postgrad        =324\n|address         =\n|city            =[[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]]\n|state           =[[Tennessee]]\n|country         = United States\n|coor            = {{coord|35.127376|-89.982297|type:edu|display=title,inline}}\n|campus          =[[Urban area|Urban]], 76 acres\n|colors          =Red and Gray<br/>{{color box|#CC092F}}&nbsp;{{color box|#A49791}}\n|mascot          = Bucky the Buccaneer\n|nickname        =[[Christian Brothers Buccaneers|Buccaneers & Lady Buccaneers]]\n|athletics       = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] \u2013 [[Gulf South Conference|Gulf South]]\n|affiliations    = [[IALU]], [[Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities|ACCU]], [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]], [[Council of Independent Colleges|CIC]]\n|website         = {{URL|www.cbu.edu}}\n|logo        = [[File:Christian Brothers University logo.png|250px]]\n}}\n\n'''Christian Brothers University''' is a private [[Catholic higher education|Catholic university]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].  The university is run by the [[Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools|De La Salle Brothers]], a Roman [[Catholic religious order]] founded by [[Jean-Baptiste de la Salle|St. John Baptist de la Salle]], the [[patron saint]] of teachers. It is the oldest collegiate degree-granting institution in the city.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:John baptist de la salle 1.jpg|thumb|120px|left|Saint John Baptist de la Salle]]\nChristian Brothers College was founded November 19, 1871, by members of the [[De La Salle Christian Brothers]]. The Brothers came to Memphis at the request of the people and [[clergy]] of the city, after more than a decade of efforts to persuade the Brothers to open a college there.<ref name=\"CBU History\">[http://www.cbu.edu/About/history.html \"CBU History.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050427205925/http://www.cbu.edu/About/history.html |date=2005-04-27 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref>\n\nChristian Brothers University traces its origins to the French priest and educational innovator, St. John Baptist de la Salle.<ref name=\"Lasallian Terminology.\">[http://www.cbu.edu/About/terms.html \"Lasallian Terminology.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712232456/http://www.cbu.edu/About/terms.html |date=July 12, 2007 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref> De la Salle began a system of [[Christianity|Christian]] schools in which teachers assist parents in the educational, ethical, and religious formation of their children. To continue his [[spirituality|spiritual]] and [[pedagogy|pedagogical]] vision, de la Salle founded the Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools, known today as the De La Salle Christian Brothers.\n\nChristian Brothers College officially became Christian Brothers University in June 1990.<ref name=\"CBU History\" />\n\n=== Founding ===\nAfter more than a decade of efforts to persuade the Brothers to open a college in Memphis, Christian Brothers College was founded in 1871.<ref name=\"CBU History\"/>\n\nBrother Maurelian was appointed the first president. His three terms as president totalled 31 years. During his presidency, the Brothers purchased the 612 Adams Street building, which housed the college until 1940 when the college moved to its present location at Central Avenue and [[East Parkway (Memphis, Tennessee)|East Parkway South]].\n\nFunctioning as a combined elementary school, high school (now [[Christian Brothers High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Christian Brothers High School]]), and college, Christian Brothers College granted [[high school diploma]]s as well as [[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor's]] and [[Master's degree|Master's Degrees]] until 1915, when the college division was suspended. Elementary classes were dropped in 1922, and the institution operated as only a high school for 18 years. Reopened in 1940 as a [[junior college]], the college began granting [[Associate's degree|Associate's Degrees]] in 1942.\n\n=== Oldest degree-granting institution in Memphis ===\nChristian Brothers awarded the first post-secondary degree in the city in 1875.<ref name=\"About CBU\">[http://www.cbu.edu/About/mission.html \"About CBU.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223185102/http://www.cbu.edu/About/mission.html |date=2010-12-23 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed March 2, 2008.</ref> LeMoyne College (one of the two constituent parts of present-day [[LeMoyne-Owen College]]) has a founding year of 1871, but it was an elementary and secondary school at the time. The city's largest university, The [[University of Memphis]], was not founded until 1912. Although [[Rhodes College]] was founded 1848, it did not move from [[Clarksville, Tennessee]] to Memphis until 1925.\n\n=== Lasallian tradition ===\nChristian Brothers University traces its origins to priest and educational innovator, [[Jean-Baptiste de la Salle|St. John Baptist de la Salle]].<ref name=\"Lasallian Terminology.\"/> De la Salle began a system of [[Christianity|Christian]] schools in which teachers assist parents in the educational, ethical, and religious formation of their children. To continue his [[spirituality|spiritual]] and [[pedagogy|pedagogical]] vision, de la Salle founded the Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools, known today as the De La Salle Christian Brothers.\n\nThe university currently has a [[laity|lay]] interim president following the fatal car accident of former president Brother Vincent Malham in 2008.<ref>{{cite web| date=May 3, 2008\n|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/may/03/cbu-president-killed-car-wreck-louisiana|title =CBU president Malham killed in car wreck in Louisiana: Had been named school head in 2005| publisher ='The Commercial Appeal'| last =Aarons | first =Dakarai I. | accessdate =2009-02-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Higher education ===\nIn 1953, the decision was made to expand the community college into a four-year institution to better serve the needs of the community. The four-year curriculum began with degrees in [[Administration (business)|Business Administration]] and [[Electrical engineering|Electrical Engineering]], with the first graduates in recent times receiving their degrees in 1955.\n\nThe curriculum was soon expanded to meet the needs for new programs in the fields of [[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical Engineering]] and [[Chemistry]]. The following degree programs were later added: [[Biology]], [[Civil Engineering]], [[Mathematics]], [[English studies|English]], [[Physics]], [[Chemical engineering|Chemical Engineering]], [[History]], [[Psychology]], [[Natural science|Natural Science]], [[Engineering physics|Engineering Physics]], [[Computer science|Computer Science]], and Religion and Philosophy. Teacher preparation programs in secondary education were added in 1969. An accelerated evening program offering a degree in Business Administration was added in 1978 to meet the needs of the adult student, and the [[Applied psychology|Applied Psychology]] degree was added in 1999. In Fall 2007, CBU introduced its [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree.\n\nPrograms at the graduate level were reinstated in 1987 with the Master's program in Telecommunication and Information Systems. The [[Master of Business Administration]] and the [[Engineering management|Master in Engineering Management]] were added in 1989. A [[Master of Education]] was added in 1997, and the [[Master of Arts in Teaching]] and Master of Science in Educational Leadership were offered beginning in 2001. The Master of Arts in Executive Leadership was added in 2005.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nWhen another Catholic college in Memphis (the all-female [[Siena College (Memphis, Tennessee)|Siena College]]) closed,  Christian Brothers University became [[coeducation]]al in 1970. Currently, women comprise approximately 55% of the student body.<ref name=\"nces\"/> Christian Brothers College officially became Christian Brothers University in June 1990.<ref name=\"CBU History\"/>\n\n== Academics ==\n\n=== Schools ===\nThe university has four schools:\n* Gadomski School of Engineering\n* Rosa Deal School of Arts\n* School of Business\n* School of Sciences\n\n=== Study abroad ===\nAs a member of the Lasallian Consortium,<ref>[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/SemestersAbroad/index.htm \"Semesters Abroad\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223012257/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/SemestersAbroad/index.htm |date=2009-02-23 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref> i.e. the seven Lasallian universities in the United States, CBU offers study abroad semesters in [[Australia]], [[Brazil]], [[China]], [[England]], [[France]], [[Ireland]], [[Italy]], [[Mexico]], [[South Africa]], and [[Spain]].<ref>[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/index.htm \"Travel/Study Abroad 2008\u20132009\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081124021357/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/index.htm |date=2008-11-24 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref> Additionally, CBU offers study abroad courses during spring and fall vacations. Upcoming courses include travel in England, France, Italy, Mexico, and [[Uganda]]. Medical missions to [[Haiti]] are available but have been postponed for the present.<ref>[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/Haiti/index.htm \"Haiti Medical Missions \u2013 Fall and Spring Breaks*\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223025151/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/Haiti/index.htm |date=2009-02-23 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref> Study abroad is optional for students but is required for completion of the global studies minor.<ref>[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/GlobalStudiesMinor/index.htm \"Global Studies Minor\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201160814/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/Academics/StudyAbroad/GlobalStudiesMinor/index.htm |date=2008-12-01 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nCBU has one of the most diverse student bodies in the [[Southern United States|South]].<ref>America's Best Colleges 2008. [http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/college/rankings/brief/univmas_s_campdiv_brief.php \"Campus Ethnic Diversity: University-Master's (South).\"] U.S. News & World Report. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref> 51% of students are [[White American|White-American]] (non-Hispanic), 33% are [[African American|African-American]] (non-Hispanic), 5% are [[Asian American|Asian-American]] or [[Pacific Islander American|Pacific Islander-American]], 2% are [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic-American]], and 2% are [[international student]]s. 6% of students have an unknown ethnicity.<ref>[http://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=219833 \"Christian Brothers University.\"] National Center for Education Statistics. Accessed October 18, 2007.</ref> Students hail from more than 28 states and 14 countries.<ref name=\"Closer Look\">[http://www.cbu.edu/About \"Take a Closer Look at CBU.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050425001527/http://www.cbu.edu/About/ |date=2005-04-25 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref>\n\nAlthough CBU is a [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] university, only 23% of students are Catholic. Religious observances are not required, and 32 different [[List of religions|faiths]] are represented in the student body.<ref name=\"Closer Look\" />\n\nNotably, 99% of Christian Brothers University undergraduates receive [[Student financial aid (United States)|financial aid]], broken down as institutional grants (98%), state/local grants (68%), federal grants (29%), and student loans (58%).<ref name=\"nces\"/>\n\nThere are 110 full-time faculty members. All of them hold at least [[master's degree]]s, and 89% hold [[doctorate]]s or [[terminal degree]]s. No courses are taught by [[teaching assistant]]s. The student to faculty ratio is 12 to 1.<ref name=\"Closer Look\" /> School of Sciences graduating classes from 2002 to 2006 boasted a 91% acceptance rate for medical school, and an 87% acceptance for pharmacy school.<ref>School of Sciences Newsletter: September 2006. [http://www.cbu.edu/~jholmes/Sciences/Newsletters/Sept/Sept06.html \"Featuring 'Natural Science' and the 'Professional School Acceptance Stats'\"] Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\n[[Image:CBUbuckman.gif|right|thumb|250px|Buckman Hall]]\n\n=== Campus ===\nChristian Brothers University is located on a {{convert|75|acre|m2|adj=on}} wooded campus in the heart of [[Midtown, Memphis]], four miles (6&nbsp;km) east of [[Downtown Memphis, Tennessee|Downtown]].\n\nThe first building on campus, Kenrick Hall, constructed in 1939 as the original [[Christian Brothers High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Christian Brothers High School]], was demolished in 2015 to make room for the Rosa Deal School of Arts, set to open in January 2017.\n\nThe university's architecture follows the [[Georgian architecture|Georgian style]] popular at the time of the campus' relocation to [[East Parkway (Memphis, Tennessee)|East Parkway]]. Arch-covered walkways traverse the main campus, allowing students and faculty to get to most buildings shielded from the weather. The campus is enclosed by an iron fence with brick accents with entrances on East Parkway South, Central Avenue, and Avery Avenue.\n\n==== Outside organizations housed on campus ====\n*Barret School of Banking\n\n=== Canale Arena ===\n{{Main|Canale Arena}}\nCanale Arena, originally called De La Salle Gymnasium, was completed in 1950.<ref name=\"chronology\">{{cite web | url = http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/AboutCBU/OverviewHistory/chronology/index.htm | title = CBU Chronology | publisher = Christian Brothers University | accessdate = 2008-05-30 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080616030514/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/AboutCBU/OverviewHistory/chronology/index.htm | archivedate = 2008-06-16 }}</ref> At that time, it was the largest indoor [[arena]] in the city of Memphis.<ref name=\"renovation\">{{cite web | date= December 1, 2004 | url= http://www.cbu.edu/News/Releases/canale.html | title = Canale Family Foundation Provides Lead Gift: CBU to Dedicate Renovated Arena on December 10 | publisher = Christian Brothers University | last = Kerr | first = John | accessdate =2008-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThe arena was fully renovated in 2004 and has a capacity of 1,000.<ref name=\"renovation\"/>\n\n==Student life==\n\n=== Athletics ===\n{{Main|Christian Brothers Buccaneers}}\nCBU is an [[NCAA Division II]] team and a member of the [[Gulf South Conference]]. Buccaneer teams include baseball, basketball, cross country, golf, and soccer. Lady Buccaneer teams include basketball, cross country, golf, soccer, softball, and volleyball.\n\nThe Lady Buccaneers and Buccaneers have won multiple athletic competitions, including the 2002 [[NCAA Women's Soccer Championship|Division II women's soccer championship]]<ref>{{cite web | date= December 9, 2002 | url =http://www.cbu.edu/News/Releases/WomenSoccerChamps.html | title =Christian Brothers University Women's Soccer Team 2002 NCAA Division II Champions! | publisher =Christian Brothers University | last =Yovich | first =Rudy | accessdate =2008-05-29}}</ref> and the 2008 GSC men's basketball championship.<ref>{{cite web | date= March 9, 2008 | url =http://gobucsgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/030908aaa.html | title =Bucs Hold On For First GSC Championship, 93-89: Kohs named Most Outstanding Player, Weybright All-Tournament | publisher =Christian Brothers University Athletics | accessdate =2009-02-23}}</ref>\nThe Men's Soccer Team has won back to back Conference titles Under Coach Clint Browne during the 2011, 2012 Seasons. Also Making it into the NCAA Tournament in 2011.\n\n=== Greek life ===\n21% of male students and 24% of female students are members of [[fraternities and sororities]]<ref name=\"ABC 2008\">America's Best Colleges 2008. [http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/college/directory/brief/drglance_3482_brief.php \"Christian Brothers University.\"] U.S. News & World Report. Accessed October 1, 2007.</ref>\n\nCampus Greek councils include the [[North-American Interfraternity Conference|Interfraternity Council]] (IFC), the [[National Panhellenic Conference|Panhellenic Council]] (NPC), and the [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px\" |\n! IFC Fraternities\n! Panhellenic Sororities\n|-\n| [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]] (\u03a3\u0391\u0395): 1989\u2013present\n| [[Alpha Sigma Alpha]] (\u0391\u03a3\u0391): 1986\u20131992\n|-\n| ------------------------------------\n| [[Alpha Sigma Tau]] (\u0391\u03a3\u03a4): 2005\u20132012\n|-\n| [[Tau Kappa Epsilon]] (\u03a4\u039a\u0395): 1979\u2013present\n| [[Alpha Xi Delta]] (\u0391\u039e\u0394): 1994\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Kappa Sigma]] (\u039a\u03a3): 1996\u2013present\n| [[Zeta Tau Alpha]] (\u0396\u03a4\u0391): 1985\u2013present\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px\" |\n! NPHC Fraternities\n! NPHC Sororities\n|-\n| [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] (\u0391\u03a6\u0391): 1977\u2013present\n| [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] (\u0391\u039a\u0391): 1978\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Phi Beta Sigma]] (\u03a6\u0392\u03a3): 1996\u2013present\n| [[Delta Sigma Theta]] (\u0394\u03a3\u0398): 1998\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] (\u039a\u0391\u03a8): 1999\u2013present\n| [[Sigma Gamma Rho]] (\u03a3\u0393\u03a1): 2001\u2013present\n|}\n \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px\" |\n! Professional Fraternity\n|-\n| [[Delta Sigma Pi]] (\u0394\u03a3\u03a0): 1964\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Theta Tau]] (\u0398\u03a4): 2015\u2013present\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px\" |\n! Local & Non-Traditional Fraternities & Sororities\n|-\n| Gamma Theta Phi (\u0393\u0398\u03a6 / Gamma): 1964\u20131997\n|-\n| [[Knights of Columbus]] (K of C): 1972\u20131988\n|}\n\n=== Honor societies and professional organizations ===\nChapters of a number of [[honor society|honor societies]] exist at CBU to recognize excellence in academia and leadership. Active honor societies and their specialties include: [[Alpha Chi]] (general academic), [[Beta Beta Beta]] (biology), the [[Order of Omega]] (fraternity and sorority members), [[Phi Alpha Theta]] (history), [[Psi Chi]] (psychology), [[Sigma Tau Delta]] (English), [[Alpha Psi Omega]] (theatre), and [[Tau Beta Pi]] (engineering).<ref name=\"clubsorg\">[http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/StudentLife/ActivitiesOrganizations/StudentGovernment/ClubsOrganizations/index.htm \"Clubs & Organizations\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126022645/http://www2.cbu.edu/cbu/StudentLife/ActivitiesOrganizations/StudentGovernment/ClubsOrganizations/index.htm |date=2009-01-26 }} Christian Brothers University. Accessed February 23, 2009.</ref>\n\nProfessional organizations include: [[American Institute of Chemical Engineers]], [[American Society of Civil Engineers]], [[American Society of Mechanical Engineers]], [[Institute of Electrical Engineers]], [[Society of Physics Students]], and the Student Affiliates of the [[American Chemical Society]].<ref name=\"clubsorg\" />\n\n=== Engineering competitions ===\n\n==== ASCE / AISC Student Steel Bridge Competition ====\nCivil engineering students also compete in the annual Student Steel Bridge Competition, sponsored by the American Society of Civil Engineers and the American Institute of Steel Construction, Inc. Scale bridges are constructed; judging is based on speed of construction, strength and durability of the bridge, and more.<ref>{{cite web|year=2008 |url=http://www.asce.org/inside/nccc.cfm |title=Student Steel Bridge Competition: 2008 Rules (page 4) |publisher=ASCE/AISC Student Steel Bridge Competition (SSBC) |accessdate=2008-03-28 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027100255/http://www.asce.org/inside/nccc.cfm |archivedate=2007-10-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== ASCE National Concrete Canoe Competition ====\nCivil engineering students construct [[concrete canoe]]s to compete at annual Deep South regional conferences for student chapters of the [[American Society of Civil Engineers]]. These canoes must be able to float and support the weight of several students as they will be raced.<ref>{{cite web|year=2008 |url=http://www.asce.org/inside/nccc.cfm |title=ASCE National Concrete Canoe Competition |publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers |accessdate=2008-03-28 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027100255/http://www.asce.org/inside/nccc.cfm |archivedate=2007-10-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====  IEEE Robotics Competition ====\nElectrical and computer engineering students annually participate in a [[robotics]] Competition organized by the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]]. The 2008 competition was held in [[Huntsville, Alabama]].<ref>{{cite web| date=March 31, 2008| url=http://ewh.ieee.org/reg/3/secon/08| title=IEEE SoutheastCon 2008 \u2013 Huntsville, Alabama| publisher=Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers| accessdate=2008-06-02| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509092841/http://ewh.ieee.org/reg/3/secon/08/| archive-date=May 9, 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==== NASA Great Moonbuggy Race ====\nMechanical engineering students gear up against competitors from schools across the country to build and race vehicles that can travel over simulated lunar terrain. The [[Great Moonbuggy Race|competition]] is held annually at the [[United States Space & Rocket Center]].<ref>{{cite web| date=March 9, 2008| url=http://moonbuggy.msfc.nasa.gov/compete.html| title=Competition, The| publisher=NASA| accessdate=2008-03-28| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403053253/http://moonbuggy.msfc.nasa.gov/compete.html| archive-date=2008-04-03| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Notable CBU people==\n{{unreferenced section|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Notable alumni===\n* [[Harry Bennett Anderson]] - former [[United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Charles Bartliff]] - soccer player and Olympian\n* [[Zach Curlin]] - college basketball coach at [[University of Memphis]] \n* [[Robert B. Hawley]] - U.S. Representative for [[Texas's 10th congressional district]] and accomplished businessman\n* [[Thomas Aquinas Higgins]] - Senior [[United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Bill Justis]] - [[rock and roll]] pioneer\n* [[Youssef Naciri]]- Moroccan professional soccer player (most recently with [[Harrisburg City Islanders]]) \n* [[David Parker (Mississippi politician)|David Parker]]- member of the [[Mississippi State Senate]]\n* [[Malcolm R. Patterson]], [[Governor of Tennessee]] (1907\u20131911)\n* [[Chip Saltsman]] - Republican political strategist and Presidential campaign manager\n* [[Kevin H. Sharp]] - former [[United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Ray Crone]] - Former Major League Baseball Pitcher who played for the Milwaukee Braves and New York Giants\n\n===Notable faculty (current and former)===\n* [[Arun Manilal Gandhi]], scholar and peace activist\n* [[Jeffrey Gros]], Catholic theologian and ecumenist\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Eiffel Tower (Paris, Tennessee)]]\n* [[Christian Brothers High School (Memphis, Tennessee)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.CBU.edu/}}\n* [http://www.gobucsgo.com/ Official athletics website]\n\n{{Lasallian universities and colleges in the United States}}\n{{Gulf South Conference navbox}}\n{{Tennessee private colleges and universities}}\n{{Colleges and universities in the Memphis Metro Area}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Christian Brothers University|*]]\n[[Category:Lasallian colleges and universities]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1871]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities]]\n", "name_user": "Naraht", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGreek life:cleanup, replaced: [[North-American Interfraternity Conference| \u2192 [[North American Interfraternity Conference|", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Brothers_University"}
