{"title_page": "University of Michigan\u2013Flint", "text_new": "{{short description|Public university in Flint, Michigan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = University of Michigan-Flint\n| image_name = UMFlintSeal.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| motto = ''Artes, Scientia, Veritas''\n| mottoeng = Arts, Knowledge, Truth\n| endowment = US$113.1 [[1000000 (number)|million]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/flint-mi/michigan-flint-2327 | title=University of Michigan-Flint \u2013 Best College \u2013 Education \u2013 US News | year=2019| accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| parent = [[University of Michigan]]\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| president = [[Mark S. Schlissel]]\n| chancellor = Deba Dutta<ref>https://www.umflint.edu/chancellor/office-chancellor</ref>\n| provost = [[Susan E. Alcock]]\n| established = 1956\n| city = [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]]\n| state = [[Michigan]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{coord|43.0184961|-83.6886902|region:US-MI_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = Urban\n| students = 7,532<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.umflint.edu/sites/default/files/groups/Institutional_Analysis/documents/cds_2018-2019_final_copy_12-20-18.pdf |title=Common Data Set |accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| undergrad = 6,097\n| postgrad = 1,435\n| staff = 526<ref name=fs>{{cite web|url=https://www.umflint.edu/analysis/qf_faculty_staff |title=Quick Facts - Faculty & Staff |accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| faculty = 568<ref name=fs/>\n| colors = Maize and Blue<ref>{{cite manual |url=https://www.umflint.edu/sites/default/files/groups/Brand/umflint-brand-toolkit-2017.pdf |title=UM-Flint Brand Toolkit \u2013 University of Michigan-Flint |accessdate=November 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709205251/https://www.umflint.edu/sites/default/files/groups/Brand/umflint-brand-toolkit-2017.pdf |archive-date=July 9, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><br/>{{color box|#FFCB05}}&nbsp;{{color box|#00274C}}\n| nickname = {{ubl|Wolverines|[[The Victors]]<ref name=\"FJ\"/> (unofficial)<ref name=tmt/>}}\n| former_names = Flint Senior College of the University of Michigan (1954\u20131964)<br>Flint College of the University of Michigan (1964\u20131971)\n| sports = Club level<ref name=\"UCO\">[https://www.umflint.edu/clubsports/club-sports Club & Organizations]. umflint.edu.</ref>\n| website = {{url|umflint.edu}}\n| logo = University of Michigan\u2013Flint logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Michigan\u2013Flint''' ('''U of M Flint''') is a [[public university]] in [[Flint, Michigan]]. It is one of the two regional campuses of the [[University of Michigan]] operating under the policies of the [[Regents of the University of Michigan|Board of Regents]]. The University of Michigan in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]] is located 55 miles to the south; the other regional campus is in [[University of Michigan\u2013Dearborn|Dearborn]], which is located 72 miles to the southeast. U of M-Flint is [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|classified]] among \"Doctoral/Professional Universities.\"<ref name=\"Carnegie Foundation\">{{cite web |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=171146 |title=The Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education |publisher=Indiana University Bloomington's Center for Postsecondary Research |accessdate=September 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Flint College===\nThe thought of establishing a part of the University of Michigan in the city of Flint started in the year 1837 when Sarah Miles wrote a letter to her family stating, \"A branch of the Michigan University at Ann Arbor is to be established in Flint at some future day.\" <ref>[http://www.umflint.edu/history-um-flint History of UM-Flint]</ref> In May 1944 the Flint Board of Education requested that the University of Michigan open a [[satellite campus]] in [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]].<ref name=gbv>{{cite news|last1=Weller|first1=Krysten|title=University of Michigan-Flint celebrates its 50th anniversary|url=http://mgb.mihomepaper.com/news/2006-09-21/News/University_of_MichiganFlint_celebrates_its_50th_an.html|accessdate=December 10, 2014|work=The Grand Blanc View|date=September 21, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002001/http://mgb.mihomepaper.com/news/2006-09-21/News/University_of_MichiganFlint_celebrates_its_50th_an.html|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In June 1944, [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] signed the [[G.I. Bill]] into law. The demand for higher education increased with the return of soldiers after World War II, and was a major factor in the establishment of a branch of the University of Michigan in the city of Flint.<ref name=\"UM-Flint\">{{cite web |url=http://www.umflint.edu/history_gallery_timeline.htm |title=Timeline and History |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |author=UM-Flint |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225112759/http://www.umflint.edu/history_gallery_timeline.htm |archivedate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> During 1947 the Regents of the University of Michigan approved a higher education needs assessment for Flint. The community indicated that they wanted a four-year liberal arts college similar to Ann Arbor's College of Literature, Science, and the Arts.<ref name=\"ur\">{{cite news|last1=Thomas Gnagey |first1=Laurel|title=Flint campus is 50 years young|url=http://ur.umich.edu/0607/Oct02_06/01.shtml|accessdate=September 5, 2017|work=University Record |date=October 2, 2006}}</ref>\n\nLater, in February 1956, David M. French was named the first dean of the Flint Senior College of the University of Michigan.<ref name=\"UM-Flint\"/> Flint College opened on the [[Mott Community College|Flint Community Junior College]] campus.<ref name=fj0>{{cite news|last1=Schuch|first1=Sarah|title=From dirt to dorms: UM-Flint still growing 40 years after historic groundbreaking |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2014/12/from_dirt_to_college_town_univ.html |accessdate=December 10, 2014|work=The Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group}}</ref> The college's initial enrollment was 167 enrollees. Degrees were offered in bachelor's degrees in liberal arts and sciences and in the professional fields of education and business administration.<ref name=\"ur\" /> Original donors to construction buildings was C.S. Mott and the Sponsors Fund of Flint. The college's first class graduated in 1958.<ref name=gbv/>\n\nThe college became a four-year institution in 1964, adding its first freshman class the next year. In 1970, the North Central Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools granted accreditation to the Flint College of the University of Michigan.<ref name=\"ur\" />\n\n===University of Michigan\u2013Flint===\nThe Regents of the University of [[Michigan]] approved the name change to The University of Michigan\u2013Flint in 1971, and named William E. Moran as the first Chancellor of the University of Michigan\u2013Flint.<ref name=\"ur\" /> Two schools were formed at Flint in 1975, the College of Arts and Sciences, the School of Management.<ref name=\"fj4\">{{cite news|last1=Emery|first1=Amanda|title=University of Michigan-Flint campus to add nursing school |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2016/10/university_of_michigan-flint_t_23.html|accessdate=October 21, 2016|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe community and city assisted U of M\u2013Flint in acquiring along the [[Flint River (Michigan)|Flint River]] 42 acres.<ref name=\"ur\" /> $5 million over five years was pledged towards a new campus in 1972 by the C.S. Mott Foundation.<ref name=fj0/> During September 1972, sixteen temporary buildings were erected to ease campus overcrowding, pressuring the Regents to move U of M-Flint to its current location along the Flint River.\n\nOn September 1, 1973, the Regents passed the plans for the first building by Sedgewick-Sellers & Associates, originally planned for a site at Lapeer Road and Court Street. Instead, the first building was moved to a site on the Flint River, the current campus location. The university acquired the Ross House and the Hubbard Building. Its ground breaking ceremony was held on May 9, 1974 at the Wilson Park bandstand.<ref name=fj0/>  In 1977, construction ended on the Class Room Office Building (CROB), later named David M. French Hall, and the Central Energy Plant.<ref name=fj0/> CROB included a library and theatre.<ref name=\"ur\" /> In 1979, the original Harrison Street [[Halo Burger]] location was vacated to make way for University of Michigan\u2013Flint parking.<ref name=\"mt\">{{cite news | author = Christy Ryan | title = Halo Burger reluctant to leave in fall | url = http://www.themichigantimes.com/article/2008/04/halo_burger_reluctant_to_leave_in_fall | format = shtml | work = Michigan Times | publisher = University of Michigan-Flint | location = Flint, Michigan | date = April 21, 2008 | accessdate = June 2, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122823/http://www.themichigantimes.com/article/2008/04/halo_burger_reluctant_to_leave_in_fall | archive-date = April 2, 2015 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> While, the Harding Mott University Center (UCen) was finished that same year and the Recreation Center in 1982.<ref name=fj1>{{cite news |last1=Schuch|first1=Sarah|title=What to know about UM-Flint buying portion of historic Flint bank building |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2015/10/what_you_need_to_know_about_um.html|accessdate=October 19, 2015|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=October 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Frances Willson Thompson Library University of Michigan.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Frances Willson Thompson Library at the University of Michigan\u2013Flint]]\nWilliam S. Murchie Science Building was completed in 1988.<ref name=fj1/> In 1991, U of M-Flint took over ownership of the Water Street Pavilion as the University Pavilion<ref name=gbv/> keeping restaurants there while moving in administrative offices.<ref name=fj1/> The library moved to its own building in 1994 with the completion of the Frances Willson Thompson Library. The 25 acre site across the river on the north side was acquired in 1997.<ref name=\"ur\" /> Northbank Center was acquired in 1998.<ref name=fj1/>\n\nIn 1989, the School of Health Professions and Studies was formed and later renamed the College of Health Sciences in 2018. The School of Education and Human Services was formed<ref name=\"fj4\"/> in 1997.\n\nIn September 1999, Juan E. Mestas began his tenure as the fifth Chancellor of the University of Michigan\u2013Flint.<ref name=gbv/> The William S. White Building was completed on the north side of the Flint River in 2002 for School of Health Professions and Studies<ref name=fj1/> and the School of Management.<ref name=fj2>{{cite news|last1=Mostafavi|first1=Beata|title=University of Michigan-Flint business students to trade stocks in mini Wall Street center in Riverfront Residence Hall |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2011/07/university_of_michigan-flint_b_1.html|accessdate=October 19, 2015|work=Flint Journal|publisher=MLive Media Group|date=July 22, 2011}}</ref> Halo Burger returned to the campus in September 2002 only to be forced out due to on-campus housing food regulations in 2008.<ref name=\"mt\"/>\n\nRuth Person became chancellor in 2008.<ref name=fj3>{{cite news|last1=Thorne|first1=Blake Thorne|title=University of Michigan-Flint Chancellor Ruth Person says she will depart in 2014 |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2013/01/university_of_michigan-flint_c_16.html|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=January 23, 2013}}</ref> The first on-campus dorms, First Street Residence Hall, were completed in 2008.<ref name=fj1/> The University of Michigan\u2013Flint in 2010 was the fastest-growing public university in the state of Michigan.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/04/um-flint_keeps_rank_as_states.html | title=Flint Campus of the University of Michigan keeps rank as state's fastest growing university | publisher=M Live |date=April 15, 2010 | accessdate=October 20, 2010}}</ref>  The School of Management moved to a leased floor of the Riverfront Residence Hall in early 2013 from the White Building at renovation cost of $5.3 million.<ref name=fj2/> In 2013, Person's five-year term was up and was extended for a year by U of M President Mary Sue Coleman to 2014.<ref name=fj3/>\n\nIn August 2014, Sue Borrego began as Chancellor.<ref name=\"mlive41714\">{{Cite web| title = University of Michigan appoints Susan Borrego as Flint chancellor |author = Woodhouse, Kellie| work = MLive.com| date = April 17, 2014| accessdate = January 11, 2015| url = http://www.mlive.com/news/ann-arbor/index.ssf/2014/04/university_of_michigan_appoint_1.html}}</ref> On October 15, 2015, University Board of Regents approved the purchase of the 160,000-square-foot, 10-story north tower building of the [[Citizens Republic Bancorp#Citizens Banking Building|Citizens Banking Buildings]] from [[FirstMerit Bank]] for $6 million expected to close in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schuch|first1=Sarah|title=UM-Flint buys part of historic downtown bank building |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2015/10/um-flint_meeting.html|accessdate=October 20, 2015|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group |date=October 15, 2015}}</ref> In mid-December 2015, the Uptown Reinvestment Corporation donated the Riverfront Residence Hall and Banquet Center to the university with the [[Charles Stewart Mott Foundation]] forgiving the remaining redevelopment loan for the center.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackman |first1=Caresse |title=Uptown Reinvestment Corporation donates Riverfront Residence Hall Banquet Center to UM-Flint |url=http://www.abc12.com/news/headlines/Uptown-Reinvestment-Corporation-donates-Riverfront-Residence-Hall-Banquet-Center-to-UM-Flint-362846881.html |accessdate=December 30, 2015 |work=ABC12.com |publisher=WJRT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604114105/http://www.abc12.com/news/headlines/Uptown-Reinvestment-Corporation-donates-Riverfront-Residence-Hall-Banquet-Center-to-UM-Flint-362846881.html |archive-date=June 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On October 20, 2016, the Regents formed the School of Nursing from the Department of Nursing in the School of Health Professions and Studies.<ref>{{cite news|title=U of Michigan creates School of Nursing at Flint campus|url=http://www.abc12.com/content/news/U-of-Michigan-creates-School-of-Nursing-at-Flint-campus-397863791.html|accessdate=October 21, 2016|work=ABC12|publisher=WJRT|date=October 21, 2016}}</ref> The Harrison Street Annex, at Kearsley and Harrison Streets in the Harrison Street parking structure, has been remodeled to be the university's engineering design studio.<ref>{{cite news|title=UM-Flint Engineering celebrates change, growth |url=https://news.umflint.edu/2017/07/20/um-flint-engineering-celebrates-change-growth/ |accessdate=July 20, 2017|work= umflint.edu |publisher= UM-Flint |date=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:300px;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''College/school founding'''<ref name=\"fj4\" />\n|-\n| '''College/school''' || '''Year founded'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<hr>\n|-\n| College of Arts and Sciences || 1955\n|-\n| School of Management || 1975\n|-\n| College of Health Sciences || 1982\n|-\n| School of Education and Human Services || 1997\n|-\n| School of Nursing || 2016\n|}\n\nThere are 138 majors/concentrations that apply to 12 Bachelor's degrees and 43 graduate majors/concentrations. U of M-Flint also offers graduate degrees including master's degrees, Professional Doctorals, and Ph.D. degrees. The university's colleges and schools include the College of Arts and Sciences (CAS), College of Health Sciences (CHS), School of Education & Human Services (SEHS), School of Management (SOM) and School of Nursing (SON).\n\n===Rankings and accreditation===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| USNWR_NU = 293-381\n| Wamo_NU = 339\n}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR undergraduate rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR 2020 Rankings\">{{cite magazine|title=University of Michigan-Flint|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=September 27, 2019 |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-michigan-flint-2327}}</ref>\n|-\n| Top Performers on Social Mobility\n| 214\n|-\n| Engineering (no doctorate)\n| 110\n|-\n|}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR graduate rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Best Grad Schools\">{{cite magazine|title=University of Michigan-Flint|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=September 27, 2019 |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-graduate-schools/university-of-michigan-flint-171146}}</ref>\n|-\n| Nursing-Anesthesia\n| 22\n|-\n| Online Master's in Nursing\n| 53\n|-\n| Physical Therapy\n| 53\n|-\n| Best Public Affairs Program\n| 216\n|-\n| Part-time MBA\n| 127\n|-\n|}\n\n''[[The Princeton Review]]'' included U of M-Flint in the \"Best Midwestern\" category in their publication ''2020 Best Colleges: Region by Region''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.princetonreview.com/college-rankings?rankings=best-midwestern |title=Best Midwestern |accessdate=September 27, 2019 |author=Princeton Review}}</ref> They also included U of M-Flint's School of Management as one of the Best Business Schools in their 2017 publication.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.umflint.edu/2016/10/26/um-flint-school-management-makes-princeton-reviews-top-business-school-list/ |title=UM-Flint Makes Princeton Review\u2019s Top Business School List|accessdate=October 26, 2016 |author=UM-Flint}}</ref> The Part-Time MBA Program was ranked 41st in the United States (overall) and 9th in the Midwest (by region) in 2010 by Businessweek.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bwnt.businessweek.com/bschools/ptmba_rankings_2009/index.asp?sortCol=rankid&sortOrder=1&pageNum=1&resultNum=100 |title=The Top ranked part-time MBA Program |accessdate=November 10, 2009 |author=Business Week |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109194947/http://bwnt.businessweek.com/bschools/ptmba_rankings_2009/index.asp?sortCol=rankid&sortOrder=1&pageNum=1&resultNum=100 |archive-date=January 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nU of M-Flint is accredited by the Higher Learning Commission (HLC) of Colleges and Schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hlcommission.org/component/directory/?Itemid=&Action=ShowBasic&instid=1370|title=HLC Accreditation|accessdate=September 27, 2019 |author=HLC}}</ref> Program-level accreditation is maintained by many programs in affiliation with: the Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://main.abet.org/aps/AccreditedProgramsDetails.aspx?OrganizationID=892&ProgramIDs=|title=ABET-Accredited Programs|accessdate=September 27, 2019 |author=ABET}}</ref> the American Chemical Society, Association for the Accreditation of Human Research Protection Programs, the Association to Advance Collegiate School of Business \u2013 International,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://datadirect.aacsb.edu/public/profiles/profile.cfm?runReport=1&unitid=54729&userType=All|title=AACSB Accreditation|accessdate=December 22, 2008 |author=AACSB}}</ref> Association of University Programs in Health Administration, the Commission on Accreditation in Physical Therapy Education,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apta.org/AM/Template.cfm?section=CAPTE3&template=/aptaapps/accreditedschools/acc_schools_map.cfm&process=2&ProgramID=935|title=APTA Accreditation|accessdate=December 22, 2008|author=APTA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081130042314/http://www.apta.org/AM/Template.cfm?section=CAPTE3&template=%2Faptaapps%2Faccreditedschools%2Facc_schools_map.cfm&process=2&ProgramID=935|archive-date=November 30, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Commission on Accreditation in Respiratory Care, the Commission of Collegiate Nursing Education, the Council for Accreditation of Teacher Education, the Council on Accreditation for Nurse Anesthesia Educational Programs,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://webapps.aana.com/AccreditedPrograms/accreditedprograms.asp?State=MI&s8fid=112299292254 |title=AANA Accreditation |accessdate=December 22, 2008 |author=AANA |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517013325/http://webapps.aana.com/AccreditedPrograms/accreditedprograms.asp?State=MI&s8fid=112299292254 |archive-date=May 17, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> the Council on Social Work Education,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://portal.cswe.org/Membership/CompanyInformation.aspx?sqs=ELAVJ5Wc13dHesWOyxqWuP349NNLV1mL3np+8zK+5YILrOkVcgZL7az6NOC2vtyj23R1MNwbw/RxxIsxMWNENYtYm1/4kCxa2Ix7b7Z5woM/NTQyucNfE8yvKfwMmPghoD7ZdEAoSixVH1aslteY1NvCGV4N1u93KRlPposYimkzKm/znhknHJAwkOekTYrsE47v4Ka3QXJVzYg19jFiskoXm0e/orF6C7oDZZC3HjmL&addressnum=|title=CSWE Accreditation|accessdate=December 22, 2008 |author=CSWE}}</ref> the Joint Review Committee on Education in Radiologic Technology,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jrcert.org/cert/View.jsp?pid=0841 |title=JRCERT Accreditation |accessdate=December 22, 2008 |author=JRCERT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225015947/http://www.jrcert.org/cert/View.jsp?pid=0841 |archive-date=December 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Michigan Department of Education, the National Association for the Education of Young Children and the National Association of Schools of Music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nasm.arts-accredit.org/index.jsp?page=Member+Lists&memberId=2473bfa56624d11662c6c5adc0f3eb46|title=NASM Accreditation|accessdate=December 22, 2008|author=NASM|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090516234204/http://nasm.arts-accredit.org/index.jsp?page=Member+Lists&memberId=2473bfa56624d11662c6c5adc0f3eb46|archive-date=May 16, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Residential and student life==\n\n===On campus housing===\n[[File:University of Michigan\u2013Flint July 2018 1 (First Street Residence Hall).jpg|right|thumb|250px|The First Street Residence Hall, a modern building dormitory for students at the University of Michigan, Flint Campus]]\n\nIn November 2004, the [[Board of Regents of the University of Michigan]] approved the request of the Flint Campus to explore the feasibility of student housing. After several assessments, studies, and surveys showing the probable progression of growth of the campus, student housing was approved. On July 16, 2007, the first-ever student dormitory, the First Street Residence Hall, opened for students.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.umflint.edu/housing/july17_release.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304073842/http://www.umflint.edu/housing/july17_release.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Uptown Reinvestment Corporation donated the Riverfront Residence Hall, a privately owned high-rise building that houses both U of M-Flint and [[Baker College]] students, to the university.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Dominic |title=U-M Flint aims to grow international enrollment with Riverfront donation|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2015/12/um-flint_aims_to_grow_internat.html|website=MLive.com|publisher=MLive Media Group|accessdate=December 19, 2015}}</ref> The 16-story Residence Hall can house up to 500 students.\n\n===Student Organizations===\nThere are over 100 recognized student organizations and 8 Sponsored Student Organizations (SSOs). They are organizations for various academic departments, religions, and cultural backgrounds, as well as organizations for honors, club sports, social fraternities and sororities, service groups, and special interests.\n\n'''University sponsored organizations:'''\n*[[The Michigan Times]], the student newspaper of the University of Michigan\u2013Flint.\n*Black Student Union\n*Campus Activities Board\n*College Panhellenic Association\n*Interfraternity Council\n*[[National Pan-Hellenic Council]]\n*Qua Literacy and Fine Arts Magazine\n*Student Government\n\n===Greek Life===\nThe university is home to several [[fraternities and sororities]]:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.umflint.edu/sil/fraternity-and-sorority-life-0 |title=Fraternity and Sorority Life |accessdate=September 28, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Sororities:'''\n*[[Delta Sigma Theta]]\n*[[Sigma Gamma Rho]]\n*[[Zeta Phi Beta]]\n*[[Phi Sigma Sigma]]\n*[[Sigma Sigma Sigma]]\n*[[Theta Phi Alpha]]\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Fraternities:'''\n*[[Alpha Phi Alpha]]\n*[[Kappa Alpha Psi]]\n*[[Phi Beta Sigma]]\n*[[Alpha Sigma Phi]]\n*[[Kappa Sigma]]\n*[[Theta Chi]]{{Col-end}}\n\n[[File:University of Michigan\u2013Flint July 2018 7 (University Pavilion).jpg|thumb|University Pavilion]]\n\n===Radio station===\nThe school owns [[WFUM]] (91.1 FM), a [[public radio]] station affiliated with the [[Michigan Radio]] network.\n\n===Student newspaper===\n''[[The Michigan Times]]'' is a student-run campus newspaper.  In 2008, the Michigan Press Association's \"Better College Newspaper Contest\" awarded ''The Michigan Times'' with nine awards in a statewide competition. This achievement was surpassed in 2009 by winning 23 awards.<ref>{{cite web|last=Profitt|first=Jennifer|title=From the Editor's Desk: M-Times wins MPA awards|url=http://www.themichigantimes.com/2.11010/from-the-editor-s-desk-1.1531477|work=The Michigan Times|accessdate=October 20, 2009}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The newspaper is printed weekly and is available free-of-cost on campus, at other area colleges, in the surrounding downtown area and elsewhere in the Greater Flint area.\n\n===Student government===\nThe University of Michigan\u2013Flint Student Government represents the students and manages student funds on the campus. Student Government is a member of the statewide Association of Michigan Universities.\n\n==Athletics==\nU of M\u2013Flint does not offer varsity intercollegiate athletics, but there are a number of club sport teams and intramural sports leagues available to students. Teams have competed as Wolverines, while an unofficial student vote in 2009 selected [[The Victors]] to avoid confusion with the main campus.<ref name=\"FJ\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/index.ssf/2008/09/sports_talk_at_university_of_m.html |title=Sports talk at University of Michigan-Flint sparks more mascot consideration |accessdate=October 29, 2008 |last=Mostafavi |first=Beata |date=September 22, 2008 |work=[[Flint Journal]] |publisher=[[Booth Newspapers]] |location=Flint, Michigan |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517100159/http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/index.ssf/2008/09/sports_talk_at_university_of_m.html |archivedate=May 17, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=tmt>{{cite news|last=Shoup|first=Allison|title='Victors' not yet a sure thing|url=http://www.themichigantimes.com/index.php/article/2008/04/victors_not_yet_a_sure_thing|accessdate=April 9, 2012|newspaper=The Michigan Times|date=April 25, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812205405/http://www.themichigantimes.com/index.php/article/2008/04/victors_not_yet_a_sure_thing|archivedate=August 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Students, staff and alumni are also able to buy tickets to the flagship campus' sporting events at a discounted price.\n\nCurrent Club Sports include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umflint.edu/clubsports/team-directory|title=Team Directory {{!}} University of Michigan-Flint|website=www.umflint.edu|language=en-us|access-date=2018-07-03}}</ref>\n\n*Men's & Women's Basketball\n*Cheer\n*Men's Ice Hockey\n*Men's & Women's Soccer\n*Women's Volleyball\n*Softball\n\nIn 2013, the men's hockey team earned a spot in the [[American Collegiate Hockey Association|ACHA]] Division III National Tournament for the first time, eventually advancing to the National Championship Game against fellow [[Michigan Collegiate Hockey Conference]] foe [[Adrian College]]. In 2015, the women's hockey team went 18-0 in conference play.\n\n== Notable faculty and alumni ==\n* [[Jim Ananich]] \u2013 [[Michigan Senate]] Minority Leader\n* Shari Ballard \u2013 Former [[Best Buy]] Senior Executive VP <ref>{{cite web|title=UM-Flint Commencement Speaker is Alumna and Best Buy Exec|url=https://news.umflint.edu/2017/04/12/14578/|publisher=UM-Flint|accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[Deborah Cherry]] \u2013 Former Michigan State Senator\n* [[John D. Cherry]] \u2013 62nd [[Lieutenant Governor of Michigan]]<ref name=\"gbv\" />\n* [[Bobby Crim]] \u2013 Former Michigan Speaker of the House and State Representative and Founder of the [[Crim Festival of Races]]<ref name=\"gbv\" /> \n* [[Christopher Paul Curtis]] (2000) \u2013 Writer and [[Newbery Medal]] winner<ref name=\"gbv\" />\n* [[Erin Darke]] \u2013 Actress <ref>{{cite web|title=Alumna Erin Darke Finds Success on Stage and Screen|url=https://news.umflint.edu/2015/06/16/alumna-erin-darke-finds-success-on-stage-and-screen/|publisher=UM-Flint|accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Mona Haydar]] \u2013 Rapper, poet, activist and chaplain\n* [[LaKisha Jones]] \u2013 Singer, [[American Idol]] contestant\n* [[Michael Moore]] \u2013 Documentary film director, author<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Moore|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/103383/Michael-Moore/biography|work=Biography|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Don Riegle]] (1960) \u2013 [[United States Senator]] from Michigan<ref>{{cite web|title=Donald W. Riegle, Jr Archives |url=https://www.umflint.edu/archives/donald-w-riegle-jr|work=Biography |publisher=University of Michigan-Flint|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Marietta S. Robinson]] \u2013 Former Commissioner of the [[U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Marietta S. Robinson |url=http://www.cpsc.gov/en/About-CPSC/Commissioners/Marietta-Robinson/|work=Biography|publisher=U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[John Sinclair (poet)|John Sinclair]] (1964) \u2013 Poet, political activist<ref>http://libguides.umflint.edu/johnsinclair{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Tim Sneller]] \u2013 member of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] from the 50th district<ref name=house_sneller>[https://housedems.com/sneller \"Meet Tim Sneller\"]. housedems.com, November 9, 2019.</ref>\n* [[Woodrow Stanley]] \u2013 Former Michigan State Representative, Mayor of Flint\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Michigan Times]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n{{Flint, Michigan}}\n{{University of Michigan System}}\n{{Public universities in Michigan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University of Michigan-Flint}}\n[[Category:University of Michigan\u2013Flint| ]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan|*Flint]]\n[[Category:Education in Flint, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Genesee County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Public universities in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1956]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Flint, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Flint, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Flint, Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public university in Flint, Michigan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = University of Michigan-Flint\n| image_name = UMFlintSeal.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| motto = ''Artes, Scientia, Veritas''\n| mottoeng = Arts, Knowledge, Truth\n| endowment = US$113.1 [[1000000 (number)|million]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/flint-mi/michigan-flint-2327 | title=University of Michigan-Flint \u2013 Best College \u2013 Education \u2013 US News | year=2019| accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| parent = [[University of Michigan]]\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| president = [[Mark S. Schlissel]]\n| chancellor = Deba Dutta<ref>https://www.umflint.edu/chancellor/office-chancellor</ref>\n| provost = [[Susan E. Alcock]]\n| established = 1956\n| city = [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]]\n| state = [[Michigan]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{coord|43.0184961|-83.6886902|region:US-MI_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = Urban\n| students = 7,532<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.umflint.edu/sites/default/files/groups/Institutional_Analysis/documents/cds_2018-2019_final_copy_12-20-18.pdf |title=Common Data Set |accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| undergrad = 6,097\n| postgrad = 1,435\n| staff = 526<ref name=fs>{{cite web|url=https://www.umflint.edu/analysis/qf_faculty_staff |title=Quick Facts - Faculty & Staff |accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| faculty = 568<ref name=fs/>\n| colors = Maize and Blue<ref>{{cite manual |url=https://www.umflint.edu/sites/default/files/groups/Brand/umflint-brand-toolkit-2017.pdf |title=UM-Flint Brand Toolkit \u2013 University of Michigan-Flint |accessdate=November 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709205251/https://www.umflint.edu/sites/default/files/groups/Brand/umflint-brand-toolkit-2017.pdf |archive-date=July 9, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><br/>{{color box|#FFCB05}}&nbsp;{{color box|#00274C}}\n| nickname = {{ubl|Wolverines|[[The Victors]]<ref name=\"FJ\"/> (unofficial)<ref name=tmt/>}}\n| former_names = Flint Senior College of the University of Michigan (1954\u20131964)<br>Flint College of the University of Michigan (1964\u20131971)\n| sports = Club level<ref name=\"UCO\">[https://www.umflint.edu/clubsports/club-sports Club & Organizations]. umflint.edu.</ref>\n| website = {{url|umflint.edu}}\n| logo = University of Michigan\u2013Flint logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Michigan\u2013Flint''' ('''U of M Flint''') is a [[public university]] in [[Flint, Michigan]]. It is one of the two regional campuses of the [[University of Michigan]] operating under the policies of the [[Regents of the University of Michigan|Board of Regents]]. The University of Michigan in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]] is located 55 miles to the south; the other regional campus is in [[University of Michigan\u2013Dearborn|Dearborn]], which is located 72 miles to the southeast. U of M-Flint is [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|classified]] among \"Doctoral/Professional Universities.\"<ref name=\"Carnegie Foundation\">{{cite web |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=171146 |title=The Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education |publisher=Indiana University Bloomington's Center for Postsecondary Research |accessdate=September 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Flint College===\nThe thought of establishing a part of the University of Michigan in the city of Flint started in the year 1837 when Sarah Miles wrote a letter to her family stating, \"A branch of the Michigan University at Ann Arbor is to be established in Flint at some future day.\" <ref>[http://www.umflint.edu/history-um-flint History of UM-Flint]</ref> In May 1944 the Flint Board of Education requested that the University of Michigan open a [[satellite campus]] in [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]].<ref name=gbv>{{cite news|last1=Weller|first1=Krysten|title=University of Michigan-Flint celebrates its 50th anniversary|url=http://mgb.mihomepaper.com/news/2006-09-21/News/University_of_MichiganFlint_celebrates_its_50th_an.html|accessdate=December 10, 2014|work=The Grand Blanc View|date=September 21, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002001/http://mgb.mihomepaper.com/news/2006-09-21/News/University_of_MichiganFlint_celebrates_its_50th_an.html|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In June 1944, [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] signed the [[G.I. Bill]] into law. The demand for higher education increased with the return of soldiers after World War II, and was a major factor in the establishment of a branch of the University of Michigan in the city of Flint.<ref name=\"UM-Flint\">{{cite web |url=http://www.umflint.edu/history_gallery_timeline.htm |title=Timeline and History |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |author=UM-Flint |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225112759/http://www.umflint.edu/history_gallery_timeline.htm |archivedate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> During 1947 the Regents of the University of Michigan approved a higher education needs assessment for Flint. The community indicated that they wanted a four-year liberal arts college similar to Ann Arbor's College of Literature, Science, and the Arts.<ref name=\"ur\">{{cite news|last1=Thomas Gnagey |first1=Laurel|title=Flint campus is 50 years young|url=http://ur.umich.edu/0607/Oct02_06/01.shtml|accessdate=September 5, 2017|work=University Record |date=October 2, 2006}}</ref>\n\nLater, in February 1956, David M. French was named the first dean of the Flint Senior College of the University of Michigan.<ref name=\"UM-Flint\"/> Flint College opened on the [[Mott Community College|Flint Community Junior College]] campus.<ref name=fj0>{{cite news|last1=Schuch|first1=Sarah|title=From dirt to dorms: UM-Flint still growing 40 years after historic groundbreaking |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2014/12/from_dirt_to_college_town_univ.html |accessdate=December 10, 2014|work=The Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group}}</ref> The college's initial enrollment was 167 enrollees. Degrees were offered in bachelor's degrees in liberal arts and sciences and in the professional fields of education and business administration.<ref name=\"ur\" /> Original donors to construction buildings was C.S. Mott and the Sponsors Fund of Flint. The college's first class graduated in 1958.<ref name=gbv/>\n\nThe college became a four-year institution in 1964, adding its first freshman class the next year. In 1970, the North Central Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools granted accreditation to the Flint College of the University of Michigan.<ref name=\"ur\" />\n\n===University of Michigan\u2013Flint===\nThe Regents of the University of [[Michigan]] approved the name change to The University of Michigan\u2013Flint in 1971, and named William E. Moran as the first Chancellor of the University of Michigan\u2013Flint.<ref name=\"ur\" /> Two schools were formed at Flint in 1975, the College of Arts and Sciences, the School of Management.<ref name=\"fj4\">{{cite news|last1=Emery|first1=Amanda|title=University of Michigan-Flint campus to add nursing school |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2016/10/university_of_michigan-flint_t_23.html|accessdate=October 21, 2016|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe community and city assisted U of M\u2013Flint in acquiring along the [[Flint River (Michigan)|Flint River]] 42 acres.<ref name=\"ur\" /> $5 million over five years was pledged towards a new campus in 1972 by the C.S. Mott Foundation.<ref name=fj0/> During September 1972, sixteen temporary buildings were erected to ease campus overcrowding, pressuring the Regents to move U of M-Flint to its current location along the Flint River.\n\nOn September 1, 1973, the Regents passed the plans for the first building by Sedgewick-Sellers & Associates, originally planned for a site at Lapeer Road and Court Street. Instead, the first building was moved to a site on the Flint River, the current campus location. The university acquired the Ross House and the Hubbard Building. Its ground breaking ceremony was held on May 9, 1974 at the Wilson Park bandstand.<ref name=fj0/>  In 1977, construction ended on the Class Room Office Building (CROB), later named David M. French Hall, and the Central Energy Plant.<ref name=fj0/> CROB included a library and theatre.<ref name=\"ur\" /> In 1979, the original Harrison Street [[Halo Burger]] location was vacated to make way for University of Michigan\u2013Flint parking.<ref name=\"mt\">{{cite news | author = Christy Ryan | title = Halo Burger reluctant to leave in fall | url = http://www.themichigantimes.com/article/2008/04/halo_burger_reluctant_to_leave_in_fall | format = shtml | work = Michigan Times | publisher = University of Michigan-Flint | location = Flint, Michigan | date = April 21, 2008 | accessdate = June 2, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122823/http://www.themichigantimes.com/article/2008/04/halo_burger_reluctant_to_leave_in_fall | archive-date = April 2, 2015 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> While, the Harding Mott University Center (UCen) was finished that same year and the Recreation Center in 1982.<ref name=fj1>{{cite news |last1=Schuch|first1=Sarah|title=What to know about UM-Flint buying portion of historic Flint bank building |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2015/10/what_you_need_to_know_about_um.html|accessdate=October 19, 2015|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=October 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Frances Willson Thompson Library University of Michigan.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Frances Willson Thompson Library at the University of Michigan\u2013Flint]]\nWilliam S. Murchie Science Building was completed in 1988.<ref name=fj1/> In 1991, U of M-Flint took over ownership of the Water Street Pavilion as the University Pavilion<ref name=gbv/> keeping restaurants there while moving in administrative offices.<ref name=fj1/> The library moved to its own building in 1994 with the completion of the Frances Willson Thompson Library. The 25 acre site across the river on the north side was acquired in 1997.<ref name=\"ur\" /> Northbank Center was acquired in 1998.<ref name=fj1/>\n\nIn 1989, the School of Health Professions and Studies was formed and later renamed the College of Health Sciences in 2018. The School of Education and Human Services was formed<ref name=\"fj4\"/> in 1997.\n\nIn September 1999, Juan E. Mestas began his tenure as the fifth Chancellor of the University of Michigan\u2013Flint.<ref name=gbv/> The William S. White Building was completed on the north side of the Flint River in 2002 for School of Health Professions and Studies<ref name=fj1/> and the School of Management.<ref name=fj2>{{cite news|last1=Mostafavi|first1=Beata|title=University of Michigan-Flint business students to trade stocks in mini Wall Street center in Riverfront Residence Hall |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2011/07/university_of_michigan-flint_b_1.html|accessdate=October 19, 2015|work=Flint Journal|publisher=MLive Media Group|date=July 22, 2011}}</ref> Halo Burger returned to the campus in September 2002 only to be forced out due to on-campus housing food regulations in 2008.<ref name=\"mt\"/>\n\nRuth Person became chancellor in 2008.<ref name=fj3>{{cite news|last1=Thorne|first1=Blake Thorne|title=University of Michigan-Flint Chancellor Ruth Person says she will depart in 2014 |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2013/01/university_of_michigan-flint_c_16.html|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=January 23, 2013}}</ref> The first on-campus dorms, First Street Residence Hall, were completed in 2008.<ref name=fj1/> The University of Michigan\u2013Flint in 2010 was the fastest-growing public university in the state of Michigan.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/04/um-flint_keeps_rank_as_states.html | title=Flint Campus of the University of Michigan keeps rank as state's fastest growing university | publisher=M Live |date=April 15, 2010 | accessdate=October 20, 2010}}</ref>  The School of Management moved to a leased floor of the Riverfront Residence Hall in early 2013 from the White Building at renovation cost of $5.3 million.<ref name=fj2/> In 2013, Person's five-year term was up and was extended for a year by U of M President Mary Sue Coleman to 2014.<ref name=fj3/>\n\nIn August 2014, Sue Borrego began as Chancellor.<ref name=\"mlive41714\">{{Cite web| title = University of Michigan appoints Susan Borrego as Flint chancellor |author = Woodhouse, Kellie| work = MLive.com| date = April 17, 2014| accessdate = January 11, 2015| url = http://www.mlive.com/news/ann-arbor/index.ssf/2014/04/university_of_michigan_appoint_1.html}}</ref> On October 15, 2015, University Board of Regents approved the purchase of the 160,000-square-foot, 10-story north tower building of the [[Citizens Republic Bancorp#Citizens Banking Building|Citizens Banking Buildings]] from [[FirstMerit Bank]] for $6 million expected to close in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schuch|first1=Sarah|title=UM-Flint buys part of historic downtown bank building |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2015/10/um-flint_meeting.html|accessdate=October 20, 2015|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group |date=October 15, 2015}}</ref> In mid-December 2015, the Uptown Reinvestment Corporation donated the Riverfront Residence Hall and Banquet Center to the university with the [[Charles Stewart Mott Foundation]] forgiving the remaining redevelopment loan for the center.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackman |first1=Caresse |title=Uptown Reinvestment Corporation donates Riverfront Residence Hall Banquet Center to UM-Flint |url=http://www.abc12.com/news/headlines/Uptown-Reinvestment-Corporation-donates-Riverfront-Residence-Hall-Banquet-Center-to-UM-Flint-362846881.html |accessdate=December 30, 2015 |work=ABC12.com |publisher=WJRT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604114105/http://www.abc12.com/news/headlines/Uptown-Reinvestment-Corporation-donates-Riverfront-Residence-Hall-Banquet-Center-to-UM-Flint-362846881.html |archive-date=June 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On October 20, 2016, the Regents formed the School of Nursing from the Department of Nursing in the School of Health Professions and Studies.<ref>{{cite news|title=U of Michigan creates School of Nursing at Flint campus|url=http://www.abc12.com/content/news/U-of-Michigan-creates-School-of-Nursing-at-Flint-campus-397863791.html|accessdate=October 21, 2016|work=ABC12|publisher=WJRT|date=October 21, 2016}}</ref> The Harrison Street Annex, at Kearsley and Harrison Streets in the Harrison Street parking structure, has been remodeled to be the university's engineering design studio.<ref>{{cite news|title=UM-Flint Engineering celebrates change, growth |url=https://news.umflint.edu/2017/07/20/um-flint-engineering-celebrates-change-growth/ |accessdate=July 20, 2017|work= umflint.edu |publisher= UM-Flint |date=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:300px;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''College/school founding'''<ref name=\"fj4\" />\n|-\n| '''College/school''' || '''Year founded'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<hr>\n|-\n| College of Arts and Sciences || 1955\n|-\n| School of Management || 1975\n|-\n| College of Health Sciences || 1982\n|-\n| School of Education and Human Services || 1997\n|-\n| School of Nursing || 2016\n|}\n\nThere are 138 majors/concentrations that apply to 12 Bachelor's degrees and 43 graduate majors/concentrations. U of M-Flint also offers graduate degrees including master's degrees, Professional Doctorals, and Ph.D. degrees. The university's colleges and schools include the College of Arts and Sciences (CAS), College of Health Sciences (CHS), School of Education & Human Services (SEHS), School of Management (SOM) and School of Nursing (SON).\n\n===Rankings and accreditation===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| USNWR_NU = 293-381\n| Wamo_NU = 339\n}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR undergraduate rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR 2020 Rankings\">{{cite magazine|title=University of Michigan-Flint|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=September 27, 2019 |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-michigan-flint-2327}}</ref>\n|-\n| Top Performers on Social Mobility\n| 214\n|-\n| Engineering (no doctorate)\n| 110\n|-\n|}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR graduate rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Best Grad Schools\">{{cite magazine|title=University of Michigan-Flint|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=September 27, 2019 |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-graduate-schools/university-of-michigan-flint-171146}}</ref>\n|-\n| Nursing-Anesthesia\n| 22\n|-\n| Online Master's in Nursing\n| 53\n|-\n| Physical Therapy\n| 53\n|-\n| Best Public Affairs Program\n| 216\n|-\n| Part-time MBA\n| 127\n|-\n|}\n\n''[[The Princeton Review]]'' included U of M-Flint in the \"Best Midwestern\" category in their publication ''2020 Best Colleges: Region by Region''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.princetonreview.com/college-rankings?rankings=best-midwestern |title=Best Midwestern |accessdate=September 27, 2019 |author=Princeton Review}}</ref> They also included U of M-Flint's School of Management as one of the Best Business Schools in their 2017 publication.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.umflint.edu/2016/10/26/um-flint-school-management-makes-princeton-reviews-top-business-school-list/ |title=UM-Flint Makes Princeton Review\u2019s Top Business School List|accessdate=October 26, 2016 |author=UM-Flint}}</ref> The Part-Time MBA Program was ranked 41st in the United States (overall) and 9th in the Midwest (by region) in 2010 by Businessweek.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bwnt.businessweek.com/bschools/ptmba_rankings_2009/index.asp?sortCol=rankid&sortOrder=1&pageNum=1&resultNum=100 |title=The Top ranked part-time MBA Program |accessdate=November 10, 2009 |author=Business Week |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109194947/http://bwnt.businessweek.com/bschools/ptmba_rankings_2009/index.asp?sortCol=rankid&sortOrder=1&pageNum=1&resultNum=100 |archive-date=January 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nU of M-Flint is accredited by the Higher Learning Commission (HLC) of Colleges and Schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hlcommission.org/component/directory/?Itemid=&Action=ShowBasic&instid=1370|title=HLC Accreditation|accessdate=September 27, 2019 |author=HLC}}</ref> Program-level accreditation is maintained by many programs in affiliation with: the Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://main.abet.org/aps/AccreditedProgramsDetails.aspx?OrganizationID=892&ProgramIDs=|title=ABET-Accredited Programs|accessdate=September 27, 2019 |author=ABET}}</ref> the American Chemical Society, Association for the Accreditation of Human Research Protection Programs, the Association to Advance Collegiate School of Business \u2013 International,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://datadirect.aacsb.edu/public/profiles/profile.cfm?runReport=1&unitid=54729&userType=All|title=AACSB Accreditation|accessdate=December 22, 2008 |author=AACSB}}</ref> Association of University Programs in Health Administration, the Commission on Accreditation in Physical Therapy Education,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apta.org/AM/Template.cfm?section=CAPTE3&template=/aptaapps/accreditedschools/acc_schools_map.cfm&process=2&ProgramID=935|title=APTA Accreditation|accessdate=December 22, 2008|author=APTA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081130042314/http://www.apta.org/AM/Template.cfm?section=CAPTE3&template=%2Faptaapps%2Faccreditedschools%2Facc_schools_map.cfm&process=2&ProgramID=935|archive-date=November 30, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Commission on Accreditation in Respiratory Care, the Commission of Collegiate Nursing Education, the Council for Accreditation of Teacher Education, the Council on Accreditation for Nurse Anesthesia Educational Programs,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://webapps.aana.com/AccreditedPrograms/accreditedprograms.asp?State=MI&s8fid=112299292254 |title=AANA Accreditation |accessdate=December 22, 2008 |author=AANA |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517013325/http://webapps.aana.com/AccreditedPrograms/accreditedprograms.asp?State=MI&s8fid=112299292254 |archive-date=May 17, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> the Council on Social Work Education,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://portal.cswe.org/Membership/CompanyInformation.aspx?sqs=ELAVJ5Wc13dHesWOyxqWuP349NNLV1mL3np+8zK+5YILrOkVcgZL7az6NOC2vtyj23R1MNwbw/RxxIsxMWNENYtYm1/4kCxa2Ix7b7Z5woM/NTQyucNfE8yvKfwMmPghoD7ZdEAoSixVH1aslteY1NvCGV4N1u93KRlPposYimkzKm/znhknHJAwkOekTYrsE47v4Ka3QXJVzYg19jFiskoXm0e/orF6C7oDZZC3HjmL&addressnum=|title=CSWE Accreditation|accessdate=December 22, 2008 |author=CSWE}}</ref> the Joint Review Committee on Education in Radiologic Technology,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jrcert.org/cert/View.jsp?pid=0841 |title=JRCERT Accreditation |accessdate=December 22, 2008 |author=JRCERT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225015947/http://www.jrcert.org/cert/View.jsp?pid=0841 |archive-date=December 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Michigan Department of Education, the National Association for the Education of Young Children and the National Association of Schools of Music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nasm.arts-accredit.org/index.jsp?page=Member+Lists&memberId=2473bfa56624d11662c6c5adc0f3eb46|title=NASM Accreditation|accessdate=December 22, 2008|author=NASM|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090516234204/http://nasm.arts-accredit.org/index.jsp?page=Member+Lists&memberId=2473bfa56624d11662c6c5adc0f3eb46|archive-date=May 16, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Residential and student life==\n\n===On campus housing===\n[[File:University of Michigan\u2013Flint July 2018 1 (First Street Residence Hall).jpg|right|thumb|250px|The First Street Residence Hall, a modern building dormitory for students at the University of Michigan, Flint Campus]]\n\nIn November 2004, the [[Board of Regents of the University of Michigan]] approved the request of the Flint Campus to explore the feasibility of student housing. After several assessments, studies, and surveys showing the probable progression of growth of the campus, student housing was approved. On July 16, 2007, the first-ever student dormitory, the First Street Residence Hall, opened for students.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.umflint.edu/housing/july17_release.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304073842/http://www.umflint.edu/housing/july17_release.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Uptown Reinvestment Corporation donated the Riverfront Residence Hall, a privately owned high-rise building that houses both U of M-Flint and [[Baker College]] students, to the university.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Dominic |title=U-M Flint aims to grow international enrollment with Riverfront donation|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2015/12/um-flint_aims_to_grow_internat.html|website=MLive.com|publisher=MLive Media Group|accessdate=December 19, 2015}}</ref> The 16-story Residence Hall can house up to 500 students.\n\n===Student Organizations===\nThere are over 100 recognized student organizations and 8 Sponsored Student Organizations (SSOs). They are organizations for various academic departments, religions, and cultural backgrounds, as well as organizations for honors, club sports, social fraternities and sororities, service groups, and special interests.\n\n'''University sponsored organizations:'''\n*[[The Michigan Times]], the student newspaper of the University of Michigan\u2013Flint.\n*Black Student Union\n*Campus Activities Board\n*College Panhellenic Association\n*Interfraternity Council\n*[[National Pan-Hellenic Council]]\n*Qua Literacy and Fine Arts Magazine\n*Student Government\n\n===Greek Life===\nThe university is home to several [[fraternities and sororities]]:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.umflint.edu/sil/fraternity-and-sorority-life-0 |title=Fraternity and Sorority Life |accessdate=September 28, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Sororities:'''\n*[[Delta Sigma Theta]]\n*[[Sigma Gamma Rho]]\n*[[Zeta Phi Beta]]\n*[[Phi Sigma Sigma]]\n*[[Sigma Sigma Sigma]]\n*[[Theta Phi Alpha]]\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Fraternities:'''\n*[[Alpha Phi Alpha]]\n*[[Kappa Alpha Psi]]\n*[[Phi Beta Sigma]]\n*[[Alpha Sigma Phi]]\n*[[Kappa Sigma]]\n*[[Theta Chi]]{{Col-end}}\n\n[[File:University of Michigan\u2013Flint July 2018 7 (University Pavilion).jpg|thumb|University Pavilion]]\n===Radio station===\nThe school owns [[WFUM]] (91.1 FM), a [[public radio]] station affiliated with the [[Michigan Radio]] network.\n\n===Student newspaper===\n''[[The Michigan Times]]'' is a student-run campus newspaper.  In 2008, the Michigan Press Association's \"Better College Newspaper Contest\" awarded ''The Michigan Times'' with nine awards in a statewide competition. This achievement was surpassed in 2009 by winning 23 awards.<ref>{{cite web|last=Profitt|first=Jennifer|title=From the Editor's Desk: M-Times wins MPA awards|url=http://www.themichigantimes.com/2.11010/from-the-editor-s-desk-1.1531477|work=The Michigan Times|accessdate=October 20, 2009}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The newspaper is printed weekly and is available free-of-cost on campus, at other area colleges, in the surrounding downtown area and elsewhere in the Greater Flint area.\n\n===Student government===\nThe University of Michigan\u2013Flint Student Government represents the students and manages student funds on the campus. Student Government is a member of the statewide Association of Michigan Universities.\n\n==Athletics==\nU of M\u2013Flint does not offer varsity intercollegiate athletics, but there are a number of club sport teams and intramural sports leagues available to students. Teams have competed as Wolverines, while an unofficial student vote in 2009 selected [[The Victors]] to avoid confusion with the main campus.<ref name=\"FJ\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/index.ssf/2008/09/sports_talk_at_university_of_m.html |title=Sports talk at University of Michigan-Flint sparks more mascot consideration |accessdate=October 29, 2008 |last=Mostafavi |first=Beata |date=September 22, 2008 |work=[[Flint Journal]] |publisher=[[Booth Newspapers]] |location=Flint, Michigan |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517100159/http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/index.ssf/2008/09/sports_talk_at_university_of_m.html |archivedate=May 17, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=tmt>{{cite news|last=Shoup|first=Allison|title='Victors' not yet a sure thing|url=http://www.themichigantimes.com/index.php/article/2008/04/victors_not_yet_a_sure_thing|accessdate=April 9, 2012|newspaper=The Michigan Times|date=April 25, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812205405/http://www.themichigantimes.com/index.php/article/2008/04/victors_not_yet_a_sure_thing|archivedate=August 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Students, staff and alumni are also able to buy tickets to the flagship campus' sporting events at a discounted price.\n\nCurrent Club Sports include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umflint.edu/clubsports/team-directory|title=Team Directory {{!}} University of Michigan-Flint|website=www.umflint.edu|language=en-us|access-date=2018-07-03}}</ref>\n\n*Men's & Women's Basketball\n*Cheer\n*Men's Ice Hockey\n*Men's & Women's Soccer\n*Women's Volleyball\n*Softball\n\nIn 2013, the men's hockey team earned a spot in the [[American Collegiate Hockey Association|ACHA]] Division III National Tournament for the first time, eventually advancing to the National Championship Game against fellow [[Michigan Collegiate Hockey Conference]] foe [[Adrian College]]. In 2015, the women's hockey team went 18-0 in conference play.\n\n== Notable faculty and alumni ==\n* [[Jim Ananich]] \u2013 [[Michigan Senate]] Minority Leader\n* Shari Ballard \u2013 Former [[Best Buy]] Senior Executive VP <ref>{{cite web|title=UM-Flint Commencement Speaker is Alumna and Best Buy Exec|url=https://news.umflint.edu/2017/04/12/14578/|publisher=UM-Flint|accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[Deborah Cherry]] \u2013 Former Michigan State Senator\n* [[John D. Cherry]] \u2013 62nd [[Lieutenant Governor of Michigan]]<ref name=\"gbv\" />\n* [[Bobby Crim]] \u2013 Former Michigan Speaker of the House and State Representative and Founder of the [[Crim Festival of Races]]<ref name=\"gbv\" /> \n* [[Christopher Paul Curtis]] (2000) \u2013 Writer and [[Newbery Medal]] winner<ref name=\"gbv\" />\n* [[Erin Darke]] \u2013 Actress <ref>{{cite web|title=Alumna Erin Darke Finds Success on Stage and Screen|url=https://news.umflint.edu/2015/06/16/alumna-erin-darke-finds-success-on-stage-and-screen/|publisher=UM-Flint|accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Mona Haydar]] \u2013 Rapper, poet, activist and chaplain\n* [[LaKisha Jones]] \u2013 Singer, [[American Idol]] contestant\n* [[Michael Moore]] \u2013 Documentary film director, author<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Moore|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/103383/Michael-Moore/biography|work=Biography|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Don Riegle]] (1960) \u2013 [[United States Senator]] from Michigan<ref>{{cite web|title=Donald W. Riegle, Jr Archives |url=https://www.umflint.edu/archives/donald-w-riegle-jr|work=Biography |publisher=University of Michigan-Flint|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Marietta S. Robinson]] \u2013 Former Commissioner of the [[U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Marietta S. Robinson |url=http://www.cpsc.gov/en/About-CPSC/Commissioners/Marietta-Robinson/|work=Biography|publisher=U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[John Sinclair (poet)|John Sinclair]] (1964) \u2013 Poet, political activist<ref>http://libguides.umflint.edu/johnsinclair{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Tim Sneller]] \u2013 member of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] from the 50th district<ref name=house_sneller>[https://housedems.com/sneller \"Meet Tim Sneller\"]. housedems.com, November 9, 2019.</ref>\n* [[Woodrow Stanley]] \u2013 Former Michigan State Representative, Mayor of Flint\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Michigan Times]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n{{Flint, Michigan}}\n{{University of Michigan System}}\n{{Public universities in Michigan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University of Michigan-Flint}}\n[[Category:University of Michigan\u2013Flint| ]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan|*Flint]]\n[[Category:Education in Flint, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Genesee County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Public universities in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1956]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Flint, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Flint, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Flint, Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Naraht", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGreek Life:cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Michigan%E2%80%93Flint"}
{"title_page": "Humanitarian crisis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2013}}\nA '''humanitarian crisis''' (or \"humanitarian disaster\") is defined as a singular event or a series of events that are threatening in terms of health, safety or well being of a community or large group of people.<ref>[http://humanitariancoalition.ca/info-portal/factsheets/what-is-a-humanitarian-crisis \"What Is a Humanitarian Crisis\"], ''Humanitarian Coalition'', Retrieved on 6 May 2013.</ref> It may be an internal or external conflict and usually occurs throughout a large land area. Local, national and international responses are necessary in such events.<ref>\"Complex Humanitarian Emergency Program.\" EDUCATION & TRAINING.  <http://globalhealthsciences.ucsf.edu/education-training/complex-humanitarian-emergency-program {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509215421/http://globalhealthsciences.ucsf.edu/education-training/complex-humanitarian-emergency-program |date=9 May 2013 }}> Retrieved on 4 May 2013.</ref>\n\nEach humanitarian crisis is caused by different factors and as a result, each different humanitarian crisis requires a unique response targeted towards the specific sectors affected. This can result in either short-term or long-term damage. Humanitarian crises can either be natural disasters, man-made disasters or complex emergencies. In such cases, complex emergencies occur as a result of several factors or events that prevent a large group of people from accessing their fundamental needs, such as food, clean water or safe shelter.<ref>So experts exclude that to address such crises it is possible to deny essential goods or pledging any action not to alleviate the suffering: [https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/01/09/683533895/humanitarian-experts-debate-trumps-use-of-the-term-humanitarian-crisis Humanitarian Experts Debate Trump's Use Of The Term 'Humanitarian Crisis', NPR24, January 9, 2019].</ref>\n\nExamples of humanitarian crises include armed [[War|conflicts]], [[epidemic]]s, [[famine]], [[natural disaster]]s and other major emergencies.<ref>[http://culturalinquiry.anu.edu.au/sites/default/files/Humanitarian%20Workshop%20flyer.pdf \"Humanitarian workshop flyer\"], Retrieved on 7 May 2013.</ref> If such a crisis causes large movements of people it could also become a [[refugee crisis]]. For these reasons, humanitarian crises are often interconnected and complex and several national and international agencies play roles in the repercussions of the incidences.\n\n==Categories==\nThere is no simple categorization of humanitarian crises. Different communities and agencies tend to have definitions related to the concrete situations they face.  A local fire service will tend to focus on issues such as flooding and weather induced crises. Medical and health related organizations are naturally focused on sudden crises to the health of a community.\n\nAn ongoing or lingering [[pandemic]] may amount to a humanitarian crisis, especially where there are increasing levels of [[virulence]], or rates of [[infection]] as in the case of [[AIDS]], [[Influenzavirus A|bird flu]] or [[Tuberculosis]]. Major health-related problems such as [[cancer]], [[global warming]] typically require an accentuated or punctuated mass-event to justify a label of \"crisis\" or \"disaster\".\n\nThe [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC)]] lists categories which include different types of natural disasters, technological disasters (i.e. hazardous material spills, [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl-type]] of nuclear accidents, chemical explosions) and long-term man-made disasters related to \"civil strife, civil war and international war\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifrc.org/what/disasters/Types/|title=Page or file not found|work=ifrc.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Internationally, the humanitarian response sector has tended to distinguish between natural disasters and complex emergencies which are related to armed conflict and wars.<ref>[http://www.reliefweb.int/library/documents/ocha__orientation__handbook_on__.htm ''Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs'' handbook for complex emergencies]</ref>\n\n==Impacts==\n===Women's social status in humanitarian crises===\nSocially, women and children (mostly girls) receive a significantly decreased amount of attention in response to humanitarian crises. Women and children make up 3 quarters of refugees or displaced persons at risk post-crisis. A quarter of this population is of reproduction age and a fifth of this population is likely to be pregnant. In times of emergency and such crises, deaths associated with pregnancy, reproductive health, sexual violence and sexual exploitation increase drastically especially amongst females. During such emergencies, women lose access to family planning services, prenatal care, postpartum care and other health services. The heightened risk of female health and safety makes them vulnerable to disease, violence and death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unfpa.org/gender/emergency.htm|title=UNFPA \u2013 United Nations Population Fund  \u2013 Protecting Women in Emergency Situations|work=unfpa.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nNon-profit organizations such as the [[Women's Refugee Commission]] deal with aiding particularly women suffering from various types of humanitarian crises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://womensrefugeecommission.org/humanitarian-crises-around-the-world|title=Women's Refugee Commission \u2013 Humanitarian Crises Around the World|author=Matthew Mesa|work=womensrefugeecommission.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> According to the Women's Refugee Commission, during the first hours of a humanitarian crisis, women and young children are at most risk. During such an event, agencies and organizations approach matters variably. However, the top critical requirements within hours and months of the crises include: keeping the refugees and internally displaced persons away from danger, allowing access to fundamental needs such as food and healthcare, identification information, preventing sexual violence and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womensrefugeecommission.org/crisis/top-10-needs-facing-refugees|title=Women's Refugee Commission \u2013 Top 10 Needs Facing Refugees and Those Displaced in Emergencies|author=Caitlin Kelley|work=womensrefugeecommission.org|accessdate=9 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209171215/http://www.womensrefugeecommission.org/crisis/top-10-needs-facing-refugees|archive-date=9 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Socio-economic realities of humanitarian crises===\nEconomic issues can lead to humanitarian crises or humanitarian crises can lead to economic downfalls. If it occurs after a humanitarian crisis affects a nation, it is imperative to return the livelihoods in the economic settings of the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanitarianstudiesconference.org/index.php?id=2|title=Themes|work=humanitarianstudiesconference.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> One of the critical needs on the Women's Refugee Commission's list is providing education and economic opportunities in order to maintain the economic qualities of the region. It is done by using the skills of the displaced persons or refugees involved to provide them with opportunities to gain income.<ref name=\"unicef.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/nutrition/training/1.1/3.html|title=Humanitarian coordination \u2013 The international humanitarian system|work=unicef.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n\n===Environmental and ecological impacts===\nIn the cases of humanitarian crises, especially natural disasters such as tornadoes, tsunamis and earthquakes, these incidences leave environmental and ecological impacts on the regions affected. The aftermaths of natural disasters can lead to a significant decrease in natural resources while making the region prone to future issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urd.org/Environment-training-toolkit|title=Groupe URD \u2013 Trainer\u2019s Guide \"Integrating the Environment into Humanitarian Action and Early Recovery\"|work=urd.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> For example, if a forest fire occurs in a large region, the area may be susceptible to air pollution, dust clouds, release of carcinogenic gases and others. Forest ecological wildlife, for example, is severely impacted by such events. In the cases of water natural disasters such as floods and tsunamis, extensive damage due to the water is prevalent.<ref>http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2012/chapter-2-the-pre-travel-consultation/natural-disasters-and-environmental-hazards.htm</ref> Fish, corals and other ocean life is impacted, which further impacts the livelihoods of fishermen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/teacher_resources/webfieldtrips/natural_disasters/|title=WWF \u2013 Ecological Consequences of Natural Disasters: Tsunami|work=panda.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Sustainable solutions==\nThere is no singular solution to any one humanitarian crisis. Often, the primary cause of a humanitarian crisis is intertwined with several other factors. Further, one repercussion can lead to another which may lead to another. For instance, in the case of a flood, fish and ocean life is impacted, an environmental and ecological impact. This can further impact humans the source of income for fishermen, an economical impact. This causes the residents of this particular area to be stripped from their source of food and their culture of consuming sea fish. This can lead to women and children being forced to work in dangerous conditions to gain income and food, a social impact. Evidently, one crisis can have many impacts that are interconnected with one another and there is no single solution.  The [[Feinstein International Center]] at Tufts University works to understand and find solutions to the intersection of various factors that contribute to humanitarian crisis.\n\n==Preparing for humanitarian crises==\n\nDisaster preparedness is critical to building both national and international capacity to prevent, respond to, and recover from humanitarian emergencies. Disaster preparedness activities can be categorized into material preparedness (building to code, avoiding building in hazardous areas, strengthening homes, preparing emergency kits, etc.) and into behavioral preparedness (training, early warning, disaster insurance, etc.).  The international community possesses five key to key entities for guidance programming, research, and funding for disaster preparedness capacity-building:\n\n* '''United Nations Office for Disaster Risk Reduction:''' The United Nations Office for Disaster Risk Reduction implements the [https://www.unisdr.org/ United Nations International Strategy for Disaster Reduction (UNISDR)]. The UNISDR, led by the United Nations Special Representative of the Secretary General for Disaster Risk Reduction, serves, \u201c\u2026as the focal point in the United Nations system for the coordination of disaster reduction and to ensure synergies among disaster reduction activities\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unisdr.org/who-we-are|title=Who we are - UNDRR|website=www.unisdr.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> A component of UNISDR work is implementation of the [https://www.unisdr.org/we/coordinate/sendai-framework Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction 2015\u20132030].<ref name=\":0\" />\n* '''[http://www.ifrc.org/en/who-we-are/ International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC)]:''' The IFRC operates around the globe and across all phases of the [https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/en/programme-cycle/space humanitarian programme cycle], helping affected nations by working with member National Societies and the international community to prepare for, respond to, and recover from \u201c\u2026natural and man-made disasters in non-conflict situations.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buildingabetterresponse.org/|title=Building a Better Response|website=www.buildingabetterresponse.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n* '''[https://www.unocha.org/about-us/who-we-are Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA)]:''' OCHA is a United Nations office, \u201c\u2026responsible for bringing together humanitarian actors to ensure a coherent response to emergencies.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unocha.org/about-us/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|date=2016-09-27|website=OCHA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> OCHA's leader operates as both the Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs and as the Emergency Relief Coordinator, advocating for increased awareness of, preparedness for, and response to humanitarian emergencies worldwide.<ref name=\":1\" /> As the Emergency Relief Coordinator, the OCHA lead also chairs the Inter-Agency Standing Committee.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* '''[https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/ Inter-Agency Standing Committee (IASC)]:''' The IASC provides a forum for both UN-affiliated and non-UN-affiliated organizations to coordinate action regarding humanitarian policies, advocacy, and response evaluation and improvement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/about-iasc-0|title=About the Inter-Agency Standing Committee {{!}} IASC|website=interagencystandingcommittee.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> In 2005, the IASC released its [https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/iasc-transformative-agenda Transformative Agenda] with 10 protocols to, \u201c\u2026improve the effectiveness of humanitarian response through greater predictability, accountability, responsibility and partnership\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/iasc-transformative-agenda|title=IASC Transformative Agenda {{!}} IASC|website=interagencystandingcommittee.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> [https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/system/files/common_framework_for_preparedness.pdf Protocol 8: \u201cCommon Framework for Preparedness\u201d] and [https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/en/coordination/preparedness/erp-approach Protocol 9: \u201dEmergency Response Preparedness\u201d] provide guidance countries and humanitarians can implement for risk assessment and preparedness planning. Additionally, IASC also oversees global humanitarian clusters as a part of the Cluster Approach.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/en/about-clusters/what-is-the-cluster-approach|title=What is the Cluster Approach? {{!}} HumanitarianResponse|website=www.humanitarianresponse.info|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n* '''[https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/en/about-clusters/what-is-the-cluster-approach Global Clusters]:''' To aid coordination during the humanitarian programme cycle, the UN established the Cluster Approach. Clusters are groups of humanitarian organizations with explicit responsibilities for coordinating action within each humanitarian sector.<ref name=\":2\" /> Preparedness is fundamental to the Cluster Approach, with leaders within each global cluster working to build international capacity by developing standards, setting policy, and sharing leading practices for their sector before a humanitarian emergency occurs.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn addition to these five disaster preparedness entities, there is a multiplicity of government donor agencies that fund disaster preparedness activities, including the [https://www.usaid.gov/ United States Agency for International Development (USAID)], the [https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development United Kingdom\u2019s Department for International Development (DFID)], the [https://www.sida.se/English/ Swedish International Development Cooperation Agency (SIDA)], and others. Additionally, there many philanthropies that support disaster preparedness, such as the [https://www.gatesfoundation.org/What-We-Do/Global-Development/Emergency-Response Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Aid agency]]\n*[[Central Emergency Response Fund]]\n*[[Emergency management]]\n*[[Human security]]\n*[[Humanitarian aid]]\n*[[Humanitarian intervention]]\n*[[International humanitarian law]]\n*[[List of droughts]]\n*[[List of epidemics]]\n*[[List of natural disasters by death toll]]\n*[[Outline of war]]\n*[[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/pop_ups/08/south_asia_sri_lanka_refugees/html/2.stm BBC Report on humanitarian crises in Sri Lanka, April 2009]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081228162119/http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/publications/reports/2006/top10_2005.html The 10 Most Underreported Humanitarian Crises of 2005] by [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Doctors Without Borders]]\n*[http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/publications/reports/2007/top10_2006.htm The 10 Most Underreported Humanitarian Crises of 2006] by [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Doctors Without Borders]]\n*[http://udspace.udel.edu/handle/19716/620 Technological and Natural Disasters and Ecological Problems: Similarities and Differences in Planning for and Managing Them]\n* [http://www.fao.org/emergencies/emergency-types/hazard-and-emergency-types/en/ Hazard and emergency types]\n* [http://www.fao.org/emergencies/resources/documents/resources-detail/en/c/157579/ Resilient Livelihoods: Disaster Risk Reduction for Food and Nutrition Security \u2013 2013 edition]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Humanitarian Crisis}}\n[[Category:Humanitarian aid|*]]\n[[Category:Emergency management]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2013}}\nA '''humanitarian crisis''' (or \"humanitarian disaster\") is defined as a singular event or a series of events that are threatening in terms of health, safety or well being of a community or large group of people.<ref>[http://humanitariancoalition.ca/info-portal/factsheets/what-is-a-humanitarian-crisis \"What Is a Humanitarian Crisis\"], ''Humanitarian Coalition'', Retrieved on 6 May 2013.</ref> It may be an internal or external conflict and usually occurs throughout a large land area. Local, national and international responses are necessary in such events.<ref>\"Complex Humanitarian Emergency Program.\" EDUCATION & TRAINING.  <http://globalhealthsciences.ucsf.edu/education-training/complex-humanitarian-emergency-program {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509215421/http://globalhealthsciences.ucsf.edu/education-training/complex-humanitarian-emergency-program |date=9 May 2013 }}> Retrieved on 4 May 2013.</ref>\n\nEach humanitarian crisis is caused by different factors and as a result, each different humanitarian crisis requires a unique response targeted towards the specific sectors affected. This can result in either short-term or long-term damage. Humanitarian crises can either be natural disasters, man-made disasters or complex emergencies. In such cases, complex emergencies occur as a result of several factors or events that prevent a large group of people from accessing their fundamental needs, such as food, clean water or safe shelter.<ref>So experts exclude that to address such crises it is possible to deny essential goods or pledging any action not to alleviate the suffering: [https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/01/09/683533895/humanitarian-experts-debate-trumps-use-of-the-term-humanitarian-crisis Humanitarian Experts Debate Trump's Use Of The Term 'Humanitarian Crisis', NPR24, January 9, 2019].</ref>\n\nExamples of humanitarian crises include armed [[War|conflicts]], [[epidemic]]s, [[famine]], [[natural disaster]]s and other major emergencies.<ref>[http://culturalinquiry.anu.edu.au/sites/default/files/Humanitarian%20Workshop%20flyer.pdf \"Humanitarian workshop flyer\"], Retrieved on 7 May 2013.</ref> If such a crisis causes large movements of people it could also become a [[refugee crisis]]. For these reasons, humanitarian crises are often interconnected and complex and several national and international agencies play roles in the repercussions of the incidences.\n\n==Categories==\nThere is no simple categorization of humanitarian crises. Different communities and agencies tend to have definitions related to the concrete situations they face.  A local fire service will tend to focus on issues such as flooding and weather induced crises. Medical and health related organizations are naturally focused on sudden crises to the health of a community.\n\nAn ongoing or lingering [[pandemic]] may amount to a humanitarian crisis, especially where there are increasing levels of [[virulence]], or rates of [[infection]] as in the case of [[AIDS]], [[Influenzavirus A|bird flu]] or [[Tuberculosis]]. Major health-related problems such as [[cancer]], [[global warming]] typically require an accentuated or punctuated mass-event to justify a label of \"crisis\" or \"disaster\".\n\nThe [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC)]] lists categories which include different types of natural disasters, technological disasters (i.e. hazardous material spills, [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl-type]] of nuclear accidents, chemical explosions) and long-term man-made disasters related to \"civil strife, civil war and international war\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifrc.org/what/disasters/Types/|title=Page or file not found|work=ifrc.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Internationally, the humanitarian response sector has tended to distinguish between natural disasters and complex emergencies which are related to armed conflict and wars.<ref>[http://www.reliefweb.int/library/documents/ocha__orientation__handbook_on__.htm ''Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs'' handbook for complex emergencies]</ref>\n\n==Impacts==\n===Women's social status in humanitarian crises===\nSocially, women and children (mostly girls) receive a significantly decreased amount of attention in response to humanitarian crises. Women and children make up 3 quarters of refugees or displaced persons at risk post-crisis. A quarter of this population is of reproduction age and a fifth of this population is likely to be pregnant. In times of emergency and such crises, deaths associated with pregnancy, reproductive health, sexual violence and sexual exploitation increase drastically especially amongst females. During such emergencies, women lose access to family planning services, prenatal care, postpartum care and other health services. The heightened risk of female health and safety makes them vulnerable to disease, violence and death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unfpa.org/gender/emergency.htm|title=UNFPA \u2013 United Nations Population Fund  \u2013 Protecting Women in Emergency Situations|work=unfpa.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nNon-profit organizations such as the [[Women's Refugee Commission]] deal with aiding particularly women suffering from various types of humanitarian crises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://womensrefugeecommission.org/humanitarian-crises-around-the-world|title=Women's Refugee Commission \u2013 Humanitarian Crises Around the World|author=Matthew Mesa|work=womensrefugeecommission.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> According to the Women's Refugee Commission, during the first hours of a humanitarian crisis, women and young children are at most risk. During such an event, agencies and organizations approach matters variably. However, the top critical requirements within hours and months of the crises include: keeping the refugees and internally displaced persons away from danger, allowing access to fundamental needs such as food and healthcare, identification information, preventing sexual violence and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womensrefugeecommission.org/crisis/top-10-needs-facing-refugees|title=Women's Refugee Commission \u2013 Top 10 Needs Facing Refugees and Those Displaced in Emergencies|author=Caitlin Kelley|work=womensrefugeecommission.org|accessdate=9 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209171215/http://www.womensrefugeecommission.org/crisis/top-10-needs-facing-refugees|archive-date=9 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Socio-economic realities of humanitarian crises===\nEconomic issues can lead to humanitarian crises or humanitarian crises can lead to economic downfalls. If it occurs after a humanitarian crisis affects a nation, it is imperative to return the livelihoods in the economic settings of the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanitarianstudiesconference.org/index.php?id=2|title=Themes|work=humanitarianstudiesconference.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> One of the critical needs on the Women's Refugee Commission's list is providing education and economic opportunities in order to maintain the economic qualities of the region. It is done by using the skills of the displaced persons or refugees involved to provide them with opportunities to gain income.<ref name=\"unicef.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/nutrition/training/1.1/3.html|title=Humanitarian coordination \u2013 The international humanitarian system|work=unicef.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIf it occurs as a cause of humanitarian crisis, the society would have been in a state of civil insecurity and economic shortfalls, which could cause the government to collapse. This can also result from food insecurity, famines, corruptions and various other issues. Direct effects of this situation include human rights violations, violence and mass murders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.odihpn.org/humanitarian-exchange-magazine/issue-40/conflict-economic-crisis-and-drought-a-humanitarian-emergency-out-of-control|title=Conflict, economic crisis and drought a humanitarian emergency out of control \u2013 Humanitarian Practice Network|work=odihpn.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Environmental and ecological impacts===\nIn the cases of humanitarian crises, especially natural disasters such as tornadoes, tsunamis and earthquakes, these incidences leave environmental and ecological impacts on the regions affected. The aftermaths of natural disasters can lead to a significant decrease in natural resources while making the region prone to future issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urd.org/Environment-training-toolkit|title=Groupe URD \u2013 Trainer\u2019s Guide \"Integrating the Environment into Humanitarian Action and Early Recovery\"|work=urd.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> For example, if a forest fire occurs in a large region, the area may be susceptible to air pollution, dust clouds, release of carcinogenic gases and others. Forest ecological wildlife, for example, is severely impacted by such events. In the cases of water natural disasters such as floods and tsunamis, extensive damage due to the water is prevalent.<ref>http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2012/chapter-2-the-pre-travel-consultation/natural-disasters-and-environmental-hazards.htm</ref> Fish, corals and other ocean life is impacted, which further impacts the livelihoods of fishermen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/teacher_resources/webfieldtrips/natural_disasters/|title=WWF \u2013 Ecological Consequences of Natural Disasters: Tsunami|work=panda.org|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Sustainable solutions==\nThere is no singular solution to any one humanitarian crisis. Often, the primary cause of a humanitarian crisis is intertwined with several other factors. Further, one repercussion can lead to another which may lead to another. For instance, in the case of a flood, fish and ocean life is impacted, an environmental and ecological impact. This can further impact humans the source of income for fishermen, an economical impact. This causes the residents of this particular area to be stripped from their source of food and their culture of consuming sea fish. This can lead to women and children being forced to work in dangerous conditions to gain income and food, a social impact. Evidently, one crisis can have many impacts that are interconnected with one another and there is no single solution.  The [[Feinstein International Center]] at Tufts University works to understand and find solutions to the intersection of various factors that contribute to humanitarian crisis.\n\n==Preparing for humanitarian crises==\n\nDisaster preparedness is critical to building both national and international capacity to prevent, respond to, and recover from humanitarian emergencies. Disaster preparedness activities can be categorized into material preparedness (building to code, avoiding building in hazardous areas, strengthening homes, preparing emergency kits, etc.) and into behavioral preparedness (training, early warning, disaster insurance, etc.).  The international community possesses five key to key entities for guidance programming, research, and funding for disaster preparedness capacity-building:\n\n* '''United Nations Office for Disaster Risk Reduction:''' The United Nations Office for Disaster Risk Reduction implements the [https://www.unisdr.org/ United Nations International Strategy for Disaster Reduction (UNISDR)]. The UNISDR, led by the United Nations Special Representative of the Secretary General for Disaster Risk Reduction, serves, \u201c\u2026as the focal point in the United Nations system for the coordination of disaster reduction and to ensure synergies among disaster reduction activities\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unisdr.org/who-we-are|title=Who we are - UNDRR|website=www.unisdr.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> A component of UNISDR work is implementation of the [https://www.unisdr.org/we/coordinate/sendai-framework Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction 2015\u20132030].<ref name=\":0\" />\n* '''[http://www.ifrc.org/en/who-we-are/ International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC)]:''' The IFRC operates around the globe and across all phases of the [https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/en/programme-cycle/space humanitarian programme cycle], helping affected nations by working with member National Societies and the international community to prepare for, respond to, and recover from \u201c\u2026natural and man-made disasters in non-conflict situations.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buildingabetterresponse.org/|title=Building a Better Response|website=www.buildingabetterresponse.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n* '''[https://www.unocha.org/about-us/who-we-are Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA)]:''' OCHA is a United Nations office, \u201c\u2026responsible for bringing together humanitarian actors to ensure a coherent response to emergencies.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unocha.org/about-us/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|date=2016-09-27|website=OCHA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> OCHA's leader operates as both the Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs and as the Emergency Relief Coordinator, advocating for increased awareness of, preparedness for, and response to humanitarian emergencies worldwide.<ref name=\":1\" /> As the Emergency Relief Coordinator, the OCHA lead also chairs the Inter-Agency Standing Committee.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* '''[https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/ Inter-Agency Standing Committee (IASC)]:''' The IASC provides a forum for both UN-affiliated and non-UN-affiliated organizations to coordinate action regarding humanitarian policies, advocacy, and response evaluation and improvement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/about-iasc-0|title=About the Inter-Agency Standing Committee {{!}} IASC|website=interagencystandingcommittee.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> In 2005, the IASC released its [https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/iasc-transformative-agenda Transformative Agenda] with 10 protocols to, \u201c\u2026improve the effectiveness of humanitarian response through greater predictability, accountability, responsibility and partnership\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/iasc-transformative-agenda|title=IASC Transformative Agenda {{!}} IASC|website=interagencystandingcommittee.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> [https://interagencystandingcommittee.org/system/files/common_framework_for_preparedness.pdf Protocol 8: \u201cCommon Framework for Preparedness\u201d] and [https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/en/coordination/preparedness/erp-approach Protocol 9: \u201dEmergency Response Preparedness\u201d] provide guidance countries and humanitarians can implement for risk assessment and preparedness planning. Additionally, IASC also oversees global humanitarian clusters as a part of the Cluster Approach.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/en/about-clusters/what-is-the-cluster-approach|title=What is the Cluster Approach? {{!}} HumanitarianResponse|website=www.humanitarianresponse.info|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n* '''[https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/en/about-clusters/what-is-the-cluster-approach Global Clusters]:''' To aid coordination during the humanitarian programme cycle, the UN established the Cluster Approach. Clusters are groups of humanitarian organizations with explicit responsibilities for coordinating action within each humanitarian sector.<ref name=\":2\" /> Preparedness is fundamental to the Cluster Approach, with leaders within each global cluster working to build international capacity by developing standards, setting policy, and sharing leading practices for their sector before a humanitarian emergency occurs.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn addition to these five disaster preparedness entities, there is a multiplicity of government donor agencies that fund disaster preparedness activities, including the [https://www.usaid.gov/ United States Agency for International Development (USAID)], the [https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development United Kingdom\u2019s Department for International Development (DFID)], the [https://www.sida.se/English/ Swedish International Development Cooperation Agency (SIDA)], and others. Additionally, there many philanthropies that support disaster preparedness, such as the [https://www.gatesfoundation.org/What-We-Do/Global-Development/Emergency-Response Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Aid agency]]\n*[[Central Emergency Response Fund]]\n*[[Emergency management]]\n*[[Human security]]\n*[[Humanitarian aid]]\n*[[Humanitarian intervention]]\n*[[International humanitarian law]]\n*[[List of droughts]]\n*[[List of epidemics]]\n*[[List of natural disasters by death toll]]\n*[[Outline of war]]\n*[[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/pop_ups/08/south_asia_sri_lanka_refugees/html/2.stm BBC Report on humanitarian crises in Sri Lanka, April 2009]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081228162119/http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/publications/reports/2006/top10_2005.html The 10 Most Underreported Humanitarian Crises of 2005] by [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Doctors Without Borders]]\n*[http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/publications/reports/2007/top10_2006.htm The 10 Most Underreported Humanitarian Crises of 2006] by [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Doctors Without Borders]]\n*[http://udspace.udel.edu/handle/19716/620 Technological and Natural Disasters and Ecological Problems: Similarities and Differences in Planning for and Managing Them]\n* [http://www.fao.org/emergencies/emergency-types/hazard-and-emergency-types/en/ Hazard and emergency types]\n* [http://www.fao.org/emergencies/resources/documents/resources-detail/en/c/157579/ Resilient Livelihoods: Disaster Risk Reduction for Food and Nutrition Security \u2013 2013 edition]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Humanitarian Crisis}}\n[[Category:Humanitarian aid|*]]\n[[Category:Emergency management]]\n", "name_user": "66.25.41.88", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Took out a paragraph that made it a little hard to understand)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humanitarian_crisis"}
{"title_page": "University of Kentucky", "text_new": "{{short description|Public research university in Lexington, KY, USA}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Coord|38|02|N|84|30|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = University of Kentucky\n| image = University of Kentucky seal.svg\n| image_upright = .65\n| latin_name = Universitas Kentuckiensis\n| motto =  United We Stand, Divided We Fall\n| established = {{start date and age|1865}}\n| type = [[Flagship campus|Flagship]]<br />[[Public University|Public]]<br />[[Land-grant University|Land-grant]]\n| academic_affiliations = [[Association of Public and Land-Grant Universities|APLU]]<br />[[Oak Ridge Associated Universities|ORAU]]<br />[[Southeastern Universities Research Association|SURA]]\n| endowment = $1.407 billion (2019)<ref name=endowment>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-Endowment-Market-Values--Final-Feb-10.ashx? |title=U.S. and Canadian 2019 NTSE Participating Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2019 Endowment Market Value, and Percentage Change in Market Value from FY18 to FY19 (Revised) |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| president = [[Eli Capilouto]]\n| provost = David W. Blackwell\n|students = 29,182 (2019)<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=University+of+Kentucky&s=all&id=157085|title=College Navigator - University of Kentucky|website=nces.ed.gov|access-date=August 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123123459/https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=university+of+kentucky&s=all&id=157085|archive-date=November 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| undergrad = 22,136  (2019)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| postgrad = 7046 (2019)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| staff = 13,145  [[Full-time equivalent|FTE]] (2015-2016)<ref name=\"booklet\">[http://www.uky.edu/iraa/sites/www.uky.edu.iraa/files/fact_booklet1516.pdf ''UK Fact Booklet 2015-2016''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014101920/http://www.uky.edu/iraa/sites/www.uky.edu.iraa/files/fact_booklet1516.pdf |date=October 14, 2016 }} (PDF). University of Kentucky. 2016. Retrieved on October 7, 2016</ref>\n| city = [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]]\n| state = [[Kentucky]]\n| country = United States\n| campus = [[Urban area|Urban]], {{convert|784|acre|km2}}<ref name=\"FACTBOOK_0607\">{{cite web | publisher=University of Kentucky | title=Fact Booklet 2006\u20132007 | year=2006 | url=http://www.uky.edu/OPIE/FactBooklet0607.pdf |format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070221130217/http://www.uky.edu/OPIE/FactBooklet0607.pdf|archivedate=February 21, 2007}}</ref>\n| colors = Blue and White<ref>{{cite book|title=Primary Color Palette|url=https://issuu.com/universityofkentucky/docs/graphic_standards_a16-7/6|publisher=University of Kentucky|work=UK Graphic Standards|date=April 6, 2016|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref><br />{{college color boxes|Kentucky Wildcats}}\n| sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division I]] \u2013 [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]\n| nickname = [[Kentucky Wildcats|Wildcats]]\n| mascot = \"The Wildcat,\" \"Scratch\"<ref name=\"UK TRAD\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukathletics.com/trads/mascot.html |title=Kentucky Wildcats Official Athletic Site - Traditions |publisher=Ukathletics.com |accessdate=December 3, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119015528/http://www.ukathletics.com/trads/mascot.html |archive-date=November 19, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|www.uky.edu}}\n| logo = University of Kentucky logo.svg\n| logo_upright = 1.1\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Kentucky''' ('''UK''') is a [[state university (U.S.)|public]] university in [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. Founded in 1865 by [[John Bryan Bowman]] as the '''Agricultural and Mechanical College of Kentucky''',<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/> the university is one of the state's two [[land-grant university|land-grant universities]] (the other being [[Kentucky State University]]) and the institution with the highest enrollment in the state, with 30,720<ref name=\"booklet\"/> students as of Fall 2015.\n\nThe institution comprises 16 colleges, a [[graduate school]], 93 [[undergraduate]] programs, 99 [[master's degrees|master programs]], 66 [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctoral]] programs, and four professional programs.<ref name=\"UKS_06\">{{cite web | title=Consolidated Financial Statements | date=June 30, 2006 | publisher=University of Kentucky | url=http://www.uky.edu/Home/AnnualReport/2006_UK_Consolidated_Statement_with_cover.pdf | format=PDF | access-date=June 12, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615130815/http://www.uky.edu/Home/AnnualReport/2006_UK_Consolidated_Statement_with_cover.pdf | archive-date=June 15, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=Stale cite may be suppressing current actual numbers.|date=February 2017}} The University of Kentucky has fifteen libraries on campus. The largest is the [[William T. Young Library]], a federal depository, hosting subjects related to [[social sciences]], [[humanities]], and [[life sciences]] collections. In recent years, the university has focused expenditures increasingly on research, following a compact formed by the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] in 1997. The directive mandated that the university become a ''Top 20'' public research institution, in terms of an overall ranking, to be determined by the university itself, by the year 2020.<ref name=\"TOP20_why\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===University origins===\nIn the early commonwealth of Kentucky, higher education was limited to a number of children from prominent families, disciplined apprentices, and those young men seeking entry into clerical, legal, and medical professions. As the first university in the territory that would become Kentucky, [[Transylvania University]] was the primary center for education, and became the forerunner of what would become the University of Kentucky.\n\n[[File:Barker Hall.jpg|thumb|left|The early campus: Barker Hall in the center, the Main Building to the right, and a lake in the foreground where the Student Center was later built.]]\n\n[[John Bryan Bowman]] founded the Agricultural and Mechanical College of Kentucky (A&M), a publicly chartered department of Kentucky University, after receiving federal support through the [[Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act]] in 1865.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\">{{cite web | title=A Brief History of the University of Kentucky | publisher=University of Kentucky | url=http://www.uky.edu/CampusGuide/uk-history.html | accessdate=January 6, 2012 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6AjVMlfoS?url=http://www.uky.edu/CampusGuide/uk-history.html | archive-date=September 17, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Courses were offered at [[Ashland, The Henry Clay Estate]].<ref name=\"UKChron\" /> Three years later, [[James Kennedy Patterson]] became the first president of the land-grant university and the first degree was awarded. In 1876, the university began to offer [[master's degree]] programs. Two years later, A&M separated from Kentucky University, which is now [[Transylvania University]].<ref name=\"UKChron\">{{cite web | title=A Chronology of UK | publisher=University of Kentucky Special Collections & Digital Programs Division | date=January 2, 2008 | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | url=http://www.uky.edu/Libraries/libpage.php?lweb_id=311&llib_id=13 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220222212/http://www.uky.edu/Libraries/libpage.php?lweb_id=311&llib_id=13 | archive-date=February 20, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> For the new school, Lexington donated a {{Convert|52|acre|m2|adj=on}} park and fair ground, which became the core of UK's present campus.<ref name=\"UKChron\" /> A&M was initially a male-only institution, but began to admit women in 1880.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/>\n\nIn 1892, the official colors of the university, royal blue and white, were adopted. An earlier color set, blue and light yellow, was adopted earlier at a Kentucky-[[Centre College]] football game on December 19, 1891.<ref name=\"UK TRAD\">{{cite web | title=University of Kentucky Traditions and songs | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | publisher=University of Kentucky | url=http://www.uky.edu/UKHome/subpages/traditions.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711073947/http://www.uky.edu/UKHome/subpages/traditions.html | archive-date=July 11, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> The particular hue of blue was determined from a necktie, which was used to demonstrate the color of royal blue.<ref name=\"UK TRAD\"/>\n\nOn February 15, 1882, [[Main Building (University of Kentucky)|Administration Building]] was the first building of three completed on the present campus.<ref name=\"UKChron\" /> Three years later, the college formed the Agricultural Experiment Station, which researches issues relating to agribusiness, food processing, nutrition, water and soil resources and the environment.<ref name=\"AES\">{{cite web | title=agResearch | publisher=University of Kentucky College of Agriculture | year=2007 | accessdate=January 7, 2007 | url=http://www.ca.uky.edu/research/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516232453/http://www.ca.uky.edu/research/ | archive-date=May 16, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> This was followed up by the creation of the university's ''Agricultural Extension Service'' in 1910, which was one of the first in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"UK_HIS2\">{{cite web | title=History Briefs | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=May 23, 2007 | url=http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/history2.html | access-date=June 12, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613040216/http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/history2.html | archive-date=June 13, 2007 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Cooperative extension service|extension service]] became a model of the federally mandated programs that were required beginning in 1914.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/>\n\n===Coeducational school: modern period===\n\n[[File:Patterson Hall 1905.jpg|thumb|Patterson Hall, shortly after its 1904 opening]]\nPatterson Hall, the school's first women's dormitory, was constructed in 1904. Residents had to cross a [[swamp]]y depression, where the now demolished Student Center later stood, to reach central campus.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/> Four years later, the school's name was changed to the \"State University, Lexington, Kentucky\" upon reaching [[university]] status, and then to the \"University of Kentucky\" in 1916.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/> The university led to the creation of the College of Home Economics in 1916, and [[Mary E. Sweeney]] was promoted from chair of the Department of Home Economics to Dean of the College. (Later renamed the College of Human Environmental Sciences, this educational unit was folded into the College of Agriculture in 2003 as the School of Human Environmental Sciences<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ca.uky.edu/hes/?p=12|title=Human Environmental Sciences|website=UK College of Agriculture, Food and Environment|accessdate=August 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011041102/http://www2.ca.uky.edu/hes/?p=12|archive-date=October 11, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>). The College of Commerce was established in 1925, known today as the [[Gatton College of Business and Economics]].<ref name=\"UK_HIS2\"/>\n\nIn 1929, [[Memorial Hall (University of Kentucky)|Memorial Hall]] was completed, dedicated to the 2,756 Kentuckians who died in [[World War I]].<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> This was followed up by the new [[Margaret I. King Library|King Library]], which opened in 1931 and was named for a long-time library director, Margaret I. King.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> The university's graduate and professional programs became racially integrated in 1949 when [[Lyman T. Johnson]], an [[African American]], won a lawsuit to be admitted to the graduate program.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/markers/DesegregationJohnson1.html | title=Desegregation of UK - Historical Marker | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626201234/http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/markers/DesegregationJohnson1.html | archive-date=June 26, 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.uky.edu/PR/News/Archives/1999/APRIL99/johnsondedi.htm | title=UK DEDICATES HISTORICAL MARKER FOR 50 YEARS OF AFRICAN AMERICANS | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=April 22, 1999 | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731124208/http://www.uky.edu/PR/News/Archives/1999/APRIL99/johnsondedi.htm | archive-date=July 31, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> African Americans would not be allowed to attend as undergraduates until 1954, following the US Supreme Court's [[Brown v. Board of Education]] decision.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ket.org/civilrights/timeline.htm | title=A Kentucky Civil Rights Timeline | accessdate=August 8, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807135415/http://www.ket.org/civilrights/timeline.htm | archive-date=August 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1939, Governor Happy Chandler appointed the first woman trustee on the University of Kentucky Board of Trustees, Georgia M. Blazer of Ashland.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://kdl.kyvl.org/catalog/xt7d251fjp5f_1 | title= Minutes of Mrs. Blazer's first Regular Meeting of the Board of Trustees, University of Kentucky, April 4, 1939 | access-date= December 12, 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141214045751/http://kdl.kyvl.org/catalog/xt7d251fjp5f_1 | archive-date= December 14, 2014 | url-status= live }}</ref> She served from 1939 to 1960. In 1962, Blazer Hall was opened as the Georgia M Blazer Hall [dormitory] for Women in tribute to her twenty-one years of service as a University of Kentucky trustee.<ref name=BlazerMinutes>{{cite web | url= http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7hmg7frh2j_48 | title= Minutes of Regular Meeting of the Board of Trustees, University of Kentucky, President Dickey's  recommendation and the Board's approval in the naming of the \"Georgia M. Blazer Hall\" dormitory for women, (pages 48 & 49), June 4, 1962 | access-date= December 12, 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141213020532/http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7hmg7frh2j_48 | archive-date= December 13, 2014 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nGround was broken for the Albert B. Chandler Hospital in 1955, when Governor of Kentucky [[Happy Chandler]] recommended that the Kentucky General Assembly appropriate $5 million for the creation of the University of Kentucky College of Medicine and a medical center at the university.<ref name=\"GB_053007\">{{ cite news | title=Officials Break Ground on New UK Albert B. Chandler Hospital | first=Amanda | last=Nelson | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=May 30, 2007 | url=http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=2334 | access-date=July 25, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830233415/http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=2334 | archive-date=August 30, 2007 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> This was completed after a series of studies were conducted that highlighted the health needs of the citizens, as well as the need to train more physicians for the state. Five years later, the [[University of Kentucky College of Medicine|College of Medicine]] and [[University of Kentucky College of Nursing|College of Nursing]] opened, followed by the [[University of Kentucky College of Dentistry|College of Dentistry]] in 1962.<ref name=\"UK_HIS2\"/>\n\nNine years after the founding of The Northern Extension Center in Covington, representing the Ashland Independent School Board of Education,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7gqn5z6j5s_25 | title=Minutes of the Meeting of the Board of Trustees of the University of Kentucky, Ashland Delegation Heard on request for off-campus University of Kentucky Center April 2, 1957 | access-date=March 11, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402141712/http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7gqn5z6j5s_25 | archive-date=April 2, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> Ashland attorney Henderson Dysard and [[Ashland Inc.|Ashland Oil & Refining Company]] founder and CEO [[Paul G. Blazer]] presented a proposal to President Dickey and the University of Kentucky Board of Trustees for the university to take over the day-to-day operations and curriculum of the Ashland [municipal] Junior College, creating the Ashland Center of the University of Kentucky in 1957.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt763x83jn3f_11 | title=Minutes of the Meeting of the Board of Trustees of the University of Kentucky, University of Kentucky \u2013 Ashland Center Established, June 11, 1957 | access-date=March 11, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402141709/http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt763x83jn3f_11 | archive-date=April 2, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> University of Kentucky Extension Centers in Fort Knox (1958), Cumberland (1960), and Henderson (1960) followed.\n\nIn 1959, the [[Patterson School of Diplomacy and International Commerce]] opened and began training professionals at the master's and doctoral level for careers in international affairs. The program was the vision of UK's first president [[James Kennedy Patterson]] who had identified the need for the United States to develop a cadre of professionals to advance its diplomatic and commercial interests around the globe. Patterson bequeathed his entire estate to establish this entity.\n\nAuthorized by the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] and signed by Governor [[Bert Combs]] on March 6, 1962, a mandate was placed upon the University of Kentucky to form a community college system.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> Two years later, the Board of Trustees implements the legislation and established the Community College System, creating centers in [[Gateway Community and Technical College|Covington]], [[Ashland Community and Technical College|Ashland]], [[Fort Knox]], [[Southeast Kentucky Community and Technical College|Cumberland]], [[Henderson Community College|Henderson]] and [[Elizabethtown Community and Technical College|Elizabethtown]]. In 1969, the [[Patterson Office Tower]] was completed, currently the tallest building on campus.\n\n[[File:UKMillerHall.jpg|thumb|Miller Hall]] In May 1970, students at the university began protesting the [[Kent State shootings|shootings at Kent State University]].<ref name=\"UKChron\"/><ref name=\"Nunncenter.org\">{{cite web|url=http://nunncenter.org/oralhistoryprojects/protests-at-uk/ |title=45th anniversary of Kent State protests at UK \u2013 Saving Stories |publisher=Nunncenter.org |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> In response, Governor [[Louie Nunn]] deferred to the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] in an attempt to disperse the protesters. An outdated [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps|ROTC]] building was destroyed by fire. The [[Louie B. Nunn Center for Oral History]] at the University of Kentucky Libraries has 13 oral history interviews with participants in the protests, university officials as well as former governor Nunn.<ref name=\"Nunncenter.org\" /> Nine years later, the Singletary Center for the Arts opened, named in honor of former university president Otis Singletary.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> In 1979, the University of Kentucky hosted the first Kentucky [[Women Writers Conference]], which is now the longest-running conference of its kind. The Kentucky Women Writers Conference is now in its 31st year.{{when|date=July 2014}}\n\n===Contemporary history===\n[[File:Engineering plaza.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The engineering plaza.]]\n\nIn 1997, the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] reorganized the community college system, withdrawing the university's jurisdiction from all but the Lexington Community College.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> The other colleges were merged with the [[Kentucky Community and Technical College System|Kentucky Technical College system]] and were placed under a separate board of control.\n\nOn April 3, 1998, work began on the [[William T. Young Library]], which was the largest university project at the time of completion.<ref name=\"HL_032298_d\">{{Cite news | last = Jester | first = Art | last2 = Stepp | first2 = Holly | title = Hub of the University | date = March 22, 1998 | newspaper = [[Lexington Herald-Leader]] | page = 2 | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> The six-level William T. Young Library was constructed on south campus and the largest book endowment among all public university libraries in the country.<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\"/> [[William T. Young]] got his fortune from selling his peanut butter company to [[Procter & Gamble]] in 1955. Nine years after the completion of the William T. Young Library, on April 13, 2007, an entire city block of neighborhood homes were demolished and ground was broken for the [[Biological Pharmaceutical Complex Building (University of Kentucky)|Biological Pharmaceutical Complex Building]], the largest academic building in the state of Kentucky, and one of the largest in the United States.<ref name=\"FutureofPharmacy\">{{cite web | title = Future of Pharmacy | date=April 13, 2007 | publisher=University of Kentucky [[Albert B. Chandler Hospital]] | url=http://www.mc.uky.edu/pharmacy/building.html | accessdate = April 5, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070207034824/http://www.mc.uky.edu/pharmacy/building.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = February 7, 2007}}</ref>\n[[File:Chemistry-Physics Building (U.K.).jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Chemistry-Physics Building]]\nThe Biological Pharmaceutical Complex Building complements the adjacent [[Biomedical Biological Science Research Building (University of Kentucky)|Biomedical Biological Science Research Building]], and is expected to be part of the new university research campus.<ref>{{cite web | title=Biomedical/Biological Sciences Research Building | publisher=University of Kentucky [[Albert B. Chandler Hospital]] | date=November 17, 2006 | url=http://ukcc.uky.edu/cgi-bin/dynamo?maps.391+campus+0509 | access-date=June 16, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017035029/http://ukcc.uky.edu/cgi-bin/dynamo?maps.391+campus+0509 | archive-date=October 17, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref> Other recent announcements include the construction of the new $450 million [[Albert B. Chandler Hospital]], which will was one of the largest projects in the state's history in terms of size and economic impact.<ref name=\"GB_053007\"/>\n\nIn 1997, the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] formed a compact with the university. The Top 20 Plan mandates that the University of Kentucky becomes a Top 20 public research university by 2020.<ref name=\"TOP20_why\">{{cite web|last=Todd|first=Lee|title=UK Reaching Top 20 Critical to Moving Kentucky Forward|publisher=University of Kentucky|date=February 28, 2007|url=http://www.uky.edu/OPBPA/whytop20.htm|access-date=February 28, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206051957/http://www.uky.edu/OPBPA/whytop20.htm|archive-date=February 6, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the compact, states with \"Top 20\" universities feature higher average household incomes, higher education attainments, healthier lives and more financial security.<ref name=\"TOP20_Presentation\">{{cite web |title=Top 20 Business Plan Presentation |publisher=University of Kentucky |year=2005 |accessdate=May 28, 2007 |url=http://www.uky.edu/OPBPA/Top20/Top20_sm.pdf |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205053622/http://www.uky.edu/OPBPA/Top20/Top20_sm.pdf |archive-date=February 5, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> As a result, fewer citizens live in poverty and as a result, fewer public dollars are spent on health care.<ref name=\"TOP20_why\"/> The plan would also spur technological advancements due to university-based research and increase the marketability of the state to investors.\n\n[[File:Main Bldg (UK).jpg|thumb|right|The [[Main Building (University of Kentucky)|Main Building]] in the foreground and the [[Patterson Office Tower]] in the background]]\n\nAs part of the \"Top 20\" plan, the university stated that it plans to,<ref name=\"TOP20_why\"/>\n# Increase enrollment by 7,000 students to 34,000;\n# Increase the state's highest graduation rate by 12% to 72%;\n# Increase the number of faculty by 625 to total 2,500;\n# Increase research expenditures by $470 million to total $768 million per year; and\n# Increase the university's role in Kentucky's \"schools, farms, businesses and communities.\"\n\nThe \"Top 20\" plan has produced some results,<ref name=\"TOP20_Presentation\"/>\n# Total enrollment increased from 24,061 in 1996 to 26,440 in 2004, an increase of 2,379.\n# The six-year graduation rate increased from 59.5 percent in 1998 to 61.2 percent in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=3442 |title=University of Kentucky News |publisher=news.uky.edu |date=April 25, 2008 |accessdate=December 29, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719031555/http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=3442 |archive-date=July 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n# Research expenditures increased from $124.8 million in 1996 to $297.6 million in 2003.<ref name=\"TOP20_Presentation\"/> It dipped slightly to $274 million for 2005.<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\"/> It is currently ranked 28th among public universities in sponsored research.<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\"/>\n# Endowment increased from $195.1 million in 1997 to $538.4 million in 2005.\n\nIn 2000, to help finance the \"Top 20\" plan, the university launched \"The Campaign for the University of Kentucky\", a $600 million [[fundraising]] effort that was used to \"enhance facilities, academic programs, public service, and scholarships.\"<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\"/> It passed that goal and the effort was raised to $1 billion. In March 2007, $1.022 billion was raised, months before the fundraising effort was set to end.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.uky.edu/ukymain/spots/spot-10106.html | title=Surpassing the Goal | publisher=University of Kentucky | year=2007 | access-date=June 19, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626092810/http://www.uky.edu/ukymain/spots/spot-10106.html | archive-date=June 26, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Statewide Facilities Condition Assessment Report'' released on April 4, 2007, the university needs $12.5 billion to complete the 1997 mandate to become a \"Top 20\" institution.<ref>{{cite news | last=Jester | first=Art | title=Report: Kentucky needs $12.5 billion for university facilities by 2020 | work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]] | date=April 7, 2007 | url=http://kentucky.com/181/story/33904.html | accessdate=April 3, 2007 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, The University of Kentucky has an endowment of 1.407 billion.<ref name=\"endowment\"/> Prior endowments were 831.8 in 2007,<ref name=\"HL_BillionDollar\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kentucky.com/211/story/54436.html|title=UK reaches billion-dollar milestone in fund-raising|last=Jester|first=Art|date=April 27, 2007|work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|accessdate=May 2, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20070801070333/http://www.kentucky.com/211/story/54436.html|archive-date=August 1, 2007}}</ref> $538.4 million in 2005, and $195.1 million in 1997, the rapid increases partially attributed to the \"Top 20\" Plan.<ref name=\"TOP20_Presentation\"/> Currently, the William T. Young Library book endowment is the largest among public universities in the United States.<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\" />\n\nIn 2018, the new Gatton Student Center was opened on North Campus. The $200 million, 378,000-square-foot facility contains a cinema, a dining facility, several chain restaurants, ballrooms, the UK Bookstore, the renovated UK Federal Credit Union, offices, and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uknow.uky.edu/campus-news/uk-opens-gatton-student-center|title=UK Celebrates New Gatton Student Center|date=2018-08-30|website=UKNow|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Departments===\n\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| ARWU_W   = 301\u2013400\n| ARWU_N   = 95\u2013116\n| THE_WSJ  = 323\n| USNWR_NU = 132\n| USNWR_W  = 349\n| QS_W     = 601\u2013650\n| THES_W   = 401\u2013500\n| Wamo_NU  = 192\n| Forbes   = 308\n}}\n\nStudents are divided into 16 colleges, a [[graduate school]], 93 [[undergraduate]] programs, 99 [[master's degrees|master programs]], 66 [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctoral]] programs, and four professional programs.<ref name=\"UKS_06\"/>{{Update inline|reason=Stale cite may be suppressing current actual numbers.|date=February 2017}} The University of Kentucky has fifteen libraries on campus. The largest is William T. Young Library, a [[Federal depository library|federal depository]], hosting subjects related to [[social sciences]], [[humanities]] and [[life sciences]] collections. In recent years, the university has focused expenditures increasingly on research, following a compact formed by the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] in 1997. The directive mandated that the university become a ''Top 20'' public research institution, in terms of an overall ranking to be determined by the university itself, by the year 2020.<ref name=\"TOP20_why\"/> The university is ranked tied for 132nd in National Universities and tied for 60th among [[Public university|public universities]] in the 2020 ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' rankings.<ref>{{cite web |title=University of Kentucky |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-kentucky-1989/overall-rankings |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |year=2020 |access-date=September 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221112312/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-kentucky-1989/overall-rankings |archive-date=February 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStudents are divided into several colleges based on their interests and specializations:\n\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Agriculture, Food, and Environment|College of Agriculture, Food and Environment]], founded 1908\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Arts and Sciences|College of Arts and Sciences]], founded 1908\n* [[Gatton College of Business and Economics]], founded 1925 (originally as the College of Commerce)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Communication & Information|College of Communication & Information]], founded 1976\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Dentistry|College of Dentistry]], founded 1962\n[[File:Biological-Pharmaceutical Building U.K.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[Biological Pharmaceutical Complex Building (University of Kentucky)|Biological-Pharmaceutical Building]] is home to the College of Pharmacy]]\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Design|College of Design]], founded 1964 (originally the College of Architecture)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Education|College of Education]], founded 1923\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Engineering|College of Engineering]], founded 1918 (through a merger of the original Colleges of Civil Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, and Mines and Metals)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Fine Arts|College of Fine Arts]], founded 1976\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Health Sciences|College of Health Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uky.edu/chs/ |title=UK College of Health Sciences |publisher=uky.edu |accessdate=January 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202082151/https://www.uky.edu/chs/ |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> founded 1966 (originally as the College of Allied Health Personnel)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Law|College of Law]], founded 1908\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Medicine|College of Medicine]], founded 1954\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Nursing|College of Nursing]], founded 1956\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Pharmacy|College of Pharmacy]], founded 1947 (originally established in 1870 in Louisville)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Public Health|College of Public Health]], founded 2004\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Social Work|College of Social Work]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://socialwork.uky.edu/ |title=UK College of Social Work |publisher=uky.edu |accessdate=January 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110053242/https://socialwork.uky.edu/ |archive-date=November 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> founded 1968\n* [[University of Kentucky Graduate School]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gradschool.uky.edu |title=UK Graduate School |publisher=Gradschool.uky.edu |date=January 4, 2013 |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213070825/http://www.gradschool.uky.edu/ |archive-date=February 13, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> founded 1912\n* [[Martin School|Martin School of Public Policy and Administration]]\n* [[Patterson School of Diplomacy and International Commerce]]\n\nOther colleges no longer in existence at the University of Kentucky include the College of Library Science (separating out of the College of Arts & Sciences in 1968 and incorporated in 2003 into what is now the College of Communication and Information) and the College of Home Economics (created in 1916 and whose founding dean was [[Mary E. Sweeney]]) now a School of Human Environmental Sciences located within the College of Agriculture.<ref>{{cite web | title = Statutory Definition, Governing Regulations, Part I | publisher = University of Kentucky | location = Lexington KY | date = June 11, 2013 | url = http://www.uky.edu/regs/files/gr/gr1.pdf | accessdate = August 1, 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120314041752/http://www.uky.edu/regs/files/gr/gr1.pdf | archive-date = March 14, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n===Lewis Honors College===\nThe Honors Program at the University of Kentucky began in 1961. It offers interdisciplinary, seminar-style classes of 15\u201320 students each as well as \"H-section\" classes that accelerate common course offerings such as chemistry, biology, and physics. The program is intended to supplement the individual interests of the students. Students are offered priority registration, one-on-one faculty attention, dedicated advising, the opportunity to engage in undergraduate research from their first semesters on campus, and are directed to other programs, including the Chellgren Fellows program, the Gaines Fellowship in the Humanities, the University Scholars Program (which allows simultaneous undergraduate and graduate study), and external scholarship opportunities. Additionally, students are offered assistance with fellowship applications, scholarship applications, study abroad opportunities, Honors designation on transcript and diploma,<ref>{{cite web|title=Honors Program|url=http://www.uky.edu/academy/about-honors|website=University of Kentucky|accessdate=April 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328230225/http://www.uky.edu/academy/about-honors|archive-date=March 28, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and/or service learning interests, among other things.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uky.edu/Honors/prospective/prospective.html |title=UK &#124; Honors &#124; Prospective Students |publisher=Uky.edu |date=October 30, 2012 |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130204193039/http://www.uky.edu/Honors/prospective/prospective.html |archive-date=February 4, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2017, the Honors Program became the Lewis Honors College. It is now Lewis Hall.<ref>{{cite web | last = Wells | first = Jenny | title = Board Approves Creation of the UK Lewis Honors College | publisher = University of Kentucky | date = May 3, 2016 | url = https://uknow.uky.edu/content/board-approves-creation-uk-lewis-honors-college | accessdate = May 5, 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160713214417/http://uknow.uky.edu/content/board-approves-creation-uk-lewis-honors-college | archive-date = July 13, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n===SECU: SEC Academic Initiative===\n\nThe University of Kentucky is a member of the SEC Academic Consortium. Now renamed the [[Southeastern Conference#The formation of SECU and SEC academic network|SECU]], the initiative was a collaborative endeavor designed to promote research, scholarship and achievement among the member universities in the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC). The SECU formed its mission to serve as a means to bolster collaborative academic endeavors of [[Southeastern Conference#Member universities|SEC universities]]. Its goals include highlighting the endeavors and achievements of SEC [[Faculty (academic staff)|faculty]], students and its universities and advancing the academic reputation of SEC universities.<ref>{{cite web|title=SECU 10-Year Anniversary Comments from Greg Sankey|url=https://www.thesecu.com/news/secu-10-year-anniversary-comments-from-greg-sankey/|publisher=SEC|accessdate=February 13, 2013|date=August 20, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515234932/https://www.thesecu.com/news/secu-10-year-anniversary-comments-from-greg-sankey/|archivedate=May 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SECU: The Academic Initiative of the SEC |url=http://www.secdigitalnetwork.com/AcademicConsortium |publisher=SEC Digital Network |accessdate=February 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721055557/http://www.secdigitalnetwork.com/AcademicConsortium |archivedate=July 21, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n{{Main|University of Kentucky student life}}\n\n===Students===\nThe University of Kentucky strives for a diverse and international student population, with a selective admissions process.\n\nIn fall 2014, there were 30,000 students enrolled for the first time. This is due in part by the high number of out-of-state students. The percentage mix of students at this time were 62% in state and 38% out-of-state. During this time, the freshman class was recorded at 5,000 students.<ref>{{cite news|title=Enrollment at University of Kentucky Tops 30,000|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/local/education/article44508666.html|work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|accessdate=April 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420104846/http://www.kentucky.com/news/local/education/article44508666.html|archive-date=April 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Student government===\n\nThe University of Kentucky Student Government Association (UKSGA) represents all undergraduate, graduate and professional students enrolled at the university in several critical ways. UKSGA exists to increase student influence over academic policy and to provide many helpful, creative and necessary student services. UKSGA also exists to protect and expand student substantive and procedural rights with the university and surrounding municipalities. Finally, UKSGA exists to better represent the student body in relations with faculty, administration, Board of Trustees and the Commonwealth of Kentucky.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org |title=University of Kentucky Student Government &#124; The UKSGA homepage |publisher=Uksga.org |date=February 5, 2012 |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105133719/http://uksga.org/ |archive-date=November 5, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nUKSGA includes an Executive, Legislative, and Judicial Branch.\n\n*Executive Branch: oversees day-to-day operations, manages budget, and facilitates major programs.\n*Legislative Branch: includes the Student Senate. There are 46 legislators in this branch. Their goal is to allocate funds, approve presidential appointments, facilitate legislative changes, and represent the larger student voice.\n*Judicial: composed of one Chief Justice and six Supreme Court Justices. The Supreme Court rules on the constitutionality of legislation, handles claims levied against SGA officials, hears any election rules violation complaints and validates election results.<ref>{{cite web|title=UKSGA|url=http://uksga.org/about|website=Student Government Association|accessdate=April 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503151307/http://uksga.org/about|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSeveral of their current programs include:\n\n*Kentucky Wildcab: a late night transportation service designed to enhance the safety efforts of the university and surrounding community in partnership with UK Transportation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uksga.org/services/|title=University of Kentucky Student Government Services|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Uksga.org|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010130829/http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/cats-cruiser|archive-date=October 10, 2012|accessdate=9 April 2020|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*Wildcat Wardrobe: provides UK students with free professional dress clothing for interviews and jobs <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uksga.org/services/|title=UKSGA: Services|website=uksga.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n*Safe CATS: provides UK students with a safer way to travel around campus by having SafeCats team members escort students to their destinations on-foot or by golf cart<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/safecats |title=SafeCats &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government |publisher=Uksga.org |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010122352/http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/safecats |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*Student Legal Services: free on-site consultation for any legal issue by a local attorney<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/student-legal-service |title=Student Legal Service &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government |publisher=Uksga.org |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010123825/http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/student-legal-service |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Childcare]] Grants: available for part-time and full-time UK students, both at the undergraduate and graduate level, who need financial assistance for day-care service for their children.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org/applications/childcare-grants |title=Childcare Grants &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government |publisher=Uksga.org |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010121545/http://uksga.org/applications/childcare-grants |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*Scholarships<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org/applications/scholarships-awards |title=Scholarships & Awards &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government |publisher=Uksga.org |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010131847/http://uksga.org/applications/scholarships-awards |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*Student Organization Funding: General Funding Grants, Club Sports Grants, Service Grants, Academic/Professional Conferences, and Senate Special Projects<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uksga.org/funding|title=Funding &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Uksga.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010130639/http://uksga.org/funding|archive-date=21 Feb 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral distinguished Student Body Presidents include Governor [[Steve Beshear]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://governor.ky.gov/about/Pages/default.aspx |title=About Meet the Governor |publisher=Governor.ky.gov |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111221706/http://governor.ky.gov/about/Pages/default.aspx |archive-date=January 11, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Student media===\n\nThe Electrical and Computer Engineering Department was the home of one of the earliest college amateur [[radio station]]s in the United States, beginning with [[W4JP]] that began continuous operation prior to [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211030614/http://www.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/UKARC/history/early/intro.html | archivedate=February 11, 2009| title=The Early Years: A Pictorial History | publisher=University of Kentucky Amateur Radio Club | accessdate=July 24, 2012| url=http://www.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/UKARC/history/early/intro.html}}</ref> In 1927, the station was relicensed as 9JL (later W9JL).<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211030619/http://www.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/UKARC/history/w9jl/intro.html| archivedate=February 11, 2009| title=The Middle Years: A Pictorial History | publisher=University of Kentucky Amateur Radio Club | accessdate=July 24, 2012| url=http://www.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/UKARC/history/w9jl/intro.html}}</ref>\n\nStudents currently run two independent [[Frequency Modulation|FM]] stations. The first, 91.3 FM [[WUKY]], is a [[Adult Album Alternative|Triple-A]] station and was the first university-owned FM radio station in the United States and Kentucky's first public radio station.<ref name=\"WUKY_About\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wuky.org/history | title=History | publisher=WUKY | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426122057/http://www.wuky.org/history | archive-date=April 26, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> The operations started on October 17, 1940 as [[WBKY]] out of [[Beattyville, Kentucky|Beattyville]], although the station moved five years later to Lexington.<ref name=\"WUKY_About\"/>\n\nIn 1971, WBKY was one of the first to carry NPR's \"All Things Considered\" and helped debut [[National Public Radio]], changing its call letters to WUKY in 1989 to better reflect its affiliation with the university. In 2007, it became the first Lexington radio station to broadcast in high-definition digital radio.<ref name=\"WUKY_About\"/> The second is 88.1 FM [[WRFL]] which has been in operation since 1988.<ref name=\"WRFL_About\">{{cite news | title = About | publisher = [[WRFL]] | url = http://wrfl881.org/about.html | accessdate = May 8, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313194831/http://www.wrfl881.org/about.html| archivedate=March 13, 2007 }}</ref> WRFL is operated by students and broadcasts live 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, and features music that is spread across most genres.\n\nThe campus is also served by the [[The Kentucky Kernel|Kentucky Kernel]], a student-run, financially independent daily newspaper, with the first issue published in 1915.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/markers/KYKernel1.html | title=Kentucky Kernel Historical Marker | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626195019/http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/markers/KYKernel1.html | archive-date=June 26, 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt72jm23bv99_1/viewer? | title=The Kentucky Kernel, First Issue | date=September 16, 1915 | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731175436/http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt72jm23bv99_1/viewer | archive-date=July 31, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> The official [[yearbook]] of the University of Kentucky is the ''Kentuckian'', first published in 1906.<ref name=\"UKChron\" /> The ''Kentuckian'' was preceded by at least one previous book, the ''Echo''.\n\n===Greek life===\n\nNineteen [[fraternities and sororities|sororities]] and twenty-three [[fraternities and sororities|fraternities]] serve the university, representing over 3,000 students with a budget of $3.2 million per year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greek Welcome|publisher=University of Kentucky|date=September 21, 2006|accessdate=January 11, 2008|url=http://www.uky.edu/StudentAffairs/Greek|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114190836/http://www.uky.edu/StudentAffairs/Greek/|archive-date=January 14, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The governing bodies include the [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]], an organization for nine historically black organizations, international Greek assemblies, the [[National Panhellenic Conference]] for sororities and the [[North American Interfraternity Conference|Interfraternity Council]] for the fraternities.<ref>{{cite web|title=UK Interfraternity Council|year=2008|accessdate=January 11, 2008|url=http://www.kentuckyifc.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213021749/http://www.kentuckyifc.com/|archive-date=December 13, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThere are many non-Greek organizations on campus, like [[Alpha Kappa Psi]], an internationally recognized Professional Business Fraternity and [[Tau Beta Sigma]], a band fraternity. The university also hosts a chapter of the [[Alpha Phi Omega]] [[co-educational]] [[service fraternity]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|Fraternities\n!colspan=2|Sororities\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n*[[Alpha Gamma Rho]]\n*[[Alpha Kappa Psi]]\n*[[Alpha Phi Alpha]]\n*[[Alpha Sigma Phi]]\n*[[Beta Theta Pi]]\n*[[Beta Upsilon Chi]]\n*[[Chi Psi]]\n*[[Delta Sigma Phi]]\n*[[Delta Tau Delta]]\n*[[Delta Upsilon]]\n\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n*[[FarmHouse]]\n*[[Iota Phi Theta]]\n*[[Kappa Alpha Order]]\n*[[Kappa Alpha Psi]]\n*[[Kappa Sigma]]\n*[[Omega Psi Phi]]\n*[[Pershing Rifles]]\n*[[Phi Beta Sigma]]\n*[[Phi Delta Theta]]\n*[[Phi Gamma Delta]]\n\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n\n*[[Phi Kappa Tau]]\n*[[Phi Sigma Kappa]]\n*[[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]]\n*[[Sigma Lambda Beta]]\n*[[Sigma Nu]]\n*[[Sigma Pi]]\n*[[Sigma Phi Epsilon]] \n*[[Tau Kappa Epsilon]]\n*[[Theta Chi]]\n*[[Triangle Fraternity]]\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n*[[Alpha Chi Omega]]\n*[[Alpha Delta Pi]]\n*[[Alpha Gamma Delta]]\n*[[Alpha Kappa Alpha]]\n*[[Alpha Omicron Pi]]\n*[[Alpha Phi]]\n*[[Ceres (Women's Agricultural Fraternity)|Ceres]]\n*[[Chi Omega]]\n*[[Delta Delta Delta]]\n*[[Delta Gamma]]\n*[[Delta Sigma Theta]]\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n*[[Delta Zeta]]\n*[[Gamma Phi Beta]]\n*[[Kappa Alpha Theta]]\n*[[Kappa Delta]]\n*[[Kappa Kappa Gamma]]\n*[[Phi Mu]]\n*[[Phi Sigma Rho]]\n*[[Pi Beta Phi]]\n*[[Sigma Gamma Rho]]\n*[[Sigma Lambda Gamma]]\n*[[Theta Nu Xi]]\n*[[Zeta Phi Beta]]\n|}\n\n===Athletics===\n\n[[File:rupparenaK.JPG|thumb|The Kentucky cheerleaders at [[Rupp Arena]] performing the traditional \"Big K\" cheer during a basketball game. Seating Capacity of Rupp Arena is 23,500.]]\n{{Main|Kentucky Wildcats}}\n{{See also|Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky Wildcats football|University of Kentucky cheerleading squad|Kentucky Wildcats women's basketball|Kentucky Wildcats men's soccer|Kentucky Wildcats softball}}\n\nUniversity of Kentucky student-athletes compete as the Wildcats under colors Kentucky blue and white.\n\nBeginning in the 1890s, students at the A&M scheduled [[american football|football]] games with neighboring colleges.<ref name=\"UK_HIS3\">{{cite web | title=History Briefs | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=May 23, 2007 | url=http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/history3.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021119074028/http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/history3.html| archivedate=November 19, 2002}}</ref> In 1902, the [[Kentucky Wildcats women's basketball|women's basketball]] program began on campus,<ref name=\"UK_HIS3\"/> and the [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|men's team]] was added one year later. The \"[[Wildcat]]s\" became associated with the university shortly after a [[American football|football]] victory over [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]] on October 9, 1909.<ref name=\"UK TRAD\"/> The then-chief of the military department, Commandant Carbuiser, stated that the team had \"fought like wildcats.\" The slogan was later adopted by the university, and a costumed mascot debuted in 1976.<ref name=\"UK TRAD\"/>\n\nIn 1930, then-[[high school]] coach [[Adolph Rupp]] was hired as a basketball coach for the university. He had a career that would span 42 years until 1972.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> During his tenure, he led the [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|men's basketball team]] to four [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] championships in 1948, 1949, 1951 and 1958.<ref name=\"UK_HIS3\"/> The Wildcats later won a fifth championship under [[Joe B. Hall]] in 1978, another in 1996 under [[Rick Pitino]] and the next under [[Tubby Smith|Orlando \"Tubby\" Smith]] in 1998.<ref name=\"UK_HIS3\"/> In 2007, the University of Kentucky named [[Billy Gillispie]] as the head coach of the men's basketball team and on March 30, 2009, the university named [[John Calipari]] as the head coach of the Wildcats. Calipari coached the team to its eighth national title in 2012.\n\nOn December 21, 2009, the men's basketball team reached another milestone, becoming the first college basketball team to reach 2000 all-time wins. The 2000th win was an 88\u201344 victory over the [[2009\u201310 Drexel Dragons men's basketball team|Drexel Dragons]]. Kentucky was also the first school to reach the 1000 all-time wins, which they accomplished in 1969.\n\nThe university boasts of numerous national championships, with its latest coming in 2012 when the men's basketball team won its eighth national title. UK also boasts of a [[cross country running|cross country]] national team championship (women's, 1988), eight individual championships in [[artistic gymnastics|gymnastics]], an [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympic]] medalist in [[track and field]], and 21 national championships in [[cheerleading]].<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\">{{cite web | title=Stats-at-a-glance | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=May 23, 2007 | url=http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/facts.html. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629200653/http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/facts.html| archivedate=June 29, 2007 }}</ref> After defeating number-one ranked Oklahoma 13\u20137 in the Sugar Bowl under legendary coach Bear Bryant, Kentucky is also an NCAA-recognized co-national champion for the 1950 season.\n\n[[File:KentuckyCommonwealthStadium-EZInterior.jpg|thumb|left|275px|Pregame of 2005 Kentucky vs. Auburn game.]]\n\nThe University of Kentucky Dance team is currently ranked 5th in the nation in [[Hip Hop]] and 7th in [[Pom-pom|Pom]] at Universal Dance Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/page/spirit-dance|title=Dance Team - UK Wildcats|publisher=|accessdate=December 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129025941/http://ukathletics.com/page/spirit-dance|archive-date=November 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOther athletic programs sponsored at the varsity level include [[baseball]], men's and women's [[basketball]], men's and women's [[cross country running]], [[American football|football]], men's and women's [[golf]], women's [[artistic gymnastics|gymnastics]], the coeducational sport of [[shooting sports|rifle]], men's and women's [[Association football|soccer]], women's [[softball]], men's and women's [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]] and [[Diving (sport)|diving]], men's and women's [[tennis]], men's and women's [[track and field]] and women's [[volleyball]].<ref>{{cite web | title=ukatlhetics.com | publisher=University of Kentucky | year=2008 | accessdate=January 3, 2008 | url=http://www.ukathletics.com/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224000436/http://www.ukathletics.com/ | archive-date=February 24, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref> The school also has a popular club-level men's [[ice hockey]] team and a rugby program that competes at the Division 1 level.\n\nThe University of Kentucky football coach is [[Mark Stoops]], named the successor to [[Joker Phillips]], who was the first African American football coach in Kentucky's history.\n\nNotable among a number of songs commonly played and sung at various events such as [[Graduation|commencement]], [[convocation]] and athletic games is the University of Kentucky [[fight song]]: ''[[On, On, U of K]]''.<ref name=songs>{{cite web | url=http://ukbands.org/schoolsongs.html | title=School Songs | publisher=University of Kentucky Bands | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116220612/http://ukbands.org/schoolsongs.html | archive-date=January 16, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, the song ''Kentucky Fight''<ref name=songs /> is played before games.\n\n==Campus==\n\n[[File:WilliamtyounglibraryUK.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Completed in 1998, the William T. Young Library serves both the university campus and the Commonwealth of Kentucky]]\n\n{{Main|List of University of Kentucky buildings}}\n\nThe University of Kentucky offers seven main dining facilities, 23 residence halls, and numerous recreation facilities spread between three distinct campuses: north, south, and central. It is also home to more than 250 student-run organizations.\n\nThe university campus is home to numerous notable structures, such as [[Main Building (University of Kentucky)|Main Building]], a four-story administration building dating to 1882,<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> which was gutted by fire on May 15, 2001. The cause of the blaze was attributed to a welders torch during repairs to the building's roof. Total costs for reconstruction after the fire exceeded $17 million. The [[Patterson Office Tower]] is the tallest building on campus. The university is also home to several major construction projects, including the [[Albert B. Chandler Hospital]] expansion. As of 2016, construction projects include Student Center renovation and expansion, and Alumni Gym.\n\nThe University of Kentucky once operated 14 [[community college]]s with more than 100 extended sites, centers and campuses under the [[University of Kentucky's Community College System|Kentucky Community and Technical College System]], but relinquished control under the [[Education in Kentucky#Postsecondary Education Improvement Act of 1997|Postsecondary Education Improvement Act of 1997]].<ref name=\"DI_070103\">{{cite news | last=Gilmore | first=Amanda | title=Merger of ACC, ATC completed | work=[[The Daily Independent (Ashland newspaper)|The Daily Independent]] | date=July 1, 2003 | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | url=http://commentsengine.cnhi.zope.net/archives/dailyindependent/story_detail?story_id=7782 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The network of community colleges is now known as the [[Kentucky Community and Technical College System]] (KCTCS). Adjoining Lexington Community College, despite the reorganization of the community colleges, remained integrated with the university, but separated from the University of Kentucky in 2004 and became a part of KCTCS; it is now known as [[Bluegrass Community and Technical College]].\n\nThe College of Engineering currently operates a satellite campus in [[Paducah, Kentucky|Paducah]], located on the campus of [[West Kentucky Community and Technical College]].<ref name=\"WKCTCS\">{{cite web | title=A Rich Heritage: A Historic Timeline | publisher=[[West Kentucky Community and Technical College]] | year=2007 | accessdate=January 7, 2007 | url=http://www.westkentucky.kctcs.edu/aboutus/wkctcdhist.shtml |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060909220212/http://www.westkentucky.kctcs.edu/aboutus/wkctcdhist.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 9, 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Funkhouser building.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Funkhouser Building]]\n\n===Campus libraries===\n\nThe University of Kentucky is home to nine campus libraries.<ref>{{cite web | title=University of Kentucky Libraries | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=2015 | accessdate=May 11, 2018 | url=http://libraries.uky.edu/CampusLibraries | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512044454/http://libraries.uky.edu/CampusLibraries | archive-date=May 12, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> Among them is the William T. Young Library, which houses a general undergraduate collection and social sciences, humanities, business, biology, and agricultural materials. The library is also a [[Federal Depository Library]] and a [[public library]] for the [[Commonwealth of Kentucky]]. Libraries include:\n\n* Agricultural Information Center\n* Design Library\n* Education Library\n* Law Library\n* Lucille Caudill Little Fine Arts Library and Learning Center\n* Medical Center Library\n* Science & Engineering Library\n* Special Collections Research Center\n* William T. Young Library\n\n[[File:Atrium of Don and Cathy Jacobs Science Building.jpg|thumb|Interior of new science building]]\n\n[[File:University of Kentucky Arboretum - DSC09377.JPG|thumb|right|250px|UK Arboretum]]\n\n===Campus landmarks===\n\nThe University of Kentucky has several noteworthy landmarks:\n\n*[[Kroger Field]]\n* [[Memorial Coliseum (Lexington)|Memorial Coliseum]]\n* [[Memorial Hall, University of Kentucky|Memorial Hall]]\n* [[Singletary Center for the Arts]]\n* [[University of Kentucky Art Museum]]\n* [[University of Kentucky/Lexington-Fayette Urban County Government Arboretum]]\n* [[University of Kentucky Research and Education Center Botanical Garden]]\n* Wildcat Alumni Plaza\n* [[William T. Young Library]]\n\n==Notable faculty==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2019}}\n\n*[[Arthur G. Hunt]], American plant and soils scientist\n*[[Ronald Werner-Wilson]] (born 1972), Chair of the Family Studies Department and Kathryn Louise Chellgren Endowed Professor for Research in Family Studies\n*[[Kimberly W. Anderson]], Chemist, Gill Eminent Professor of Chemical Engineering and Associate Dean for Administration and Academic Affairs in the College of Engineering\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n{{Main|List of University of Kentucky alumni}}\n\nThe university has over 140,246 alumni in the state of Kentucky,<ref>{{cite web | title=Alumni throughout the Bluegrass State | publisher=University of Kentucky Alumni Association | date=January 2007 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | url=http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/statewebmap.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123065959/http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/statewebmap.htm | archive-date=January 23, 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref> 216,737 in the United States,<ref>{{cite web | title=Alumni across the nation | publisher=University of Kentucky Alumni Association | date=January 2007 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | url=http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/framemap.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123065922/http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/framemap.htm | archive-date=January 23, 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref> and 1,119 internationally.<ref>{{cite web | title=Alumni around the world | publisher=University of Kentucky Alumni Association | date=January 2007 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | url=http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/worldmap.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123070004/http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/worldmap.htm | archive-date=January 23, 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref> The University of Kentucky Alumni Association is the primary affiliation for former students and faculty, and is located at the corner of Rose Street and Euclid Avenue. The building, dedicated in 1963, is named for Helen G. King, the first permanent director of the association and was former \"Miss University of Kentucky\". The association also meets at [[Spindletop Hall]], a large mansion along Iron Works Pike, which serves as a central alumni gathering point.<ref>{{cite news | title=Mission & History | year=2007 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | publisher=University of Kentucky Alumni Association | url=http://www.ukalumni.net/pages.php?page_id=6 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515165033/http://www.ukalumni.net/pages.php?page_id=6 | archive-date=May 15, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe University of Kentucky boasts seven governors, including former [[Governor of Kentucky]] [[Steve Beshear]], former [[Governor of Ohio]] [[Ted Strickland]], former [[Governor of North Carolina]] [[Beverly Perdue]], and former governors [[Ernie Fletcher]], [[Paul E. Patton]] and Arkansas' [[Tom Jefferson Terral]], and former governor, [[U.S. Senator]] and Commissioner of [[Major League Baseball]] [[Happy Chandler|Albert \"Happy\" Chandler]]. It also claims [[Ken Lucas]], a former [[U.S. representative]] from the commonwealth's fourth [[congressional district]], United Methodist Bishop [[Alfred W. Gwinn]], current [[U.S. Senator]] [[Mitch McConnell]], [[Bill Gatton|Carol Gatton]], an automobile dealer executive and donor of the largest gift ever to the university, and Paul Chellgren, [[Chairman]] and [[CEO]] of [[Ashland Inc.]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Twenty to be inducted into UK Hall of Distinguished Alumni | last=Scharfenberger | first=John | date=April 10, 2000 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | publisher=University of Kentucky | url=http://www.uky.edu/PR/News/Archives/2000/April2000/distalumni.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013124528/http://www.uky.edu/PR/News/Archives/2000/April2000/distalumni.htm | archive-date=October 13, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> The university was also the home of Dr. [[Thomas Hunt Morgan]], a scientist and winner of the 1933 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]], and [[William Lipscomb]], 1976 winner of the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]].<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> The university claims actors such as [[Miss Elizabeth]] and  [[Ashley Judd]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/politics-government/article44418894.html|title=Ashley Judd bought a house in Kentucky in March|work=kentucky|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201233111/http://www.kentucky.com/news/politics-government/article44418894.html|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:Thomas_Hunt_Morgan.jpg|[[Thomas Hunt Morgan]], recipient of the [[Nobel Prize]] in Physiology or Medicine, and father of modern [[genetics]]\nFile:Mitch McConnell official photo.jpg|[[Mitch McConnell]], [[U.S. Senator]], current [[Senate Majority Leader]]\nFile:Ashley Judd head.jpg|[[Ashley Judd]], actress\nFile:William n lipscomb jr.jpg|[[William Lipscomb]], 1976 winner of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of forestry universities and colleges]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Collier's Poster|Kentucky, University of|the University of Kentucky}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.ukathletics.com University of Kentucky Athletics website]\n*[http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7n8p5v980r/guide Digitized images of the University of Kentucky from the Glass plate negative collection, 1898\u20131918] housed at the University of Kentucky Libraries Special Collections Research Center\n\n{{University of Kentucky}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|Kentucky Wildcats|color=white}}\n|list =\n{{Kentucky Higher Education}}\n{{Southeastern Conference navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Universities Research Association}}\n{{Lexington (Kentucky)}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kentucky, University Of}}\n[[Category:University of Kentucky| ]]\n[[Category:Land-grant universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1865]]\n[[Category:Flagship universities in the United States]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Lexington, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Distance education institutions based in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public research university in Lexington, KY, USA}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Coord|38|02|N|84|30|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = University of Kentucky\n| image = University of Kentucky seal.svg\n| image_upright = .65\n| latin_name = Universitas Kentuckiensis\n| motto =  United We Stand, Divided We Fall\n| established = {{start date and age|1865}}\n| type = [[Flagship campus|Flagship]]<br />[[Public University|Public]]<br />[[Land-grant University|Land-grant]]\n| academic_affiliations = [[Association of Public and Land-Grant Universities|APLU]]<br />[[Oak Ridge Associated Universities|ORAU]]<br />[[Southeastern Universities Research Association|SURA]]\n| endowment = $1.407 billion (2019)<ref name=endowment>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-Endowment-Market-Values--Final-Feb-10.ashx? |title=U.S. and Canadian 2019 NTSE Participating Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2019 Endowment Market Value, and Percentage Change in Market Value from FY18 to FY19 (Revised) |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| president = [[Eli Capilouto]]\n| provost = David W. Blackwell\n|students = 29,182 (2019)<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=University+of+Kentucky&s=all&id=157085|title=College Navigator - University of Kentucky|website=nces.ed.gov|access-date=August 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123123459/https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=university+of+kentucky&s=all&id=157085|archive-date=November 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| undergrad = 22,136  (2019)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| postgrad = 7046 (2019)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| staff = 13,145  [[Full-time equivalent|FTE]] (2015-2016)<ref name=\"booklet\">[http://www.uky.edu/iraa/sites/www.uky.edu.iraa/files/fact_booklet1516.pdf ''UK Fact Booklet 2015-2016''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014101920/http://www.uky.edu/iraa/sites/www.uky.edu.iraa/files/fact_booklet1516.pdf |date=October 14, 2016 }} (PDF). University of Kentucky. 2016. Retrieved on October 7, 2016</ref>\n| city = [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]]\n| state = [[Kentucky]]\n| country = United States\n| campus = [[Urban area|Urban]], {{convert|784|acre|km2}}<ref name=\"FACTBOOK_0607\">{{cite web | publisher=University of Kentucky | title=Fact Booklet 2006\u20132007 | year=2006 | url=http://www.uky.edu/OPIE/FactBooklet0607.pdf |format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070221130217/http://www.uky.edu/OPIE/FactBooklet0607.pdf|archivedate=February 21, 2007}}</ref>\n| colors = Blue and White<ref>{{cite book|title=Primary Color Palette|url=https://issuu.com/universityofkentucky/docs/graphic_standards_a16-7/6|publisher=University of Kentucky|work=UK Graphic Standards|date=April 6, 2016|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref><br />{{college color boxes|Kentucky Wildcats}}\n| sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division I]] \u2013 [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]\n| nickname = [[Kentucky Wildcats|Wildcats]]\n| mascot = \"The Wildcat,\" \"Scratch\"<ref name=\"UK TRAD\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukathletics.com/trads/mascot.html |title=Kentucky Wildcats Official Athletic Site - Traditions |publisher=Ukathletics.com |accessdate=December 3, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119015528/http://www.ukathletics.com/trads/mascot.html |archive-date=November 19, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|www.uky.edu}}\n| logo = University of Kentucky logo.svg\n| logo_upright = 1.1\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Kentucky''' ('''UK''') is a [[state university (U.S.)|public]] university in [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. Founded in 1865 by [[John Bryan Bowman]] as the '''Agricultural and Mechanical College of Kentucky''',<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/> the university is one of the state's two [[land-grant university|land-grant universities]] (the other being [[Kentucky State University]]) and the institution with the highest enrollment in the state, with 30,720<ref name=\"booklet\"/> students as of Fall 2015.\n\nThe institution comprises 16 colleges, a [[graduate school]], 93 [[undergraduate]] programs, 99 [[master's degrees|master programs]], 66 [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctoral]] programs, and four professional programs.<ref name=\"UKS_06\">{{cite web | title=Consolidated Financial Statements | date=June 30, 2006 | publisher=University of Kentucky | url=http://www.uky.edu/Home/AnnualReport/2006_UK_Consolidated_Statement_with_cover.pdf | format=PDF | access-date=June 12, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615130815/http://www.uky.edu/Home/AnnualReport/2006_UK_Consolidated_Statement_with_cover.pdf | archive-date=June 15, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=Stale cite may be suppressing current actual numbers.|date=February 2017}} The University of Kentucky has fifteen libraries on campus. The largest is the [[William T. Young Library]], a federal depository, hosting subjects related to [[social sciences]], [[humanities]], and [[life sciences]] collections. In recent years, the university has focused expenditures increasingly on research, following a compact formed by the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] in 1997. The directive mandated that the university become a ''Top 20'' public research institution, in terms of an overall ranking, to be determined by the university itself, by the year 2020.<ref name=\"TOP20_why\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===University origins===\nIn the early commonwealth of Kentucky, higher education was limited to a number of children from prominent families, disciplined apprentices, and those young men seeking entry into clerical, legal, and medical professions. As the first university in the territory that would become Kentucky, [[Transylvania University]] was the primary center for education, and became the forerunner of what would become the University of Kentucky.\n\n[[File:Barker Hall.jpg|thumb|left|The early campus: Barker Hall in the center, the Main Building to the right, and a lake in the foreground where the Student Center was later built.]]\n\n[[John Bryan Bowman]] founded the Agricultural and Mechanical College of Kentucky (A&M), a publicly chartered department of Kentucky University, after receiving federal support through the [[Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act]] in 1865.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\">{{cite web | title=A Brief History of the University of Kentucky | publisher=University of Kentucky | url=http://www.uky.edu/CampusGuide/uk-history.html | accessdate=January 6, 2012 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6AjVMlfoS?url=http://www.uky.edu/CampusGuide/uk-history.html | archive-date=September 17, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Courses were offered at [[Ashland, The Henry Clay Estate]].<ref name=\"UKChron\" /> Three years later, [[James Kennedy Patterson]] became the first president of the land-grant university and the first degree was awarded. In 1876, the university began to offer [[master's degree]] programs. Two years later, A&M separated from Kentucky University, which is now [[Transylvania University]].<ref name=\"UKChron\">{{cite web | title=A Chronology of UK | publisher=University of Kentucky Special Collections & Digital Programs Division | date=January 2, 2008 | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | url=http://www.uky.edu/Libraries/libpage.php?lweb_id=311&llib_id=13 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220222212/http://www.uky.edu/Libraries/libpage.php?lweb_id=311&llib_id=13 | archive-date=February 20, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> For the new school, Lexington donated a {{Convert|52|acre|m2|adj=on}} park and fair ground, which became the core of UK's present campus.<ref name=\"UKChron\" /> A&M was initially a male-only institution, but began to admit women in 1880.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/>\n\nIn 1892, the official colors of the university, royal blue and white, were adopted. An earlier color set, blue and light yellow, was adopted earlier at a Kentucky-[[Centre College]] football game on December 19, 1891.<ref name=\"UK TRAD\">{{cite web | title=University of Kentucky Traditions and songs | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | publisher=University of Kentucky | url=http://www.uky.edu/UKHome/subpages/traditions.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711073947/http://www.uky.edu/UKHome/subpages/traditions.html | archive-date=July 11, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> The particular hue of blue was determined from a necktie, which was used to demonstrate the color of royal blue.<ref name=\"UK TRAD\"/>\n\nOn February 15, 1882, [[Main Building (University of Kentucky)|Administration Building]] was the first building of three completed on the present campus.<ref name=\"UKChron\" /> Three years later, the college formed the Agricultural Experiment Station, which researches issues relating to agribusiness, food processing, nutrition, water and soil resources and the environment.<ref name=\"AES\">{{cite web | title=agResearch | publisher=University of Kentucky College of Agriculture | year=2007 | accessdate=January 7, 2007 | url=http://www.ca.uky.edu/research/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516232453/http://www.ca.uky.edu/research/ | archive-date=May 16, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> This was followed up by the creation of the university's ''Agricultural Extension Service'' in 1910, which was one of the first in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"UK_HIS2\">{{cite web | title=History Briefs | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=May 23, 2007 | url=http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/history2.html | access-date=June 12, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613040216/http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/history2.html | archive-date=June 13, 2007 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Cooperative extension service|extension service]] became a model of the federally mandated programs that were required beginning in 1914.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/>\n\n===Coeducational school: modern period===\n\n[[File:Patterson Hall 1905.jpg|thumb|Patterson Hall, shortly after its 1904 opening]]\nPatterson Hall, the school's first women's dormitory, was constructed in 1904. Residents had to cross a [[swamp]]y depression, where the now demolished Student Center later stood, to reach central campus.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/> Four years later, the school's name was changed to the \"State University, Lexington, Kentucky\" upon reaching [[university]] status, and then to the \"University of Kentucky\" in 1916.<ref name=\"UK_HIS1\"/> The university led to the creation of the College of Home Economics in 1916, and [[Mary E. Sweeney]] was promoted from chair of the Department of Home Economics to Dean of the College. (Later renamed the College of Human Environmental Sciences, this educational unit was folded into the College of Agriculture in 2003 as the School of Human Environmental Sciences<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ca.uky.edu/hes/?p=12|title=Human Environmental Sciences|website=UK College of Agriculture, Food and Environment|accessdate=August 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011041102/http://www2.ca.uky.edu/hes/?p=12|archive-date=October 11, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>). The College of Commerce was established in 1925, known today as the [[Gatton College of Business and Economics]].<ref name=\"UK_HIS2\"/>\n\nIn 1929, [[Memorial Hall (University of Kentucky)|Memorial Hall]] was completed, dedicated to the 2,756 Kentuckians who died in [[World War I]].<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> This was followed up by the new [[Margaret I. King Library|King Library]], which opened in 1931 and was named for a long-time library director, Margaret I. King.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> The university's graduate and professional programs became racially integrated in 1949 when [[Lyman T. Johnson]], an [[African American]], won a lawsuit to be admitted to the graduate program.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/markers/DesegregationJohnson1.html | title=Desegregation of UK - Historical Marker | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626201234/http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/markers/DesegregationJohnson1.html | archive-date=June 26, 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.uky.edu/PR/News/Archives/1999/APRIL99/johnsondedi.htm | title=UK DEDICATES HISTORICAL MARKER FOR 50 YEARS OF AFRICAN AMERICANS | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=April 22, 1999 | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731124208/http://www.uky.edu/PR/News/Archives/1999/APRIL99/johnsondedi.htm | archive-date=July 31, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> African Americans would not be allowed to attend as undergraduates until 1954, following the US Supreme Court's [[Brown v. Board of Education]] decision.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ket.org/civilrights/timeline.htm | title=A Kentucky Civil Rights Timeline | accessdate=August 8, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807135415/http://www.ket.org/civilrights/timeline.htm | archive-date=August 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1939, Governor Happy Chandler appointed the first woman trustee on the University of Kentucky Board of Trustees, Georgia M. Blazer of Ashland.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://kdl.kyvl.org/catalog/xt7d251fjp5f_1 | title= Minutes of Mrs. Blazer's first Regular Meeting of the Board of Trustees, University of Kentucky, April 4, 1939 | access-date= December 12, 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141214045751/http://kdl.kyvl.org/catalog/xt7d251fjp5f_1 | archive-date= December 14, 2014 | url-status= live }}</ref> She served from 1939 to 1960. In 1962, Blazer Hall was opened as the Georgia M Blazer Hall [dormitory] for Women in tribute to her twenty-one years of service as a University of Kentucky trustee.<ref name=BlazerMinutes>{{cite web | url= http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7hmg7frh2j_48 | title= Minutes of Regular Meeting of the Board of Trustees, University of Kentucky, President Dickey's  recommendation and the Board's approval in the naming of the \"Georgia M. Blazer Hall\" dormitory for women, (pages 48 & 49), June 4, 1962 | access-date= December 12, 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141213020532/http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7hmg7frh2j_48 | archive-date= December 13, 2014 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nGround was broken for the Albert B. Chandler Hospital in 1955, when Governor of Kentucky [[Happy Chandler]] recommended that the Kentucky General Assembly appropriate $5 million for the creation of the University of Kentucky College of Medicine and a medical center at the university.<ref name=\"GB_053007\">{{ cite news | title=Officials Break Ground on New UK Albert B. Chandler Hospital | first=Amanda | last=Nelson | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=May 30, 2007 | url=http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=2334 | access-date=July 25, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830233415/http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=2334 | archive-date=August 30, 2007 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> This was completed after a series of studies were conducted that highlighted the health needs of the citizens, as well as the need to train more physicians for the state. Five years later, the [[University of Kentucky College of Medicine|College of Medicine]] and [[University of Kentucky College of Nursing|College of Nursing]] opened, followed by the [[University of Kentucky College of Dentistry|College of Dentistry]] in 1962.<ref name=\"UK_HIS2\"/>\n\nNine years after the founding of The Northern Extension Center in Covington, representing the Ashland Independent School Board of Education,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7gqn5z6j5s_25 | title=Minutes of the Meeting of the Board of Trustees of the University of Kentucky, Ashland Delegation Heard on request for off-campus University of Kentucky Center April 2, 1957 | access-date=March 11, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402141712/http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7gqn5z6j5s_25 | archive-date=April 2, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> Ashland attorney Henderson Dysard and [[Ashland Inc.|Ashland Oil & Refining Company]] founder and CEO [[Paul G. Blazer]] presented a proposal to President Dickey and the University of Kentucky Board of Trustees for the university to take over the day-to-day operations and curriculum of the Ashland [municipal] Junior College, creating the Ashland Center of the University of Kentucky in 1957.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt763x83jn3f_11 | title=Minutes of the Meeting of the Board of Trustees of the University of Kentucky, University of Kentucky \u2013 Ashland Center Established, June 11, 1957 | access-date=March 11, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402141709/http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt763x83jn3f_11 | archive-date=April 2, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> University of Kentucky Extension Centers in Fort Knox (1958), Cumberland (1960), and Henderson (1960) followed.\n\nIn 1959, the [[Patterson School of Diplomacy and International Commerce]] opened and began training professionals at the master's and doctoral level for careers in international affairs. The program was the vision of UK's first president [[James Kennedy Patterson]] who had identified the need for the United States to develop a cadre of professionals to advance its diplomatic and commercial interests around the globe. Patterson bequeathed his entire estate to establish this entity.\n\nAuthorized by the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] and signed by Governor [[Bert Combs]] on March 6, 1962, a mandate was placed upon the University of Kentucky to form a community college system.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> Two years later, the Board of Trustees implements the legislation and established the Community College System, creating centers in [[Gateway Community and Technical College|Covington]], [[Ashland Community and Technical College|Ashland]], [[Fort Knox]], [[Southeast Kentucky Community and Technical College|Cumberland]], [[Henderson Community College|Henderson]] and [[Elizabethtown Community and Technical College|Elizabethtown]]. In 1969, the [[Patterson Office Tower]] was completed, currently the tallest building on campus.\n\n[[File:UKMillerHall.jpg|thumb|Miller Hall]] In May 1970, students at the university began protesting the [[Kent State shootings|shootings at Kent State University]].<ref name=\"UKChron\"/><ref name=\"Nunncenter.org\">{{cite web|url=http://nunncenter.org/oralhistoryprojects/protests-at-uk/ |title=45th anniversary of Kent State protests at UK \u2013 Saving Stories |publisher=Nunncenter.org |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> In response, Governor [[Louie Nunn]] deferred to the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] in an attempt to disperse the protesters. An outdated [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps|ROTC]] building was destroyed by fire. The [[Louie B. Nunn Center for Oral History]] at the University of Kentucky Libraries has 13 oral history interviews with participants in the protests, university officials as well as former governor Nunn.<ref name=\"Nunncenter.org\" /> Nine years later, the Singletary Center for the Arts opened, named in honor of former university president Otis Singletary.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> In 1979, the University of Kentucky hosted the first Kentucky [[Women Writers Conference]], which is now the longest-running conference of its kind. The Kentucky Women Writers Conference is now in its 31st year.{{when|date=July 2014}}\n\n===Contemporary history===\n[[File:Engineering plaza.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The engineering plaza.]]\n\nIn 1997, the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] reorganized the community college system, withdrawing the university's jurisdiction from all but the Lexington Community College.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> The other colleges were merged with the [[Kentucky Community and Technical College System|Kentucky Technical College system]] and were placed under a separate board of control.\n\nOn April 3, 1998, work began on the [[William T. Young Library]], which was the largest university project at the time of completion.<ref name=\"HL_032298_d\">{{Cite news | last = Jester | first = Art | last2 = Stepp | first2 = Holly | title = Hub of the University | date = March 22, 1998 | newspaper = [[Lexington Herald-Leader]] | page = 2 | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> The six-level William T. Young Library was constructed on south campus and the largest book endowment among all public university libraries in the country.<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\"/> [[William T. Young]] got his fortune from selling his peanut butter company to [[Procter & Gamble]] in 1955. Nine years after the completion of the William T. Young Library, on April 13, 2007, an entire city block of neighborhood homes were demolished and ground was broken for the [[Biological Pharmaceutical Complex Building (University of Kentucky)|Biological Pharmaceutical Complex Building]], the largest academic building in the state of Kentucky, and one of the largest in the United States.<ref name=\"FutureofPharmacy\">{{cite web | title = Future of Pharmacy | date=April 13, 2007 | publisher=University of Kentucky [[Albert B. Chandler Hospital]] | url=http://www.mc.uky.edu/pharmacy/building.html | accessdate = April 5, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070207034824/http://www.mc.uky.edu/pharmacy/building.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = February 7, 2007}}</ref>\n[[File:Chemistry-Physics Building (U.K.).jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Chemistry-Physics Building]]\nThe Biological Pharmaceutical Complex Building complements the adjacent [[Biomedical Biological Science Research Building (University of Kentucky)|Biomedical Biological Science Research Building]], and is expected to be part of the new university research campus.<ref>{{cite web | title=Biomedical/Biological Sciences Research Building | publisher=University of Kentucky [[Albert B. Chandler Hospital]] | date=November 17, 2006 | url=http://ukcc.uky.edu/cgi-bin/dynamo?maps.391+campus+0509 | access-date=June 16, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017035029/http://ukcc.uky.edu/cgi-bin/dynamo?maps.391+campus+0509 | archive-date=October 17, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref> Other recent announcements include the construction of the new $450 million [[Albert B. Chandler Hospital]], which will was one of the largest projects in the state's history in terms of size and economic impact.<ref name=\"GB_053007\"/>\n\nIn 1997, the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] formed a compact with the university. The Top 20 Plan mandates that the University of Kentucky becomes a Top 20 public research university by 2020.<ref name=\"TOP20_why\">{{cite web|last=Todd|first=Lee|title=UK Reaching Top 20 Critical to Moving Kentucky Forward|publisher=University of Kentucky|date=February 28, 2007|url=http://www.uky.edu/OPBPA/whytop20.htm|access-date=February 28, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206051957/http://www.uky.edu/OPBPA/whytop20.htm|archive-date=February 6, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the compact, states with \"Top 20\" universities feature higher average household incomes, higher education attainments, healthier lives and more financial security.<ref name=\"TOP20_Presentation\">{{cite web |title=Top 20 Business Plan Presentation |publisher=University of Kentucky |year=2005 |accessdate=May 28, 2007 |url=http://www.uky.edu/OPBPA/Top20/Top20_sm.pdf |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205053622/http://www.uky.edu/OPBPA/Top20/Top20_sm.pdf |archive-date=February 5, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> As a result, fewer citizens live in poverty and as a result, fewer public dollars are spent on health care.<ref name=\"TOP20_why\"/> The plan would also spur technological advancements due to university-based research and increase the marketability of the state to investors.\n\n[[File:Main Bldg (UK).jpg|thumb|right|The [[Main Building (University of Kentucky)|Main Building]] in the foreground and the [[Patterson Office Tower]] in the background]]\n\nAs part of the \"Top 20\" plan, the university stated that it plans to,<ref name=\"TOP20_why\"/>\n# Increase enrollment by 7,000 students to 34,000;\n# Increase the state's highest graduation rate by 12% to 72%;\n# Increase the number of faculty by 625 to total 2,500;\n# Increase research expenditures by $470 million to total $768 million per year; and\n# Increase the university's role in Kentucky's \"schools, farms, businesses and communities.\"\n\nThe \"Top 20\" plan has produced some results,<ref name=\"TOP20_Presentation\"/>\n# Total enrollment increased from 24,061 in 1996 to 26,440 in 2004, an increase of 2,379.\n# The six-year graduation rate increased from 59.5 percent in 1998 to 61.2 percent in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=3442 |title=University of Kentucky News |publisher=news.uky.edu |date=April 25, 2008 |accessdate=December 29, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719031555/http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=3442 |archive-date=July 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n# Research expenditures increased from $124.8 million in 1996 to $297.6 million in 2003.<ref name=\"TOP20_Presentation\"/> It dipped slightly to $274 million for 2005.<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\"/> It is currently ranked 28th among public universities in sponsored research.<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\"/>\n# Endowment increased from $195.1 million in 1997 to $538.4 million in 2005.\n\nIn 2000, to help finance the \"Top 20\" plan, the university launched \"The Campaign for the University of Kentucky\", a $600 million [[fundraising]] effort that was used to \"enhance facilities, academic programs, public service, and scholarships.\"<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\"/> It passed that goal and the effort was raised to $1 billion. In March 2007, $1.022 billion was raised, months before the fundraising effort was set to end.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.uky.edu/ukymain/spots/spot-10106.html | title=Surpassing the Goal | publisher=University of Kentucky | year=2007 | access-date=June 19, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626092810/http://www.uky.edu/ukymain/spots/spot-10106.html | archive-date=June 26, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Statewide Facilities Condition Assessment Report'' released on April 4, 2007, the university needs $12.5 billion to complete the 1997 mandate to become a \"Top 20\" institution.<ref>{{cite news | last=Jester | first=Art | title=Report: Kentucky needs $12.5 billion for university facilities by 2020 | work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]] | date=April 7, 2007 | url=http://kentucky.com/181/story/33904.html | accessdate=April 3, 2007 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, The University of Kentucky has an endowment of 1.407 billion.<ref name=\"endowment\"/> Prior endowments were 831.8 in 2007,<ref name=\"HL_BillionDollar\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kentucky.com/211/story/54436.html|title=UK reaches billion-dollar milestone in fund-raising|last=Jester|first=Art|date=April 27, 2007|work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|accessdate=May 2, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20070801070333/http://www.kentucky.com/211/story/54436.html|archive-date=August 1, 2007}}</ref> $538.4 million in 2005, and $195.1 million in 1997, the rapid increases partially attributed to the \"Top 20\" Plan.<ref name=\"TOP20_Presentation\"/> Currently, the William T. Young Library book endowment is the largest among public universities in the United States.<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\" />\n\nIn 2018, the new Gatton Student Center was opened on North Campus. The $200 million, 378,000-square-foot facility contains a cinema, a dining facility, several chain restaurants, ballrooms, the UK Bookstore, the renovated UK Federal Credit Union, offices, and more. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uknow.uky.edu/campus-news/uk-opens-gatton-student-center|title=UK Celebrates New Gatton Student Center|date=2018-08-30|website=UKNow|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Departments===\n\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| ARWU_W   = 301\u2013400\n| ARWU_N   = 95\u2013116\n| THE_WSJ  = 323\n| USNWR_NU = 132\n| USNWR_W  = 349\n| QS_W     = 601\u2013650\n| THES_W   = 401\u2013500\n| Wamo_NU  = 192\n| Forbes   = 308\n}}\n\nStudents are divided into 16 colleges, a [[graduate school]], 93 [[undergraduate]] programs, 99 [[master's degrees|master programs]], 66 [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctoral]] programs, and four professional programs.<ref name=\"UKS_06\"/>{{Update inline|reason=Stale cite may be suppressing current actual numbers.|date=February 2017}} The University of Kentucky has fifteen libraries on campus. The largest is William T. Young Library, a [[Federal depository library|federal depository]], hosting subjects related to [[social sciences]], [[humanities]] and [[life sciences]] collections. In recent years, the university has focused expenditures increasingly on research, following a compact formed by the [[Kentucky General Assembly]] in 1997. The directive mandated that the university become a ''Top 20'' public research institution, in terms of an overall ranking to be determined by the university itself, by the year 2020.<ref name=\"TOP20_why\"/> The university is ranked tied for 132nd in National Universities and tied for 60th among [[Public university|public universities]] in the 2020 ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' rankings.<ref>{{cite web |title=University of Kentucky |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-kentucky-1989/overall-rankings |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |year=2020 |access-date=September 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221112312/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-kentucky-1989/overall-rankings |archive-date=February 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStudents are divided into several colleges based on their interests and specializations:\n\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Agriculture, Food, and Environment|College of Agriculture, Food and Environment]], founded 1908\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Arts and Sciences|College of Arts and Sciences]], founded 1908\n* [[Gatton College of Business and Economics]], founded 1925 (originally as the College of Commerce)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Communication & Information|College of Communication & Information]], founded 1976\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Dentistry|College of Dentistry]], founded 1962\n[[File:Biological-Pharmaceutical Building U.K.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[Biological Pharmaceutical Complex Building (University of Kentucky)|Biological-Pharmaceutical Building]] is home to the College of Pharmacy]]\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Design|College of Design]], founded 1964 (originally the College of Architecture)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Education|College of Education]], founded 1923\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Engineering|College of Engineering]], founded 1918 (through a merger of the original Colleges of Civil Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, and Mines and Metals)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Fine Arts|College of Fine Arts]], founded 1976\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Health Sciences|College of Health Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uky.edu/chs/ |title=UK College of Health Sciences |publisher=uky.edu |accessdate=January 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202082151/https://www.uky.edu/chs/ |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> founded 1966 (originally as the College of Allied Health Personnel)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Law|College of Law]], founded 1908\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Medicine|College of Medicine]], founded 1954\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Nursing|College of Nursing]], founded 1956\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Pharmacy|College of Pharmacy]], founded 1947 (originally established in 1870 in Louisville)\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Public Health|College of Public Health]], founded 2004\n* [[University of Kentucky College of Social Work|College of Social Work]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://socialwork.uky.edu/ |title=UK College of Social Work |publisher=uky.edu |accessdate=January 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110053242/https://socialwork.uky.edu/ |archive-date=November 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> founded 1968\n* [[University of Kentucky Graduate School]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gradschool.uky.edu |title=UK Graduate School |publisher=Gradschool.uky.edu |date=January 4, 2013 |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213070825/http://www.gradschool.uky.edu/ |archive-date=February 13, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> founded 1912\n* [[Martin School|Martin School of Public Policy and Administration]]\n* [[Patterson School of Diplomacy and International Commerce]]\n\nOther colleges no longer in existence at the University of Kentucky include the College of Library Science (separating out of the College of Arts & Sciences in 1968 and incorporated in 2003 into what is now the College of Communication and Information) and the College of Home Economics (created in 1916 and whose founding dean was [[Mary E. Sweeney]]) now a School of Human Environmental Sciences located within the College of Agriculture.<ref>{{cite web | title = Statutory Definition, Governing Regulations, Part I | publisher = University of Kentucky | location = Lexington KY | date = June 11, 2013 | url = http://www.uky.edu/regs/files/gr/gr1.pdf | accessdate = August 1, 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120314041752/http://www.uky.edu/regs/files/gr/gr1.pdf | archive-date = March 14, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n===Lewis Honors College===\nThe Honors Program at the University of Kentucky began in 1961. It offers interdisciplinary, seminar-style classes of 15\u201320 students each as well as \"H-section\" classes that accelerate common course offerings such as chemistry, biology, and physics. The program is intended to supplement the individual interests of the students. Students are offered priority registration, one-on-one faculty attention, dedicated advising, the opportunity to engage in undergraduate research from their first semesters on campus, and are directed to other programs, including the Chellgren Fellows program, the Gaines Fellowship in the Humanities, the University Scholars Program (which allows simultaneous undergraduate and graduate study), and external scholarship opportunities. Additionally, students are offered assistance with fellowship applications, scholarship applications, study abroad opportunities, Honors designation on transcript and diploma,<ref>{{cite web|title=Honors Program|url=http://www.uky.edu/academy/about-honors|website=University of Kentucky|accessdate=April 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328230225/http://www.uky.edu/academy/about-honors|archive-date=March 28, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and/or service learning interests, among other things.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uky.edu/Honors/prospective/prospective.html |title=UK &#124; Honors &#124; Prospective Students |publisher=Uky.edu |date=October 30, 2012 |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130204193039/http://www.uky.edu/Honors/prospective/prospective.html |archive-date=February 4, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2017, the Honors Program became the Lewis Honors College. It is now Lewis Hall.<ref>{{cite web | last = Wells | first = Jenny | title = Board Approves Creation of the UK Lewis Honors College | publisher = University of Kentucky | date = May 3, 2016 | url = https://uknow.uky.edu/content/board-approves-creation-uk-lewis-honors-college | accessdate = May 5, 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160713214417/http://uknow.uky.edu/content/board-approves-creation-uk-lewis-honors-college | archive-date = July 13, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n===SECU: SEC Academic Initiative===\n\nThe University of Kentucky is a member of the SEC Academic Consortium. Now renamed the [[Southeastern Conference#The formation of SECU and SEC academic network|SECU]], the initiative was a collaborative endeavor designed to promote research, scholarship and achievement among the member universities in the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC). The SECU formed its mission to serve as a means to bolster collaborative academic endeavors of [[Southeastern Conference#Member universities|SEC universities]]. Its goals include highlighting the endeavors and achievements of SEC [[Faculty (academic staff)|faculty]], students and its universities and advancing the academic reputation of SEC universities.<ref>{{cite web|title=SECU 10-Year Anniversary Comments from Greg Sankey|url=https://www.thesecu.com/news/secu-10-year-anniversary-comments-from-greg-sankey/|publisher=SEC|accessdate=February 13, 2013|date=August 20, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515234932/https://www.thesecu.com/news/secu-10-year-anniversary-comments-from-greg-sankey/|archivedate=May 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SECU: The Academic Initiative of the SEC |url=http://www.secdigitalnetwork.com/AcademicConsortium |publisher=SEC Digital Network |accessdate=February 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721055557/http://www.secdigitalnetwork.com/AcademicConsortium |archivedate=July 21, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n{{Main|University of Kentucky student life}}\n\n===Students===\nThe University of Kentucky strives for a diverse and international student population, with a selective admissions process.\n\nIn fall 2014, there were 30,000 students enrolled for the first time. This is due in part by the high number of out-of-state students. The percentage mix of students at this time were 62% in state and 38% out-of-state. During this time, the freshman class was recorded at 5,000 students.<ref>{{cite news|title=Enrollment at University of Kentucky Tops 30,000|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/local/education/article44508666.html|work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|accessdate=April 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420104846/http://www.kentucky.com/news/local/education/article44508666.html|archive-date=April 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Student government===\n\nThe University of Kentucky Student Government Association (UKSGA) represents all undergraduate, graduate and professional students enrolled at the university in several critical ways. UKSGA exists to increase student influence over academic policy and to provide many helpful, creative and necessary student services. UKSGA also exists to protect and expand student substantive and procedural rights with the university and surrounding municipalities. Finally, UKSGA exists to better represent the student body in relations with faculty, administration, Board of Trustees and the Commonwealth of Kentucky.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org |title=University of Kentucky Student Government &#124; The UKSGA homepage |publisher=Uksga.org |date=February 5, 2012 |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105133719/http://uksga.org/ |archive-date=November 5, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nUKSGA includes an Executive, Legislative, and Judicial Branch.\n\n*Executive Branch: oversees day-to-day operations, manages budget, and facilitates major programs.\n*Legislative Branch: includes the Student Senate. There are 46 legislators in this branch. Their goal is to allocate funds, approve presidential appointments, facilitate legislative changes, and represent the larger student voice.\n*Judicial: composed of one Chief Justice and six Supreme Court Justices. The Supreme Court rules on the constitutionality of legislation, handles claims levied against SGA officials, hears any election rules violation complaints and validates election results.<ref>{{cite web|title=UKSGA|url=http://uksga.org/about|website=Student Government Association|accessdate=April 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503151307/http://uksga.org/about|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSeveral of their current programs include:\n\n*Kentucky Wildcab: a late night transportation service designed to enhance the safety efforts of the university and surrounding community in partnership with UK Transportation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uksga.org/services/|title=University of Kentucky Student Government Services|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Uksga.org|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010130829/http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/cats-cruiser|archive-date=October 10, 2012|accessdate=9 April 2020|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*Wildcat Wardrobe: provides UK students with free professional dress clothing for interviews and jobs <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uksga.org/services/|title=UKSGA: Services|website=uksga.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n*Safe CATS: provides UK students with a safer way to travel around campus by having SafeCats team members escort students to their destinations on-foot or by golf cart<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/safecats |title=SafeCats &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government |publisher=Uksga.org |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010122352/http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/safecats |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*Student Legal Services: free on-site consultation for any legal issue by a local attorney<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/student-legal-service |title=Student Legal Service &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government |publisher=Uksga.org |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010123825/http://uksga.org/programs-and-services/student-legal-service |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Childcare]] Grants: available for part-time and full-time UK students, both at the undergraduate and graduate level, who need financial assistance for day-care service for their children.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org/applications/childcare-grants |title=Childcare Grants &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government |publisher=Uksga.org |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010121545/http://uksga.org/applications/childcare-grants |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*Scholarships<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uksga.org/applications/scholarships-awards |title=Scholarships & Awards &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government |publisher=Uksga.org |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010131847/http://uksga.org/applications/scholarships-awards |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*Student Organization Funding: General Funding Grants, Club Sports Grants, Service Grants, Academic/Professional Conferences, and Senate Special Projects<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uksga.org/funding|title=Funding &#124; University of Kentucky Student Government|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Uksga.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010130639/http://uksga.org/funding|archive-date=21 Feb 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral distinguished Student Body Presidents include Governor [[Steve Beshear]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://governor.ky.gov/about/Pages/default.aspx |title=About Meet the Governor |publisher=Governor.ky.gov |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111221706/http://governor.ky.gov/about/Pages/default.aspx |archive-date=January 11, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Student media===\n\nThe Electrical and Computer Engineering Department was the home of one of the earliest college amateur [[radio station]]s in the United States, beginning with [[W4JP]] that began continuous operation prior to [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211030614/http://www.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/UKARC/history/early/intro.html | archivedate=February 11, 2009| title=The Early Years: A Pictorial History | publisher=University of Kentucky Amateur Radio Club | accessdate=July 24, 2012| url=http://www.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/UKARC/history/early/intro.html}}</ref> In 1927, the station was relicensed as 9JL (later W9JL).<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211030619/http://www.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/UKARC/history/w9jl/intro.html| archivedate=February 11, 2009| title=The Middle Years: A Pictorial History | publisher=University of Kentucky Amateur Radio Club | accessdate=July 24, 2012| url=http://www.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/UKARC/history/w9jl/intro.html}}</ref>\n\nStudents currently run two independent [[Frequency Modulation|FM]] stations. The first, 91.3 FM [[WUKY]], is a [[Adult Album Alternative|Triple-A]] station and was the first university-owned FM radio station in the United States and Kentucky's first public radio station.<ref name=\"WUKY_About\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wuky.org/history | title=History | publisher=WUKY | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426122057/http://www.wuky.org/history | archive-date=April 26, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> The operations started on October 17, 1940 as [[WBKY]] out of [[Beattyville, Kentucky|Beattyville]], although the station moved five years later to Lexington.<ref name=\"WUKY_About\"/>\n\nIn 1971, WBKY was one of the first to carry NPR's \"All Things Considered\" and helped debut [[National Public Radio]], changing its call letters to WUKY in 1989 to better reflect its affiliation with the university. In 2007, it became the first Lexington radio station to broadcast in high-definition digital radio.<ref name=\"WUKY_About\"/> The second is 88.1 FM [[WRFL]] which has been in operation since 1988.<ref name=\"WRFL_About\">{{cite news | title = About | publisher = [[WRFL]] | url = http://wrfl881.org/about.html | accessdate = May 8, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313194831/http://www.wrfl881.org/about.html| archivedate=March 13, 2007 }}</ref> WRFL is operated by students and broadcasts live 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, and features music that is spread across most genres.\n\nThe campus is also served by the [[The Kentucky Kernel|Kentucky Kernel]], a student-run, financially independent daily newspaper, with the first issue published in 1915.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/markers/KYKernel1.html | title=Kentucky Kernel Historical Marker | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626195019/http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/markers/KYKernel1.html | archive-date=June 26, 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt72jm23bv99_1/viewer? | title=The Kentucky Kernel, First Issue | date=September 16, 1915 | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731175436/http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt72jm23bv99_1/viewer | archive-date=July 31, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> The official [[yearbook]] of the University of Kentucky is the ''Kentuckian'', first published in 1906.<ref name=\"UKChron\" /> The ''Kentuckian'' was preceded by at least one previous book, the ''Echo''.\n\n===Greek life===\n\nNineteen [[fraternities and sororities|sororities]] and twenty-three [[fraternities and sororities|fraternities]] serve the university, representing over 3,000 students with a budget of $3.2 million per year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greek Welcome|publisher=University of Kentucky|date=September 21, 2006|accessdate=January 11, 2008|url=http://www.uky.edu/StudentAffairs/Greek|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114190836/http://www.uky.edu/StudentAffairs/Greek/|archive-date=January 14, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The governing bodies include the [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]], an organization for nine historically black organizations, international Greek assemblies, the [[National Panhellenic Conference]] for sororities and the [[North-American Interfraternity Conference|Interfraternity Council]] for the fraternities.<ref>{{cite web|title=UK Interfraternity Council|year=2008|accessdate=January 11, 2008|url=http://www.kentuckyifc.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213021749/http://www.kentuckyifc.com/|archive-date=December 13, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThere are many non-Greek organizations on campus, like [[Alpha Kappa Psi]], an internationally recognized Professional Business Fraternity and [[Tau Beta Sigma]], a band fraternity. The university also hosts a chapter of the [[Alpha Phi Omega]] [[co-educational]] [[service fraternity]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|Fraternities\n!colspan=2|Sororities\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n*[[Alpha Gamma Rho]]\n*[[Alpha Kappa Psi]]\n*[[Alpha Phi Alpha]]\n*[[Alpha Sigma Phi]]\n*[[Beta Theta Pi]]\n*[[Beta Upsilon Chi]]\n*[[Chi Psi]]\n*[[Delta Sigma Phi]]\n*[[Delta Tau Delta]]\n*[[Delta Upsilon]]\n\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n*[[FarmHouse]]\n*[[Iota Phi Theta]]\n*[[Kappa Alpha Order]]\n*[[Kappa Alpha Psi]]\n*[[Kappa Sigma]]\n*[[Omega Psi Phi]]\n*[[Pershing Rifles]]\n*[[Phi Beta Sigma]]\n*[[Phi Delta Theta]]\n*[[Phi Gamma Delta]]\n\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n\n*[[Phi Kappa Tau]]\n*[[Phi Sigma Kappa]]\n*[[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]]\n*[[Sigma Lambda Beta]]\n*[[Sigma Nu]]\n*[[Sigma Pi]]\n*[[Sigma Phi Epsilon]] \n*[[Tau Kappa Epsilon]]\n*[[Theta Chi]]\n*[[Triangle Fraternity]]\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n*[[Alpha Chi Omega]]\n*[[Alpha Delta Pi]]\n*[[Alpha Gamma Delta]]\n*[[Alpha Kappa Alpha]]\n*[[Alpha Omicron Pi]]\n*[[Alpha Phi]]\n*[[Ceres (Women's Agricultural Fraternity)|Ceres]]\n*[[Chi Omega]]\n*[[Delta Delta Delta]]\n*[[Delta Gamma]]\n*[[Delta Sigma Theta]]\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; font-size:smaller;\"|\n*[[Delta Zeta]]\n*[[Gamma Phi Beta]]\n*[[Kappa Alpha Theta]]\n*[[Kappa Delta]]\n*[[Kappa Kappa Gamma]]\n*[[Phi Mu]]\n*[[Phi Sigma Rho]]\n*[[Pi Beta Phi]]\n*[[Sigma Gamma Rho]]\n*[[Sigma Lambda Gamma]]\n*[[Theta Nu Xi]]\n*[[Zeta Phi Beta]]\n|}\n\n===Athletics===\n\n[[File:rupparenaK.JPG|thumb|The Kentucky cheerleaders at [[Rupp Arena]] performing the traditional \"Big K\" cheer during a basketball game. Seating Capacity of Rupp Arena is 23,500.]]\n{{Main|Kentucky Wildcats}}\n{{See also|Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky Wildcats football|University of Kentucky cheerleading squad|Kentucky Wildcats women's basketball|Kentucky Wildcats men's soccer|Kentucky Wildcats softball}}\n\nUniversity of Kentucky student-athletes compete as the Wildcats under colors Kentucky blue and white.\n\nBeginning in the 1890s, students at the A&M scheduled [[american football|football]] games with neighboring colleges.<ref name=\"UK_HIS3\">{{cite web | title=History Briefs | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=May 23, 2007 | url=http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/history3.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021119074028/http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/history3.html| archivedate=November 19, 2002}}</ref> In 1902, the [[Kentucky Wildcats women's basketball|women's basketball]] program began on campus,<ref name=\"UK_HIS3\"/> and the [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|men's team]] was added one year later. The \"[[Wildcat]]s\" became associated with the university shortly after a [[American football|football]] victory over [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]] on October 9, 1909.<ref name=\"UK TRAD\"/> The then-chief of the military department, Commandant Carbuiser, stated that the team had \"fought like wildcats.\" The slogan was later adopted by the university, and a costumed mascot debuted in 1976.<ref name=\"UK TRAD\"/>\n\nIn 1930, then-[[high school]] coach [[Adolph Rupp]] was hired as a basketball coach for the university. He had a career that would span 42 years until 1972.<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> During his tenure, he led the [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|men's basketball team]] to four [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] championships in 1948, 1949, 1951 and 1958.<ref name=\"UK_HIS3\"/> The Wildcats later won a fifth championship under [[Joe B. Hall]] in 1978, another in 1996 under [[Rick Pitino]] and the next under [[Tubby Smith|Orlando \"Tubby\" Smith]] in 1998.<ref name=\"UK_HIS3\"/> In 2007, the University of Kentucky named [[Billy Gillispie]] as the head coach of the men's basketball team and on March 30, 2009, the university named [[John Calipari]] as the head coach of the Wildcats. Calipari coached the team to its eighth national title in 2012.\n\nOn December 21, 2009, the men's basketball team reached another milestone, becoming the first college basketball team to reach 2000 all-time wins. The 2000th win was an 88\u201344 victory over the [[2009\u201310 Drexel Dragons men's basketball team|Drexel Dragons]]. Kentucky was also the first school to reach the 1000 all-time wins, which they accomplished in 1969.\n\nThe university boasts of numerous national championships, with its latest coming in 2012 when the men's basketball team won its eighth national title. UK also boasts of a [[cross country running|cross country]] national team championship (women's, 1988), eight individual championships in [[artistic gymnastics|gymnastics]], an [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympic]] medalist in [[track and field]], and 21 national championships in [[cheerleading]].<ref name=\"UK_FACTS\">{{cite web | title=Stats-at-a-glance | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=May 23, 2007 | url=http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/facts.html. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629200653/http://www.uky.edu/Home/AboutUK/facts.html| archivedate=June 29, 2007 }}</ref> After defeating number-one ranked Oklahoma 13\u20137 in the Sugar Bowl under legendary coach Bear Bryant, Kentucky is also an NCAA-recognized co-national champion for the 1950 season.\n\n[[File:KentuckyCommonwealthStadium-EZInterior.jpg|thumb|left|275px|Pregame of 2005 Kentucky vs. Auburn game.]]\n\nThe University of Kentucky Dance team is currently ranked 5th in the nation in [[Hip Hop]] and 7th in [[Pom-pom|Pom]] at Universal Dance Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/page/spirit-dance|title=Dance Team - UK Wildcats|publisher=|accessdate=December 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129025941/http://ukathletics.com/page/spirit-dance|archive-date=November 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOther athletic programs sponsored at the varsity level include [[baseball]], men's and women's [[basketball]], men's and women's [[cross country running]], [[American football|football]], men's and women's [[golf]], women's [[artistic gymnastics|gymnastics]], the coeducational sport of [[shooting sports|rifle]], men's and women's [[Association football|soccer]], women's [[softball]], men's and women's [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]] and [[Diving (sport)|diving]], men's and women's [[tennis]], men's and women's [[track and field]] and women's [[volleyball]].<ref>{{cite web | title=ukatlhetics.com | publisher=University of Kentucky | year=2008 | accessdate=January 3, 2008 | url=http://www.ukathletics.com/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224000436/http://www.ukathletics.com/ | archive-date=February 24, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref> The school also has a popular club-level men's [[ice hockey]] team and a rugby program that competes at the Division 1 level.\n\nThe University of Kentucky football coach is [[Mark Stoops]], named the successor to [[Joker Phillips]], who was the first African American football coach in Kentucky's history.\n\nNotable among a number of songs commonly played and sung at various events such as [[Graduation|commencement]], [[convocation]] and athletic games is the University of Kentucky [[fight song]]: ''[[On, On, U of K]]''.<ref name=songs>{{cite web | url=http://ukbands.org/schoolsongs.html | title=School Songs | publisher=University of Kentucky Bands | accessdate=July 24, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116220612/http://ukbands.org/schoolsongs.html | archive-date=January 16, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, the song ''Kentucky Fight''<ref name=songs /> is played before games.\n\n==Campus==\n\n[[File:WilliamtyounglibraryUK.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Completed in 1998, the William T. Young Library serves both the university campus and the Commonwealth of Kentucky]]\n\n{{Main|List of University of Kentucky buildings}}\n\nThe University of Kentucky offers seven main dining facilities, 23 residence halls, and numerous recreation facilities spread between three distinct campuses: north, south, and central. It is also home to more than 250 student-run organizations.\n\nThe university campus is home to numerous notable structures, such as [[Main Building (University of Kentucky)|Main Building]], a four-story administration building dating to 1882,<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> which was gutted by fire on May 15, 2001. The cause of the blaze was attributed to a welders torch during repairs to the building's roof. Total costs for reconstruction after the fire exceeded $17 million. The [[Patterson Office Tower]] is the tallest building on campus. The university is also home to several major construction projects, including the [[Albert B. Chandler Hospital]] expansion. As of 2016, construction projects include Student Center renovation and expansion, and Alumni Gym.\n\nThe University of Kentucky once operated 14 [[community college]]s with more than 100 extended sites, centers and campuses under the [[University of Kentucky's Community College System|Kentucky Community and Technical College System]], but relinquished control under the [[Education in Kentucky#Postsecondary Education Improvement Act of 1997|Postsecondary Education Improvement Act of 1997]].<ref name=\"DI_070103\">{{cite news | last=Gilmore | first=Amanda | title=Merger of ACC, ATC completed | work=[[The Daily Independent (Ashland newspaper)|The Daily Independent]] | date=July 1, 2003 | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | url=http://commentsengine.cnhi.zope.net/archives/dailyindependent/story_detail?story_id=7782 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The network of community colleges is now known as the [[Kentucky Community and Technical College System]] (KCTCS). Adjoining Lexington Community College, despite the reorganization of the community colleges, remained integrated with the university, but separated from the University of Kentucky in 2004 and became a part of KCTCS; it is now known as [[Bluegrass Community and Technical College]].\n\nThe College of Engineering currently operates a satellite campus in [[Paducah, Kentucky|Paducah]], located on the campus of [[West Kentucky Community and Technical College]].<ref name=\"WKCTCS\">{{cite web | title=A Rich Heritage: A Historic Timeline | publisher=[[West Kentucky Community and Technical College]] | year=2007 | accessdate=January 7, 2007 | url=http://www.westkentucky.kctcs.edu/aboutus/wkctcdhist.shtml |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060909220212/http://www.westkentucky.kctcs.edu/aboutus/wkctcdhist.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 9, 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Funkhouser building.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Funkhouser Building]]\n\n===Campus libraries===\n\nThe University of Kentucky is home to nine campus libraries.<ref>{{cite web | title=University of Kentucky Libraries | publisher=University of Kentucky | date=2015 | accessdate=May 11, 2018 | url=http://libraries.uky.edu/CampusLibraries | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512044454/http://libraries.uky.edu/CampusLibraries | archive-date=May 12, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> Among them is the William T. Young Library, which houses a general undergraduate collection and social sciences, humanities, business, biology, and agricultural materials. The library is also a [[Federal Depository Library]] and a [[public library]] for the [[Commonwealth of Kentucky]]. Libraries include:\n\n* Agricultural Information Center\n* Design Library\n* Education Library\n* Law Library\n* Lucille Caudill Little Fine Arts Library and Learning Center\n* Medical Center Library\n* Science & Engineering Library\n* Special Collections Research Center\n* William T. Young Library\n\n[[File:Atrium of Don and Cathy Jacobs Science Building.jpg|thumb|Interior of new science building]]\n\n[[File:University of Kentucky Arboretum - DSC09377.JPG|thumb|right|250px|UK Arboretum]]\n\n===Campus landmarks===\n\nThe University of Kentucky has several noteworthy landmarks:\n\n*[[Kroger Field]]\n* [[Memorial Coliseum (Lexington)|Memorial Coliseum]]\n* [[Memorial Hall, University of Kentucky|Memorial Hall]]\n* [[Singletary Center for the Arts]]\n* [[University of Kentucky Art Museum]]\n* [[University of Kentucky/Lexington-Fayette Urban County Government Arboretum]]\n* [[University of Kentucky Research and Education Center Botanical Garden]]\n* Wildcat Alumni Plaza\n* [[William T. Young Library]]\n\n==Notable faculty==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2019}}\n\n*[[Arthur G. Hunt]], American plant and soils scientist\n*[[Ronald Werner-Wilson]] (born 1972), Chair of the Family Studies Department and Kathryn Louise Chellgren Endowed Professor for Research in Family Studies\n*[[Kimberly W. Anderson]], Chemist, Gill Eminent Professor of Chemical Engineering and Associate Dean for Administration and Academic Affairs in the College of Engineering\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n{{Main|List of University of Kentucky alumni}}\n\nThe university has over 140,246 alumni in the state of Kentucky,<ref>{{cite web | title=Alumni throughout the Bluegrass State | publisher=University of Kentucky Alumni Association | date=January 2007 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | url=http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/statewebmap.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123065959/http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/statewebmap.htm | archive-date=January 23, 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref> 216,737 in the United States,<ref>{{cite web | title=Alumni across the nation | publisher=University of Kentucky Alumni Association | date=January 2007 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | url=http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/framemap.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123065922/http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/framemap.htm | archive-date=January 23, 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref> and 1,119 internationally.<ref>{{cite web | title=Alumni around the world | publisher=University of Kentucky Alumni Association | date=January 2007 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | url=http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/worldmap.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123070004/http://www.ukalumni.net/Maps/worldmap.htm | archive-date=January 23, 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref> The University of Kentucky Alumni Association is the primary affiliation for former students and faculty, and is located at the corner of Rose Street and Euclid Avenue. The building, dedicated in 1963, is named for Helen G. King, the first permanent director of the association and was former \"Miss University of Kentucky\". The association also meets at [[Spindletop Hall]], a large mansion along Iron Works Pike, which serves as a central alumni gathering point.<ref>{{cite news | title=Mission & History | year=2007 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | publisher=University of Kentucky Alumni Association | url=http://www.ukalumni.net/pages.php?page_id=6 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515165033/http://www.ukalumni.net/pages.php?page_id=6 | archive-date=May 15, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe University of Kentucky boasts seven governors, including former [[Governor of Kentucky]] [[Steve Beshear]], former [[Governor of Ohio]] [[Ted Strickland]], former [[Governor of North Carolina]] [[Beverly Perdue]], and former governors [[Ernie Fletcher]], [[Paul E. Patton]] and Arkansas' [[Tom Jefferson Terral]], and former governor, [[U.S. Senator]] and Commissioner of [[Major League Baseball]] [[Happy Chandler|Albert \"Happy\" Chandler]]. It also claims [[Ken Lucas]], a former [[U.S. representative]] from the commonwealth's fourth [[congressional district]], United Methodist Bishop [[Alfred W. Gwinn]], current [[U.S. Senator]] [[Mitch McConnell]], [[Bill Gatton|Carol Gatton]], an automobile dealer executive and donor of the largest gift ever to the university, and Paul Chellgren, [[Chairman]] and [[CEO]] of [[Ashland Inc.]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Twenty to be inducted into UK Hall of Distinguished Alumni | last=Scharfenberger | first=John | date=April 10, 2000 | accessdate=January 11, 2008 | publisher=University of Kentucky | url=http://www.uky.edu/PR/News/Archives/2000/April2000/distalumni.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013124528/http://www.uky.edu/PR/News/Archives/2000/April2000/distalumni.htm | archive-date=October 13, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> The university was also the home of Dr. [[Thomas Hunt Morgan]], a scientist and winner of the 1933 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]], and [[William Lipscomb]], 1976 winner of the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]].<ref name=\"UKChron\"/> The university claims actors such as [[Miss Elizabeth]] and  [[Ashley Judd]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/politics-government/article44418894.html|title=Ashley Judd bought a house in Kentucky in March|work=kentucky|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201233111/http://www.kentucky.com/news/politics-government/article44418894.html|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:Thomas_Hunt_Morgan.jpg|[[Thomas Hunt Morgan]], recipient of the [[Nobel Prize]] in Physiology or Medicine, and father of modern [[genetics]]\nFile:Mitch McConnell official photo.jpg|[[Mitch McConnell]], [[U.S. Senator]], current [[Senate Majority Leader]]\nFile:Ashley Judd head.jpg|[[Ashley Judd]], actress\nFile:William n lipscomb jr.jpg|[[William Lipscomb]], 1976 winner of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of forestry universities and colleges]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Collier's Poster|Kentucky, University of|the University of Kentucky}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.ukathletics.com University of Kentucky Athletics website]\n*[http://exploreuk.uky.edu/catalog/xt7n8p5v980r/guide Digitized images of the University of Kentucky from the Glass plate negative collection, 1898\u20131918] housed at the University of Kentucky Libraries Special Collections Research Center\n\n{{University of Kentucky}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|Kentucky Wildcats|color=white}}\n|list =\n{{Kentucky Higher Education}}\n{{Southeastern Conference navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Universities Research Association}}\n{{Lexington (Kentucky)}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kentucky, University Of}}\n[[Category:University of Kentucky| ]]\n[[Category:Land-grant universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1865]]\n[[Category:Flagship universities in the United States]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Lexington, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Distance education institutions based in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Naraht", "label": "safe", "comment": "